<DOCOLDNO>IA079-000543-B012-28</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.aascpa.com:80/overview.htm 199.78.60.91 19970124171818 text/html 4995
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 24 Jan 1997 17:19:15 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 4824
Last-modified: Fri, 20 Dec 1996 11:51:35 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.01Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#000040" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#408080" ALINK="#FF0000">

<TABLE WIDTH="80%" >
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="25%" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG SRC="ashlog1.gif" HEIGHT=59 WIDTH=179>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><B><FONT COLOR="#8F982C">SERVICES<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+0>-AIMR-<BR>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=-1>OVERVIEW</FONT></FONT></B></H1>

<LI><B><FONT COLOR="#408080"><A HREF="services.htm">services</A></FONT></B></LI>

<LI><B><FONT COLOR="#408080"><A HREF="advantages.htm">advantages</A></FONT></B></LI>

<LI><B><FONT COLOR="#408080"><A HREF="quickstart.htm">quick start</A></FONT></B></LI>

<LI><B><FONT COLOR="#408080"><A HREF="reports.htm">sample reports</A></FONT></B></LI>

<LI><B><FONT COLOR="#408080"><A HREF="index.htm">home</A></FONT></B></LI>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH="1%"></TD>

<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="70%">
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><B><FONT COLOR="#8F982C"><FONT SIZE=+2>&quot;Overview&quot;</FONT></FONT></B></H3>

<CENTER><P>
<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH="100%"></P></CENTER>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">Investment manager searches are increasingly requiring
money managers to not only be in compliance with the AIMR PPS, but also
to be verified. </FONT></P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#8F982C">This is why... Quality of information.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">The AIMR Performance Presentation Standards were
designed to promote full and fair disclosure of investment managers' performance
results, increase the comparability of evaluating investment managers,
and decrease managers' ability to present only their best performing accounts
and/or time periods.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">In order to claim compliance with the Standards,
adopted on January 1, 1993, investment managers must do two things: </FONT></P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">1) calculate performance according to an acceptable
methodology </FONT></P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">2) disclose all relevant information on the investment
style(s) being presented.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">When the Performance Presentation Standards were
written, they proposed two possible levels of verification, Level 1 and
Level 2: </FONT></P>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#8F982C"><FONT SIZE=+0>Level 1 Verification
</FONT></FONT></H3>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">A Level 1 verification simply ensures that the
manager has included all appropriate accounts for all time periods. This
process audits the performance of the composite and the make-up of each
composite. Each account the firm manages is tracked from period to period
and any account that &quot;disappears&quot; from the manager's records
must be documentable. Accounts are also checked to ensure they are actual
accounts under management, not simulated. Once this process is complete,
the firm verifying the manager's data must then be sure the manager has
all mandatory disclosures in place and is representing these disclosures
accurately. </FONT></P>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#8F982C"><FONT SIZE=+0>Level 2 Verification
</FONT></FONT></H3>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">A Level II verification includes a Level I verification
and is a detailed audit of the portfolio returns that make up the composite
returns. This level of verification checks security pricing, holdings,
income and performance. </FONT></P>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#8F982C"><FONT SIZE=+0>Which Level of Verification
Is Most Appropriate? </FONT></FONT></H3>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">The verification process adds its greatest value
at Level I. Our firm requires all strategies currently presented or actively
marketed by a client to undergo a Level I verification. At this level,
we can assist our clients in defining the composites, deciding which accounts
to include or exclude, and providing necessary disclosure information.
</FONT></P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">Level II verifications turn up very few errors.
The fact is, custodial banks, consultants and many other parties already
&quot;verify&quot; cash flows, portfolio returns, and security pricing.
Ashland Accounting does not engage in Modified Level II verifications because
we believe they undermine the original intent of the AIMR Performance Presentation
Standards. </FONT></P>

<P>
<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#8F982C"><FONT SIZE=-2>Copyright &copy; 1996 Ashland
Accounting Services, P.C.<BR>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="mailto:info@aascpa.com">info@aascpa.com</A></FONT></FONT></P></CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="25%"></TD>

<TD></TD>

<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
