<DOCHDR>
http://www.miserybay.com:80/faq.htm 199.166.223.215 19970211083516 text/html 16747
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Tue, 11 Feb 1997 08:34:04 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
Last-Modified: Sun, 05 Jan 1997 20:08:23 GMT
Content-Length: 16546
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Frequently Asked Questions</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bk36.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H1 ALIGN="center"><IMG BORDER="0" SRC="letter.gif" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"><FONT SIZE="+7">Greetings! </FONT></H1>
<H3><B>We get several questions a day. We spend countless hours via e-mail trying to answer these questions. Hopefully this will help you.</B></H3>
<P> <BR>
<I><B>Now comes the disclaimer: </B></I><B> These answers will tend to be opinions. PLEASE if you know it all, don't e-mail with corrections. We are just trying to help get rid of the smoke and mirrors of the Internet. People are tired of pompous answers  from KNOW-IT-ALLs. <INS> </INS>If the Internet tends to overwhelm you then feel safe in the Harbor of Misery Bay.</B></P>
<P ALIGN="center"><IMG BORDER="0" SRC="redbuttd.gif"></P>
<FORM METHOD="POST">
<H2>  If there's only one Internet - why would it matter how I got there?  Does it make a difference to the end-user &quot;how, when, or with who&quot; he got there?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">It doesn't matter how you got there.  
There are several ways your computer can get to the Internet.
Basically your computer calls a local dial-up server. 
This server in turn gives you an open line to the internet. 
Whether you use AOL, CompuServe, Prodigy...  
or just use the local internet dial-up server-  It doesn't matter.
The different companies like AOL, CompuServe...  have added
features.  I am not too fond of them, BUT they are great for
those wishing to get started on the internet. 
Once you have used them for awhile you may find that the
extra bells and whistles are not needed.  Local Dial-up Servers
get you quick access to the internet and for very reasonable
rates.  They do have a few downfalls, but I'll try to get into
this with your other questions.

</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<P ALIGN="left">&nbsp;
</P>
<H2 ALIGN="left">Why is there such a variance in Internet Service Providers fees?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">This is a new market.  There is no regulations, so some 
companies tend to make others feel inept.   So they will price 
by what they feel the market will take.  In this case you do not
necessarily get what you pay for.  We have seen some servers
charge for each link on a site to another web site.  There is no
mystery in the links, but because some don't know better, they 
will charge for it.  Our charges are pretty much figured out by
how much time will be involved with a site.  When we figure
out our Site charges we figure about $25
an hour or $200 a day.   (Please note that our prices on a Web 
Site Account INCLUDE ALL ART charges!)
You will find some that will charge $70
- $500 an hour.  We figure that it isn't any different than an art
charge that you may incur in a project.  A company that will
charge $750 a page for a web site is nuts, but people will pay.
The space on the internet is cheep, it is the design of the site
that costs. </TEXTAREA>
</P>
<H2 ALIGN="left">Are there different kinds of Service Providers out there?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">Yes!  There are first the Local Dial-up Servers.  They get you 
out there.  They will also give or sell you Internet web space
for your own homepage.  (They then will charge you to design
your site, if you need it.  This also may not be available because
they themselves are usually far behind in getting all those pages
out!) We dealt with our local dial-up server for a while for our
site.  Let me explain why we went and rented our own space. 
First of all we always supplied our server with pages. 
He would take 2-3 weeks just to load them onto his server. 
Because you weren't sure where in the computer he would
place your file, your own links could be wrong.  Or he just plain
uploaded the wrong pages.  Maybe he had old files hanging
around...  It would take several days to get his attention...  He 
wasn't as worried about them as we were.  He also would be
&quot;down&quot;  when your local server is down... Not only are you
unable to dial out, NO ONE on the internet can access your 
Site!  Now that we are out on our own our traffic count just
soared!!!!  We use to get 1-2 hits a day.  I can't even figure
out the changes!!!  It does make a difference where you site
is located.
So there are also ISP who just rent out space.  We have a
great company that we work with!  I recommend them
whenever someone is looking for just the space.  They are
inexpensive.  I don't like being a &quot;Middle man&quot;.  We would
prefer to design your site for you and let you place it on your
server, or have it on ours.  If it is a place with several changes
(Our client Marytown is constantly changing.  They are located 
       at  http://www.Marytown.org
We have them on our server.  It makes up dates much easier.  
By the way, we can upload our changes IMMEDIATELY!!  We
do not take 2-3 weeks.
</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<H2 ALIGN="left">How about speed ---- I hear a lot about it.  What can I ask of the Internet Service Provider when I'm shopping to find if I'm going to get my money's worth?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">If you are fortunate enough to have a choice on which local
 dial-up server they should have a minimum of 14.4 or 28.8 Bds.
 for modem hook-up. (Same goes for your computer modem)
 After you are on the internet cruising around the rest depends
 on several things.
     1.   One of the biggest problems is the local  dial-up server 
           having enough phone lines to handle the traffic!
           We hear (OK, so we grump about it too!) of numerous times
           where you dial-up and the phone lines are busy.
     2.   How many MHZ is your computer. ( A 100mhz is faster than 
            a 75mhz for example)
     3.   How bogged down is the internet itself? Somedays nothing
           loads onto your computer very fast due too the system
           being bogged down. ( Sort of like a traffic jam.)
     4.   And what kind of server is the site you are visiting on?
          If the site is for example Microsoft, this is a very busy site
          and it often takes a longer time for downloads. Even if you
          are looking at the pages instead of downloading software,
          it will take a little while. (Go to McDonalds for a box of fries
          just after a school bus arrived. Even though you may just
          want fries, you will wait like you were waiting to give your
          whole office lunch requests! :&gt;)
     5.  Currently our server is located on a T3 backbone in the 
          MCI building in New York. It is suppose to be the fastest 
          at this time, you STILL have to have #1 &amp; #2 working for you.
  

</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<H3 ALIGN="left"><BR>
  <B>How do I know if an ISP is &quot;genuine&quot; or a &quot;middle-man&quot; (value-adder)?</B></H3>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">I don't know if you can really tell. My advice is... Is the price
reasonable? Do they offer what you want? How is their customer 
service? If you feel confident in their service and don't feel like 
you aren't getting ripped off... Go for it. Personally if someone 
wasn't satisfied with our service and we can't make it right, 
WE WILL give someone their money back. We want to be 
around for the long haul.</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<H2 ALIGN="left"><BR>
Do all the ISPs provide direct dial-up access to the Internet?</H2>
<H2 ALIGN="center"><BR>
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">Nope.  We are not a local dial-up server.</TEXTAREA>
</H2>
<H2>What should I look out for when shopping for an ISP?  What should I steer away from?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">High prices , hidden costs, ... Another thing that I discovered is 
that if they can't accept Visa/Mastercard that may be a warning. 
Because if you can't get the service you want and they won't
listen, YOUR credit card company will go after them. We now
will not buy software (that we have tried out on the internet) with a
check. We learned a lesson. Once a check is cashed it is pretty
much gone. But Visa/Mastercard will fight for you. (We are one 
of the few ISP's that can accept Visa/Mastercard.   We had 
absolutely no problem. It surprised both the Branch Manager of
the bank and us!)</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<H2 ALIGN="left">How are you connected to Internet?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">The servers are located in New York City, one floor belowMCI's 
International T3 backbone. The connection to this backboneis 
made via a direct 10 Mbp/s ethernet cable. This is 6.5 times
faster than a T1 connection plus there is no &quot;long haul&quot; pointof
failure. Many ISP's have a point of failure in the dedicated telephone
line (often a T1) that runs between their office and their uplink 
provider. The uplink provider is another point of failure.  We 
connect directly to the backbone, eliminating these major points 
of failure.</TEXTAREA>
</P>

<H2>  How can I compare &quot;apples to apples&quot; when comparative shopping for <BR>
an ISP?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">You will have to do some work. Know exactly what you want, be
specific, and check out the pricing of services. Since this is
unregulated, it will be all over the board. If someone offers more 
than the other as far as services, check with the others if it is a 
service that others have as well. I know that it is hard to keep up
with all that we can offer our own clients. We are constantly 
learning new things to give our customers.</TEXTAREA>
</P>

<H2>Could you please outline your fee schedule for me, including:  <BR>
initiation fee, if any; monthly fees; promotional price structures; 
 additional charges per hour, if applicable; any hidden costs; etc, etc.  Please state local currency in your quotes.</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">Our currency is US. We don't have any set-up fees.  No hidden
charges.  We would tell you up front if a service that you require
has an added cost.
We would like 1/2 the year up front. But that isn't even absolute.
If you just need a Misery Bay Mall Site, your site doesn't require
a huge layout of time to get it up and running, then the first 
month in advance will be sufficient.
We definitely don't charge the final amount until the customer is
up and running on the site. Then they can pay the rest in 11 
monthly payments, or they will get 2 months off the cost if they
pay the rest at that time. The fees include ALL updates and 
maintenance on the site. If they need a survey, forms, you 
name it we will do it. The charges are based on how much 
work a site will require and how much space that amount of 
work may require for storage.</TEXTAREA>
<BR>
<B>For Web Site Accounts and fees go to<A HREF="http://www.miserybay.com/pay.htm"> http://www.miserybay.com/pay.htm</A></B><A HREF="http://www.miserybay.com/pay.htm"></A></P>
<H2>Does your service allows you to have your own domain name? </H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">Currently to have your own domain name with us you need the
10M of  server space.  This is the Granite Site that is $3600 for
the year (Or $300 a month).  This includes Misery Bay Publications
doing EVERYTHING for the sites homepages  (ALL graphics, 
lay out, HTML's, scanning, linking, FTP into site...  What ever 
the customer needs.   Also included is the registering and setting
up the domain.We also program various search engines within a
customer's site.  (For example if they have a huge catalog and 
wished to help potential customers easily locate a product. </TEXTAREA>
</P>
<H2 ALIGN="left">What are your restictions?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">Misery Bay Publication's standards are our own personal standards.  
We will not place any immoral, illegal, or unethical material, text, 
or photos on our sites.   We have too many clients of whom, we 
do not wish to insult by representing an unconscionable client along
side.  We have turned down clients because of this.  Sorry if that 
offends some, but we have to be able to live with ourselves.  The
internet at this time boasts of anonymity, but we know who we are.      </TEXTAREA>
</P>

<H2>What are your Customer Support hours?  Is there an extra fee for Customer Support?  </H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">No Charge!  We answer E-mail whenever we download.
(Several times a day.) If you call by phone generally we would 
appreciate somewhat normal business hours (9am-5pm Eastern Standard time)
We work at our homes. But we do continually check our e-mail.</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<H2>Do you currently have any promotional packages or incentives?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">A cheery smile? 
Currently we will pretty much do what you want :)
Ok, we have recently signed up to be able to submit ALL our 
sites to over 450 Internet Web Search Engines. Some places
require customers to pay for this service. We like it and think that
this is a Great Service. SO we contracted it ourselves for our
clients.</TEXTAREA>
<BR>
</P>
<H2><BR>
Is there a lease needed?  If so, for how long?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">No.  We would like to have a customer around for a year. But if
you leave and need your pages to go with you to the next server,
you may take them with you. (Providing that the art work has 
been covered in the charges that you have paid.  If you have 
already paid 1/2 up front, it will be covered)</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<H2>Is it necessary for me to be geographically located close to your <BR>
place of business, or your host computer?  If so, why?  If not, why <BR>
not?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">No. With the Internet it just doesn't matter.  There are no 
geographical boarders.  </TEXTAREA>
</P>
<H2> How is payment for your service made?  Is Pre-Authorized Payment <BR>
Plan through a chequing account via a Canadian bank account accepted?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">If you pay by check, we just have to make sure it clears before 
we start. You do need 1/2 up front. We will refund your money if
you aren't happy. We also accept Visa/Mastercard and would 
get authorization from you on the amount before we charge it.</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<H2>Do you provide a &quot;log&quot; or a print-out of account activities forbilling purposes?  If not, is anything like that available through your service?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">We can send you some information that we receive on OUR
&quot;stats&quot;. We also could put up a counter that you can see, or an
invisible one that you can view privately. Sometimes you don't 
want others to be able to view how frequently or infrequently 
your site is visited. If you purchase the account that has your 
own domain name, you will receive your own &quot;stats&quot;. You will 
be able to see where people are visiting from, at what times, ect.</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<H2>Is there a separate fee for an e-mail address and account?  If so, <BR>
how much.  Are there extra charges per piece of mail delivered?  If <BR>
so, how much?</H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">We can forward your e-mail from you web site. You do need a 
dial-up server or an e-mail account. (There is a Great Free E-mail
Service called Juno. See them at http://www.juno.com)</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<H2>How do I sign up with MiseryBay Publications? </H2>
<P ALIGN="center">
<TEXTAREA NAME="TextField" COLS="75" ROWS="4">Fax, phone, mail, or e-mail us with what you would like. We can 
then give you a quote. We work one-on-one with the customer.
Once you give us the go ahead... We jump to it. We will be 
getting a form up on the internet soon, but most of the time you 
do eventually have to call the customer.</TEXTAREA>
</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FORM>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
