<HTML>

<HEAD><TITLE>PEC Anti-Nuclear Campaign - Court of Justice Ruling</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="mask2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#3141CE" VLINK="#408080">
<a name="top"><!-- HEADER -->
<A HREF="index.htm"><img src="dove.gif" align="right" border=0 alt="The Dove of Peace Will Fly"></A>

<br clear>
<!-- END HEADER -->

                                   
<BODY>

<P>
<STRONG><EM>We have too many guns in schools now already! JROTC teaches
the idea that guns are a legitimate way to gain power and prestige.
Let's stop the violence, and stop the military invasion of our
schools.</EM></STRONG>
<P>
<H1><CENTER>TEACH PEACE!</CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=center SIZE=3>
<H1><CENTER>R.O.T.C</CENTER></H1>
<P>
<H3><EM>So, You're thinking of joining the military --</EM> the JROTC.
You think it's a great way to get a start? Well...maybe. But
first you should know a little of what the program won't tell
you.</H3>

<STRONG><EM><UL>
<LI>The first thing you should know is that it's the military
you're dealing with.
</UL>
</EM></STRONG>
 <STRONG>This is not a pre-college program, a job training program,
or -- despite what the name says -- a program to help you become
a military officer. Many people find our too late that the military's
primary goal is combat -- not job training or college prep.</STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG><EM><UL>
<LI>They tell you it's a program for future officers.
</UL>
</EM></STRONG>

<STRONG>Not quite. If past JROTC graduates are any indication, you
probably won't become an officer. If you do go on into the military
(as about half of JROTC students do), it will most likely be as
a private -- scrubbing toilets with toothbrushes and doing push-ups
in the rain while somebody calls you a &quot;maggot&quot; This
is NOT a training program -- it's a recruiting program to pull
you into the bottom of the army.</STRONG>
<BR>
<EM>&quot;We don't want to be misleading, but too much combat
footage interferes with the long term attributes of army service
we want to portray: money for college, skills training, and relevance
to a civilian career. &quot; Col. John Meyers, director of advertising
for the army recruiting command, New York Times.</EM>
<P>
<STRONG><EM><UL>
<LI>They tell you it's a chance to learn job skills.
</UL>
</EM></STRONG>
<STRONG>Maybe, but the jobs in the military are military jobs, and
the skills are mostly being a soldier. Besides, even though you're
promised training in a field like electronics or mechanics, they
don't have to assign you to a job in that field. You could wind
up in the: infantry or anywhere else the military wants you.</STRONG>
<BR>
<STRONG>When you get our. you may be no better off than you are right
now --just older, poorer, and behind all of your classmates. A
recent study by Ohio State University found that only 12 our of
every hundred men, and 6 out of every hundred women made any use
of their military skills later in civilian jobs (unless you want
a job cleaning toilets). In fact, unemployment among young veterans
is 35% higher than among non-veterans of the same age group.</STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG><EM><UL>
<LI>They tell you they offer opportunities to minorities.
</UL>
</EM></STRONG>
<STRONG>Actually, many veterans say that racism is worse inside the
military. For example, they don't tell you that 30% of the enlisted
people are minorities, or that, during the Gulf War, the majority
of front-line troops were minorities, while only one of every
ten officers is not white.</STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG><EM><UL>
<LI>They tell you that women are treated the same as everyone else.
</UL>
</EM></STRONG>
<STRONG>Maybe. But ask people in the program what &quot;Tailhook&quot;
is. (Female officers were physically and sexually assaulted.)
Furthermore, women trained in the same areas as men, such as marksmanship
or combat, are often assigned to do the typing and filing. Why
did 65% of the women in the army say they were being sexually
harassed in 1981? Why is the rate of reported rapes higher in
the military than in civilian life?</STRONG>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="bird.gif"></CENTER>
<H3><CENTER>TEACH PEACE!!!<BR>
P.O. Box 25102<BR>
Lansing, MI 48909</CENTER>
</H3>
<CENTER><STRONG><EM><H3>We want safe schools, not military recruitment centers</H3></EM></STRONG></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="bird.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Some Facts About JROTC</H2></CENTER>
<STRONG><UL>
<LI> The JROTC curriculum claims to teach subjects like history,
civics, English, and health science, even though the Instructors
do not have credentials to teach these subjects.
</UL>

<UL><LI> JROTC teachers are not required to have a college degree
to receive their special subjects credential. State credential
guidelines do not even require them to take the CBEST!</UL>
<UL><LI>&quot;Fortunately for the Army, the government policy of
pushing the Indians farther west then wiping them out was carried
out successfully. &quot; -3rd year Army JROTC textbook, page 185</I></UL></strong>
<STRONG><UL><LI> The value of JROTC credits is so worthless that they do
not count toward entrance requirements for state colleges and
universities. Students' JROTC grades are excluded in computation
of grade point averages, for student aid eligibility.</UL>
<UL><LI>'Americans generally place a high value on human life.
This may not necessarily be the case in other cultures or countries
<EM>. . . for example certain of the terrorist-sponsoring nations
of the Middle East. &quot;-4th year Navy JROTC textbook, page
141</EM></UL></STRONG>
<STRONG><UL><LI> JROTC has never produced valid data to substantiate its
claim that it helps keep students in  school and out of trouble.
In fact, students with academic or disciplinary problems are excluded
from the Navy JROTC program.</UL>
<UL><LI>&quot;Modern advocates of gun control, registration and
the banning of gun ownership should at least be aware that their
efforts, . . . are probably unconstitutional. &quot;-AFJROTC text,
Careen In Aerospace, page 76</UL></STRONG>
<STRONG><UL><LI> The military-style leadership JROTC teaches is inconsistent
with the goals of our schools. More important to students are
the cooperative, democratic leadership and self-discipline already
taught through other programs like music, student government,
and sports.</UL>
<UL><LI> JROTC is a military recruiting program, plain and simple.
This is reflected in the textbooks and stated in official JROTC
documents. Dept. of Defense statistics indicate that almost 50%
of students who pass through the program join the military, the
vast majority in the bottom ranks.</UL>
<UL><LI>&quot;The mark of a true soldier has always been loyalty
and obedience to leaders. It b the same for NJROTC cadets...&quot;-1st
year Navy JROTC textbook, page 24</UL></STRONG>
<STRONG><UL><LI> JROTC propagandizes students with politically-biased lessons
and historical material that is often distorted and sometimes
false. This conclusion was supported by a District-appointed committee
when it reviewed the Air Force JROTC textbooks a few years ago.</UL>
<UL><LI>JROTC discriminates in hiring: teachers must be 'physically
fit': less than 1% of 3ROTC teachers are women; and gays and lesbians are automatically excluded
from the pool of retired officers who are eligible to teach.</UL>
<UL><LI>&quot;Among the traits of a good follower, loyalty is at
the top of the list. This means loyalty to those above us in the
chain of command, whether or not we agree with them. &quot; -1st
year Navy JROTC textbook, page 24</UL></STRONG>
<STRONG><UL><LI> JROTC teaches students rifle marksmanship and drills them
with mock weapons. This is thewrong message when we are trying to convince young people
to stay away from guns and avoid violence.</UL>

<UL><LI>&quot;Take the religion you know best. for instance. .
. It speaks of one God who is the Father of all mankind. . . the
idea of one Universal Father is stressed. &quot; -2nd year Air
Force JROTC textbook, page 67</UL></STRONG>
<STRONG><UL><LI>The JROTC program is not cost effective. While a partial
federal subsidy is received for staff salaries, extra staff, including
an administrator, must be hired. In 1993, the District discovered
that JROTC teachers were costing $301,000 more than regular classroom
teachers!</UL></STRONG>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="bird.gif"></CENTER><BR>
