<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>PEC Anti-Nuclear Campaign - Court of Justice Ruling</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="mask2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#3141CE" VLINK="#408080">
<a name="top"><!-- HEADER -->
<A HREF="index.htm"><img src="dove.gif" align="right" border=0 alt="The Dove of Peace Will Fly"></A>
<br><hr size=4>
<br clear>
<!-- END HEADER -->

<tt>
<H4>For Immediate Release . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .  July 14, 1996
<p>
<b><FONT SIZE="+3">Michigan Lawyers And Activists Hail International Court Of Justice Ruling:<br><p>
 <i>Threat or use of nuclear weapons illegal</I></FONT></P>
</b>
<p>
<table border align="left"><tr><td><font size="+6"><tt>T</tt></font></td></tr></table>he International Court of Justice ruled Monday, July 8, 1996 that "The threat or use of nuclear weapons would generally be contrary to the principles and rules of humanitarian law" and affirmed the "obligation" of all countries "to bring to a conclusion negotiations leading to nuclear disarmament in all its aspects." <p>
<B>THREAT OR USE OF NUCLEAR WEAPONS VIOLATES INTERNATIONAL LAW </B><p>
The International Court of Justice has held that "the threat or use of nuclear weapons would generally be contrary to the rules of international law applicable in armed conflict and in particular the principles and rules of humanitarian law."
<P>
"The International Court has paved the way beyond the nuclear age through law and agreement rather than annihilation," said Anabel Dwyer, a Michigan attorney who was in the Hague during the Court's deliberations as a member of the World Court Project Legal Team for the International Association of Lawyers Against Nuclear Arms. <P>
The Court reaffirmed the primacy of rules of humanitarian law as fundamental legal limits and found that nuclear weapons violate the principles and rules of humanitarian law because nuclear weapons cannot distinguish between civilians and combatants, cause unnecessary suffering, are uncontrollable, and cause long-term, severe and widespread damage to the environment.
<P>
"This is what we've been saying all along," said Rev. Peter Dougherty of Lansing who has been frequently arrested and jailed for resisting nuclear weapons.
<P>
The historic decision was announced Monday, July 8, 1996, as the International Court of Justice read its opinion at the Peace Palace in the Hague.  The judicial arm of the United Nations rendered its decision on a question brought to it by the United Nations General Assembly.
<P>
<B>LARGE MAJORITY OF THE COURT HOLDS THAT INTERNATIONAL LAW CONTROLS </B><P>
Ten of the fourteen judges of the International Court held that the principles and rules of humanitarian law applied even before a state threatened or used nuclear weapons. This was a resounding defeat for the nuclear states, which had argued that they had the right to decide when to threaten or use nuclear weapons and that the law was only applicable after further threat or use of nuclear weapons.
<P>
In addition, seven of the fourteen judges found that the threat or use of nuclear weapons generally violated binding humanitarian law. Those seven, which made a majority because of the tie-breaking vote cast by the President of the Court, provided one caveat to present illegality of nuclear weapons. The Court's majority could not "conclude definitively whether the threat or use of nuclear weapons would be lawful or unlawful in an extreme circumstance of selfdefence in which the very survival of a State would be at stake." <P>
Three judges voted against the caveat finding that present law prohibited any threat or use nuclear weapons even in "extreme circumstances."
<P>
Only four of the fourteen judges found that the Court should not have heard the case or that nuclear weapons were presently beyond the reach of the law.
<P>
The majority opinion also carefully reviews the law of self-defense reminding the nuclear powers that any act of self-defense must be proportional to an attack and must also comport with the principles and rules of humanitarian law.
<P>
"Michigan citizens who have been challenging the legality of nuclear weapons have been affirmed by this decision," said Deborah Choly, a Detroit attorney who has for many years defended civil resisters to nuclear weapons using reasoning similar to that of the International Court.
<P>
"In practice these holdings rule out any legal threat or use of nuclear weapons. The evidence presented to the Court showed overwhelmingly that nuclear weapons are so poisonous, indiscriminate and uncontrollable that they cannot meet the requirements of humanitarian law. The Court's majority simply added the caveat because the reality remains that the nuclear states still have the physical capacity to wreck the sort of havoc that negates the rule of law all together," said Dwyer.
<P>
<B>NUCLEAR DISARMAMENT AN OBLIGATION FOR ALL COUNTRIES
</B><P>
Finally and unanimously the Court held: "There exists an obligation to pursue in good faith and to bring to a conclusion negotiations leading to nuclear disarmament in all its aspects under strict and effective international control."
<P>
"We now have the legal grounding for working out a treaty with the details of eliminating these weapons. The Court obligated all countries to conclude a nuclear disarmament treaty and not only the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty signatories," said Elliot Meyrowitz, Detroit College of Law adjunct professor and author of a major text on Nuclear Weapons and International Law. "Arms control agreements, under this decision, must have the effect of leading to or contributing to achieving nuclear disarmament."
<P>

The Court declined to rule on another question brought by the World Health Organization. But Dr. Victor Seidel, co-president of the International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War commented, "The Court still used the World Health Organization data on the impact of nuclear weapons on health, health services and the environment. So, in effect, the decision that nuclear weapons threat or use is generally contrary to humanitarian law answers the World Health Organization question about the legality of nuclear weapons."
<P>
The achievement of this crucial opinion by the world's highest court is a result of the long-term commitment and dedication of many in Michigan, the U.S. and throughout the world. The court proceeding was initiated by international peace and disarmament groups including the International Association of Lawyers Against Nuclear Arms, the International Peace Bureau and the International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War.
<P>
With the opinion of the International Court of Justice behind them, many local groups are throwing new efforts behind the Abolition 2000 caucus of peace and justice organizations from around the world. Abolition 2000 members work actively on a treaty to abolish all nuclear weapons which can now bring U.S. policy in line with the law.
<P>
"The rapid completion of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty and immediate nuclear disarmament negotiations are now not only a good idea but are also called for by the Court's opinion. A nuclear abolition treaty could and should be completed by the year 2000. Our demands that the U.S. end its $33 billion a year expenditure on nuclear annihilation now have the force of law behind them," said Dwyer.
<P>
<B>For interviews and further information:
</B><P>
<B>Anabel Dwyer, J.D.</B>,            (616) 436-5654.
World Court Project Legal Team, Board Member, Lawyers' Committee on Nuclear Policy, U.S. Branch of International Association of Lawyers Against Nuclear Arms, Michigan Nuremberg Campaign
<P>
<B>Rev. C. Peter Dougherty</B>,       (517) 484-3178
Michigan Peace Teams, Michigan Faith and Resistance <P>
<B>Deborah Choly, J.D.</B>,           (313) 842-0061 National Lawyers Guild, Michigan Nuremberg Campaign <P>
<B>Elliot Meyrowitz, J.D., PhD</B>,   (810) 540-8078 
Lawyers' Committee on Nuclear Policy, author, Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons: The Relevance of International Law <P><br><p>
</H4><hr size=12>
<p>
</tt>
