<TITLE>Peace Education Center Newsletter - Mexican Peace Talks</TITLE>
</HEAD>


<HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="earth2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#3141CE" VLINK="#408080">

<a name="top"><!-- HEADER -->
<A HREF="index.htm"><img src="dove.gif" align="right"border=0 alt="The Dove of Peace Will Fly"></A>
<br><hr size=4>
<br clear>
<!-- END HEADER -->

<BODY>

<P><CENTER>
<H2>Government Violence Threatens Merdcan Peace Talks</H2></CENTER>
<P>
<H3>The Peace Talks between the Zapatista National liberation
Front (EZLN) and the Mexican government are threatened by six
violent (and in two cases lethal) evictions by state police from
lands that had been occupied since last year by local peasants.
The evictions have taken place in the last three days while peace
negotiations have been underway.</H3>
<P>
<H3>The sites oflethal violence were in the municipalities of
Nicolas Ruiz and Pichucalco. peace negotiations continue in an
extremely tense atmosphere punctuated by angry denunciations of
the police actions by the EZLN delegation.</H3>
<P>
<H3>The following first hand report is based on a visit to Nicolas
Ruiz on March 22 by Terra Nunez, Global Exchange volunteer; Miguel
Angel de los Santos, human rights lawyer for the Organizations
of Non-governmental Organizations for Peace (CONPAZ); and Marcos
Arana, a physician also from CONPAZ.</H3>
<P>
<H3>On March 21, 1996, sixty campesinos were working on the property
called Gran Poder which they claim legal right to since 1734,
when they officaliy bought it from the Spanish colonizers. Peasants
had occupied Gran Poder (located three kilometers outside the
municipal capital of Nicolas Ruiz) last year. Nicolas Ruiz is
a Tzotzil indigenous municipality located about two hours southeast
of San Cristobal de las Casas.</H3>
<P>
<H3>At ten in the morning, trucks with over 100 police from the
Seguridad Publica (Public Security) arrived at Gran Poder. Police
surrounded the community and began firing tear gas and live ammunition
to drive the peasants off the land. Witnesses from the community
with whom the delegation spoke said the police had come not just
to evict them but &quot;to kill us&quot;.</H3>
<P>
<H3> At three o'clock the same day, the Mexican Federal Army arrived
to assist the Public Security with the continuing eviction.</H3>
<P>
<H3> The eviction at Gran Poder occurred without any prior notice
by the authorities and took the community by surprise. Three men,
Jose Alfonso Lara, Alfonso Moreno Alvarez, and Gilbaldo Ramirez
Reyes, were killed in the confrontation. One of them was shot
to death as he was eating his noon meal. The remaining men who
were working on the land at the time of the attack were d&quot;ested
by the police. In addition to the three dead peasants, one police
officer was killed. Twenty one peasants Were injured and at least
112 of them are currently being held in jail in Tuxtla Gutierrez,
the state capital.</H3>
<P>
<H3>These six violent evictions haw occurred just days after thirty
local campesino groups met with President Zedillo and signed accords
dealing with land tenure and production issues.</H3>
<P>
<H3> Community members ofNicolas Ruiz are demanding an end to
police attacks, freedom for those being detained, and swift punishment
of the police officers who provoked the confrontation.</H3>
<P>
<H3>In addition to the evictions at Gran Poder, there was a similar
violent eviction that resulted in the death of three peasants
in the municipality of Pichucalco at the finca &quot;Platanera
San Luis del Sureste&quot; on the 20th of March.</H3>
<P>
<H3>by Terra Nunez</H3>
<br>
<H3>Date: March 23, 1996</H3><CENTER>
<A HREF="newscont.htm"><IMG SRC="tealprev.gif"></A></CENTER>
