<TITLE>Peace Education Center - Situation in the West Bank Remains Critical</TITLE>
</HEAD>


<HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="mask2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#3141CE" VLINK="#408080">
<a name="top"><!-- HEADER -->
<A HREF="index.htm"><img src="dove.gif" align="right"border=0 alt="The Dove of Peace Will Fly"></A>
<br><hr size=4>
<br clear>
<!-- END HEADER -->


<BODY>
<P>
<CENTER><H2>Situation in the West Bank Remains Critical</H2>
</CENTER><P>
<H4> Despite the recent easing of the internal closure of the
West Bank on Saturday, 16 March, the human rights situation in
the West Bank remains critical. Hospitals and clinics have been
unable to resume badly needed treatments for lack of medication
and supplies, military checkpoints remain throughout the West
Bank, and several villages remain under curfew. In addition, it
has become clear that settlers have used this period of siege
on Palestinian towns and villages to carry out acts of aggression
against Palestinian land Finally, the witch hunt continues against
Islamic institutions, with two additional charity organizations
shut down by the Israeli army.</H4>
<P>
<H4> In economic terms, the past two weeks have taken a devastating
toll as the siege not only prevented workers and goods from entering
Israel but prevented internal travel as well. Even with the easing
of restrictions inside the West Bank, the sealing off of the West
Bank and Gaza from Israel continues to cripple the Palestinian
economy. President Arafat has stated that this type of total closure
represents a daily loss of about 6 million dollars, and approximately
70,000 workers from the West Bank and Cats are unable to reach
their workplaces in Jerusalem and Israel.</H4>
<P>
<H4> Hospitals and clinics still await badly needed medication
as supplies have still been held up at the military checkpoints
into the West Bank. Advanced treatments like chemotherapy have
had to be suspended due to the lack of supplies. Two days after
the easing of the internal closure this situation remains critical.</H4>
<P>
<H4>On the day after the easing of the internal closure, Israeli
military checkpoints remained in place between Areas A, B and
C, hindering movement between these Areas.</H4>
<P>
<H4> On 16 March, the Israeli army entered Rumana village near
Jenin and arrested three men. The figures for the total arrested
by the Israeli army in the West Bank varies widely, partly because,
due to the internal state of siege, family members were not able
to go to the Red Cross offices and report missing or arrested
family members. Some estimates put the number as high as 1000.</H4>
<P>
<H4> On 17 March, two additional Islamic charity institutions
were closed by the Israeli army. Israeli army and police raided
the Holy Land Fund in Jerusalem, confiscated documents, and ordered
the office closed for 14 days. Even more serious, army and police
forcibly entered the Islamic Relief Committee in Nazareth and
confiscated money, checks, documentation, fax machines, computers,
and other office equipment. The office was then closed and welded
shut.</H4>
<P>
<H4> On 17 March, Israeli Prime Minister Peres again went on record
as supporting the expulsion of HAMAS members.</H4>
<P>
<H4> On 17 March, in Walja village near Bethlehem, curfew was
imposed for the second time since 5 March, 20 men were arrested,
and many houses raided. By 18 March, total curfew remained in
effect for the third straight week in Rafat, Burqa and Qariut
villages, near Nablus, and in al Fawar refugee camp near Hebron.</H4>
<P>
<H4> The Israeli army set up a new military checkpoint at the
entrance to Habla village, near Qalqilya, and soldiers stopped
all cars and residents entering and leaving the village. No reason
for this additional checkpoint was given.</H4>
<P>
<H4> Efrat settlement took advantage of the internal siege of
the West Bank to seize land belonging to El Khader residents.
Settlers have begun excavating the land in preparation for the
building of new housing units on the land. Residents were only
able to seek legal advice after the easing of the internalclosure.</H4>
<P>
<H4> The Jahalin Bedouin tribe continues to receive eviction orders
and house/tent demolition orders from the Israeli government to
make way for the continuing expansion of Ma'aleh Adumim settlement,
located between Jerusalem and Jericho in the West Bank.</H4>
<P>
<H4>Wanted:</H4>
<P>
<H4>On 16 March, a resident of Fardes village, near</H4>
<P>
<H4>Bethlehem, received a warning of demolition against this home.</H4>
<P>
<H4> On 17 March residents of Tamoun village, between Nablus and
Jenin, discovered that during the siege, settlers from Beqa'ot
and Roi settlements had seized and destroyed 1500 dunums (375
acres) of land cultivated with wheat. Residents put the loss of
this land, some of the richest agricultural land in this area,
at approximately one million dollars. This represents a massive
economic loss for this village.</H4>
<P>
<H4> On 18 March, the Israeli army demolished a house in Shoqa,
near Tulkarem, for having no permit. This brings to 62 the total
number of houses demolished since the signing of the Oslo Accord
in September 1993.</H4>
<P>
<H4> Since the Tel Aviv bombing on 4 March, four houses have been
demolished, and another seven have received demolition orders
and have been sealed.</H4>
<P>
<H4>Land and Water Establishment</H4>
<br>
<H4>  PO Box 20873</H4>
<br>
<H4>   Jerusalem</H4>
<br>
<H4>Tel: (972)) (2) 812364/824559</H4>
<br>
<H4> Fax: (972) (2) 811072</H4>
<br>
<H4>email: lawe@netvision.net.il</H4>
<P>
<H4> Land and Water Establishment is a non-governmental organization
based in Jerusalem, dedicated to preserving human rights through
legal advocacy. Your comments on the above are welcome. Please
do not hesitate to contact us.</H4>
