<TITLE>Peace Education Center Newsletter - Sweep of Birzeit Area Villages</TITLE>
</HEAD>


<HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="earth2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#3141CE" VLINK="#408080">
<a name="top"><!-- HEADER -->
<A HREF="index.htm"><img src="dove.gif" align="right"border=0 alt="The Dove of Peace Will Fly"></A>
<br><hr size=4>
<br clear>
<!-- END HEADER -->
<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><H2>Massive Sweep of Birzeit Area Villages</H2>
</CENTER><P>
<H3> The following was received by the Christian Peacemaker Team
in Hebron. Birzeit, the oldest university in the West Bank, has
been a political and cultural center for Palestine since 1967.</H3>
<P>
<H3> Since Birzeit's phone lines were all down at the moment,
a group of international students and faculty, including Carmen
Pauls, former Hebron CPTer, requested that this release be put
out over CPT net.</H3>
<P>
<H3> &quot;Birzeit, Palestine--In the early hours of the morning,
at least 370 Palestinians in the villages of Birzeit, Abu Qash,
and Abu Shukhaydim were roused from their sleep and taken from
their homes in the largest Israeli raid since the signing of the
Oslo Accords.</H3>
<P>
<H3> Many of the detainees are Birzeit University students. Although
Israel Defense Force (IDF) authorities claimed to be targeting
Hamas militants and students from Gaza, the majority of those
taken in for questioning were West Bank residents.</H3>
<P>
<H3> Furthermore, the arrests appeared to be haphazard. Among
those picked up were individuals from a variety of political factions,
including Christians from Bethlehem and elsewhere. The detainees
were held in a playground near the Birzeit campus before being
taken away, blindfolded and in handcuffs. IDF forces imposed house
arrest on the village from 3:30 am to 10 am, forbidding residents
to leave their homes.</H3>
<P>
<H3> Hundreds of Israeli soldiers, aided by helicopter surveillance,
broke down apartment doors and forced residents, including women
and children, into the street while the premises were searched.</H3>
<P>
<H3> As a result of this military operation, classes at Birzeit
were once again disrupted. The university was essentially closed
for several weeks due to restrictions on travel imposed by the
Israeli military, and classes resumed only ten days ago.</H3>
<P>
<H3> Spontaneous demonstrations broke out at the Birzeit-Ramallah
military checkpoint when the students and faculty were prevented
from reaching the University. At least one student was injured
and taken to the hospital. A Swedish choir that was scheduled
to perform at Birzeit today was also held up and, in a gesture
of support, sang several pieces from their repertoire at the checkpoint.</H3>
<P>
<H3>In the afternoon, Birzeit student leaders organized a convocation
at the university, followed by a demonstration near the Israeli
military headquarters in Beit El. Faculty and students expressed
their solidarity with those detained and protested the massive
human rights violations, including the use of collective punishment.</H3>
<P>
<H3> Israeli troops fired into the air, injuring at least one
woman. Faculty and students are concerned that the Israeli roundup
might be a prelude to closing the University.</H3>
<P>
<H3>Submitted by members of the International Community at Birzeit
University</H3><CENTER><CENTER><IMG SRC="snake2.gif"></CENTER>
<A HREF="newscont.htm"><IMG SRC="tealprev.gif"></A></CENTER>
