<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Peace Education Center - Where Tax Money Really Goes</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="money.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#3141CE" VLINK="#408080">
<a name="top"><!-- HEADER -->
<A HREF="index.htm"><img src="dove.gif" align="right" border=0 alt="The Dove of Peace Will Fly"></A>

<!-- END HEADER -->

<P>
<H1><CENTER>Poll Finds U.S. Citizens Expect Peace Dividend</CENTER></H1>
<P><IMG SRC="tax03.gif" HSPACE=1.5 ALIGN=right>
<H4>&quot;Three out of four Americans say the warming of relations
between the United States and the Soviet Union can open the way
for cuts in military spending; by a wide margin they want this 'peace dividend' spent to fight problems here at home....&quot;</H4>
<P>
<H4> But there is no more &quot;Soviet Union&quot; you say? Right.
The quote above and chart are from 1990.*  President George Bush
was about to present the fiscal year 1991 budget, and the Cold
War between the two world superpowers was melting. The Berlin
Wall had fallen and change was sweeping Eastern Europe.</H4>
<P>
<H4> Flip this sheet over and we're up to date. In February 1994,
President Bill Clinton sent this budget proposal to Congress and
to the American people for comment. The percentages tell all:
change has not swept the U.S. government. We are still waiting
for that &quot;peace dividend,&quot; while homelessness, hunger,
unemployment, pollution, poverty, poor schools, and hopelessness
plague our society and so much of the world. </H4>
<P>
<H4>In the next five years the Pentagon will spend $1.3 trillion
for the so-called &quot;defense&quot; of the U.S. That's $400,000
a minute for guns, missiles, submarines, and soldiers, yet people
do not feel safe in their homes. The 1995 budget includes $28
billion for secret military programs; this &quot;black budget&quot;
is even secret from most of Congress.</H4>
<P>
<STRONG><EM>  <H4> Setting the priorities of the nation is everyone's business.</H4></EM></STRONG>
<P>
<H4>The people have called for a peace dividend, so why are we
still spending our hard-earned tax dollars teaching young people
to kill? Let's give them scholarships to become doctors for rural
communities. Foreign countries would welcome U.S. doctors instead
of U.S. soldiers. With that $400,000 a minute, let's retrain the
workers who build military weapons to build trains and buses,
to fix our roads and bridges, to clean up the environment. Let's
take the billions from &quot;Star Wars&quot; military systems
and create a &quot;Star Wars&quot; to fight AIDS, breast cancer,
and infant mortality. </H4>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="fish2.gif"></CENTER>
<H2><EM>Set your own priorities. How would you finish this sentence:</EM></H2>
<P>
<H3>  Let's take (circle one) $50 billion/$100 billion/$200 billion/ALL
$302 billion from the military and spend it on ______________________________.</H3>

<CENTER><H2>Now tell that to the President and Congress.</H2></CENTER>
<P>
<STRONG>     * New York Times, January 25, 1990, page B9</STRONG>
<P><CENTER>
<A HREF="tax.htm"><IMG SRC="tealprev.gif"></A></CENTER>
