<HEAD><TITLE>Building the Bement Library</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pastel.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF0080">
<P>

<P><h3>Building the Bement Library</h3></P>
<P><h4><FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>
ollowing the crash of 1929, monetary chaos in  the large financial centers crept gradually out to the smaller communities.  In 1933 the banks in Saint Johns reluctantly closed for federally mandated bank holidays.  There was discomfort among the population but no panic.  Thanks to the conservative banking policies of people like John C. Hicks, Coleman C. Vaughn, Arthur E. Wilson, and O.P. DeWitt, banks in Saint Johns were still fiscally sound.</P>
<P>People in Saint Johns were also suspicious of make-work and boondoggling federal programs and generally shied away from PWA projects.  In 1934, however, the City availed itself of a PWA grant to develop the old Emmons Woods land into a modern city park </P>
<P>On September 9, 1938 the City of Saint Johns petitioned the Federal Emergency Administration of Public Works for a grant to aid in financing the construction of and equipping of a Library City Hall.  They designated R.V. Gay as the architect.  </P>
<P> The three City Commissioners that year were Harry Bradley, George Brooks and George H. Schoenhals.  Two weeks later they voted to take $20,428.88 from the Bement fund, $6,593.87 from the General Fund, and $477.25 from the Water fund and place the whole $27,500 into the Library City Hall Building account.</P>
<P>Then on October 31, 1938 it was announced that Saint Johns had received federal approval for two grants of $22,500 each to help finance construction of a new Perrin School and a City Hall-Library building.  Actually the Federal government agreed to supply 45% of funding for the buildings, not to exceed $22,500.  All equipment for the City's building, except for the books, was to be purchased with the Federal money.  Work on the new buildings could commence no later than December 31, 1938; and the project was to be completed within 10 months.</P>
<P>On November 9 the Commission voted to purchase Carl Bunge's second hand store and the American Legion Hall, lots 7 and 8 of Block number 7.  The next night they accepted the options given them by the Bunges and Leah Fowler Hunt.</P>
<P>The American Legion was offered $1500 and the building across the street that was then being occupied by the Building and Loan Association, the Royal Neighbors, and the Modern Woodmen.  The City took $5,000 out of the water fund for the Legion to purchase the building from Mrs. Hunt.  Then they contributed $25 to the Royal Neighbors and the Modern Woodmen to help them move.  The Bunge building was purchased for $3,000 that was also taken from the Water fund.</P>
<P>Contracts were awarded on December 24.  Hudson and Howe of Owosso had bid $39,336 for the general contract work.  The Plumbing and Heating contract went to C.G. Brenner of Lansing with a bid of $6,504.  Reed-Tyler Electric of Lansing had bid $2,616.  The first estimate was that the building would cost $50,000.  Now it appeared that it would cost $52,500; so another $2500 was taken out of the Water fund </P>
<P>In the summer of 1939 $3,600 was taken from the general fund and placed into a separate Library Fund.  The Park Commission's budget was set at $1,400.  The City Commission appropriated $3,600 for the Fire Department </P>
<P>On June 27, 1939 an amendatory application to PWA Project Michigan 1816 F was submitted to the Federal government asking for an increase in the grant.  Changes and additions made by the Commission had raised the general contractor's expenses to $43,499.50.  Plumbing and Heating now would cost $7,309.54.  Electrical wiring would amount to $2,604.00.  The Hardware contract, awarded to VanDervoort Hardware in Lansing, stood at $921.60.  Venetian Blinds would cost $700.  The equipment fo for the building would cost another $3,800.  Legal and administrative costs would be $150.  Another $165.36 was written into the grant application for contingencies.  The total cost of everything, except the books, was going to be $63,000.</P>
<P>The City needed another $13,000 and put up their 55% of that amount, $7,150.  The Commission was asking that the Federal government add $5,850 to the original $22,500 grant.  </P>
<P> The Federal government approved the amended application on October 16, 1939.  A few days later the Commission requested an extension of the project completion time from October 28 to December 28, 1939.  This request also was granted.</P>
<P>Architect R.V. Gay attended that same meeting and told the Commissioners that he had purchased brass letters spelling out &quot;Bement Library&quot; and Municipal Building.&quot;  The letters would cost $135.  Due to time constraints, the Commission decided to assume this expense outside the general contract.</P>
<P>A document of completion was issued to the contractors and sent to the PWA on December 19, 1939.  A month later the Commission found that another $7.79 was needed to complete the project.  It was taken from the Water fund.  The final cost of the building and its contents was $63,507.79.</P>
<P>At the December 19, 1940 meeting the City Commissioners appointed a Library Board of five directors for the newly established library pursuant to the provisions of Act 164 of the Public Acts of 1877 as Amended, being sec. 8059 to 8075 inclusive, Compiled Laws of Michigan for 1929, to serve from January 1, 1940 for the following terms:</P>
<P>Frank P. Buck for the term of five (5) years.</P>
<P>Miss Winifred C. Daboll for the term of four (4) years.</P>
<P>Myron E. Ward for the term of three (3) years.</P>
<P>Mrs. Lee A. DeWitt for the term of two (2) years.</P>
<P>Mrs. Robert J. Merrill for the term of one (1) year.</P>
<P>THE CITY OFFICES</P>
<P>The City offices opened first.  City manager Theodore H. Townsend and Miss Ada Cochrane, the city clerk, moved in on Monday February 19, 1940.  The next night the City Commission held its first regular meeting in the new Commission chambers.</P>
<P>Besides the city offices and library, the building contained an auditorium and dining hall which included a stage and kitchen facilities.   There were club rooms and two public toilets in the basement.</P>
<P>Built of buff brick and stone, the City Hall-Library was a 50x80-foot two-story structure which effectively used the basement as a third story.  The front elevation on Walker Street extended east 50 feet from the fire hall with a 16-foot lawn on Spring.  The east elevation, extending north from Walker, had a double entrance to the library on the first floor and the club rooms in the basement.</P>
<P>On the Walker Street side there was a recessed entrance trimmed with stone and three ornamental bronze lights. </P>
<P> Just inside the double doors was a small vestibule, wainscoted in tile, that lead to the main hall.  At the left a wide stairway rose to the second floor. Built into one approach to the stairs was a wall of glass block that concealed electric lights which added to the illumination given off by overhead chandeliers.</P>
<P>The first door at the right of the hall opened into the 14x20 foot Commission chamber.  Beyond this room to the east and north were three smaller offices for the city manager, engineer and assessor.</P>
<P>On down the main hall beyond the Commission room door, the next turn to the right led to a small lobby flanked on the north by the 13x22 foot city clerk's office with public counters for the transaction of business.  At the west end of this office was a 9x14 foot fireproof vault equipped with a heavy steel door.  Adjacent to the lobby were cloak rooms for the use of city officials.</P>
<P>The main hall was terrazzo floor while the lobby and several offices were floored with asphalt tile.  All of the building's windows had Venetian blinds.</P>
<P>At the north end of the first floor hall was a stairway descending to the basement and a narrow hall leading to the library.  Off this latter hall to the west were two small rest rooms.</P>
<P>THE LIBRARY</P>
<P>The main approach to the library was from the Spring Street side of the building, up a few steps from the street level to a small platform with an iron railing. The monumental type brick entrance with its double doors led to the small vestibule and on into the library.</P>
<P>The main library room was 40 feet long by 30 feet wide with  ventilator type windows along the north and east walls.  From the colorful mosaic ceiling hung several white metal chandeliers.  The library and the other rooms on the first and second floors were considered sound-proofed.  Along all sides of the library, and between and under the windows, were book shelves of various heights.  There was space for between 6,000 and 7,000 volumes.</P>
<P>Library equipment included tables and chairs for public use, magazine racks, a special charge desk, and a work room for the librarian.  The woodwork was of birch, as it was throughout the whole building.</P>
<P>THE AUDITORIUM</P>
<P>The combined auditorium and dining hall was equipped with a maple floor suitable for dancing.  Its approximately 48 square feet were built to accommodate 300 persons at a banquet and at least 400 for a play or public meeting.  </P>
<P>The auditorium's colored ceiling was done in Celotex, and there were nine indirect lighting fixtures and four other lights set flush in the ceiling.  Two large radiators along the east wall were equipped with fans and allegedly provided direct radiant heat and air conditioning.</P>
<P>The stage was nearly 27 feet wide by 12 feet deep with fluted pilasters on either side of the proscenium arch.  The curtain was done in wine colored velour with a matching valance trimmed in gold.  Under the stage was storage space for tables and 400 wood and metal folding chairs.</P>
<P>At the top of the stairway leading to the second floor was a 9x30 foot kitchen with electric stove and refrigerator, cupboard space, and two sinks.  Between the kitchen and auditorium was a serving room and a cloak room.</P>
<P><B>THE BASEMENT</B></P>
<P>The organization rooms in the basement were reached by means of the curving stairs on the Spring Street side. This entrance was directly below that of the library and opened into a small lobby serving both the large and small organization rooms.  One had dimensions of 30x40 feet and the other was 22x25 feet.  Adjacent to these was a smaller room used as a kitchen.  These organization rooms were ventilated by means of eight-foot ceilings and were lighted for daytime use by well-type windows.</P>
<P>At the rear of the building on the north side was a small door with stairs leading to all three floors.  This was called the stage entrance because the door at the top connected directly with the auditorium's stage.</P>
<P>The boiler that provided heat for both the Municipal Building and the fire hall also was located in the basement's south side.</P>
<P><B><I>THE </I></B><B>FIRST LIBRARY </B></P>
<P><B>BOARD</B></P>
<P>The first meeting of the Board of Directors of the Bement Library was held on January 25, 1940.  The members were sworn in by City Clerk Ada Cochrane.  Myron Ward, a member of the City Commission, opened the meeting and appointed Mr. Buck temporary chairman.</P>
<P>Officers for that first Library Board included Frank Buck, president; Teresa Merrill, secretary; and Nina DeWitt, treasurer.</P>
<P>Winifred Daboll, Myron Ward, and Teresa Merrill were appointed to a committee to develop rules and regulations for the new library.</P>
<P>City Manager Theodore Townsend spoke briefly about the lack of interest shown in good reading at the present time.  He believed, he said, that this was due at least in part to the general condition of unrest among the people.</P>
<P>Finally a letter was introduced from the Ministerial Association asking that some religious books be included in the selection of new books.</P>
<P>At the next meeting on February 1, 1940 letters of application for the position of Librarian were read.  The Board voted to tender the position to Miss Minnie Barrington.</P>
<P>A Constitution and By-Laws had been approved at the February 1, 1940 meeting.  This document included the following paragraphs:</P>
<P><B>CONSTITUTION</B></P>
<P>The name of this body shall be the Board of Directors of the Municipal Library of St. Johns, or the Bement Public Library. </P>
<P>The Board of Directors shall consist of five members appointed January 1st, 1940 by the Mayor of St. Johns for the terms of five, four, three, two, and one years respectively, as provided by sections 8060-11 of Act 248 of Public Libraries Laws of the State of Michigan.  Thereafter the Mayor shall appoint annually one member for five years.</P>
<P>The Mayor shall have power, with the consent of the City Commission, to remove any director for misconduct or neglect of duty.</P>
<P>No officers except the librarian and assistant shall receive any compensation.</P>
<P>This Constitution may be added to at the annual meeting by the unanimous vote of the Board of Directors.</P>
<P><B>BY LAWS</B></P>
<P>Powers of the Board</P>
<P>of Directors</P>
<P>I.  The Board of Directors shall have power to make and adopt by-laws and rules and regulations not inconsistent with the Act regarding Public Libraries.</P>
<P>II.  To have exclusive control of all moneys collected to the credit of the Library Fund, but to be disbursed only by the officers of the City of St. Johns upon vouchers properly authenticated by the Librarian.</P>
<P>III.  To have supervision, care and custody of the rooms set apart for the purposes of the Library.</P>
<P>IV.  To exclude from the use of the Library any and all persons who shall willfully violate its rules.</P>
<P>V.  To appoint a suitable librarian and assistant and to fix their compensations and also to remove such appointees.</P>
<P>VI.  To purchase books, periodicals, newspapers and other material and supplies and furnishings needful for a library.</P>
<P><B>RULES AND REGULATIONS</B></P>
<P>The Library shall be free to the inhabitants of St. Johns, subject to the rules and regulations adopted by the Board; and to the inhabitants of Clinton County except that persons unknown to the librarian must present a card signed by some responsible resident of St. Johns.  The use of books in the Reading Room shall be free to all persons but, transients shall not take books from the Reading room.</P>
<P>The Library shall be open daily except Sunday and Legal Holidays;</P>
<P>Monday, Wednesday, Thurs-day and Saturday 1 - 5 P.M.</P>
<P>Tuesday and Friday 2 - 4 and 7 - 9 P.M.</P>
<P>No talking or noise shall be permitted that disturbs those engaged in the legitimate use of the Library.</P>
<P>Reference and current newspapers and magazines shall not be taken from the Reading Room.</P>
<P>A fine of two cents a day shall be collected upon books held beyond the allotted time.  Failure to pay the fine shall entail forfeiture of the privilege of drawing books or other materials from the Library until the fine is paid.</P>
<P>The Library shall not be available for meetings of committees, groups of individuals or organizations except those of the Library Board.</P>
<P><B>DUTIES OF BOARD OF DIRECTORS</B></P>
<P>I.   The Board shall make at the close of each and every year a report to the City Commission of their trust, including:</P>
<P><B><I>        </I></B>a)  All sums of mo<B><I>ney</I></B></P>
<P><B><I>        received and their sources.</I></B></P>
<P><B><I>        </I></B>b)  All sums of money</P>
<P><B><I>       </I></B> expended and their purposes.</P>
<P>c)  Number of books and periodicals on hand.</P>
<P>d)  Number of books and periodicals added and their sources.</P>
<P>e)  Number of books and periodicals lost and missing.</P>
<P>f)  Number of books and periodicals lent.</P>
<P>g)  General character of book and periodicals lent.</P>
<P>h)  Suggestions of policy in conduct of library.</P>
<P>The Board shall make a report on the receipt and expenditure of money; on the number of books on hand, the number of books lost, the number missing and purchased.</P>
<P>Later the Board voted to inset a paragraph to the effect that full price, less 10%, should be charged for any lost book.</P>
<P>Winifred Daboll suggested that various civic organizations be asked to contribute magazine subscriptions to the library.  These magazines, along with any books, were to be subject to the approval of the Library Board, the Librarian, and ultimately the State Librarian Mrs. McClure.</P>
<P>On February 28 the completed selection of books was put up for bids, and a $16 dictionary and a $2.50 bound .cb</P>
<P>secretary's book were purchased from Parr's Drug Store.</P>
<P>Two weeks later the Board voted to accept the $442.76 bid from Boker and Taylor for the list of books that would be available when the library opened.</P>
<P>Just before the library opened for the first time, the Board agreed to purchase the Bliss library of 170 books for $50.  Miss Eleanor Trask was hired to be the Assistant Librarian. She would be expected to work 5 1/2 days per week at regular compensation.  Finally Board members decided to order the Detroit Free Press as the daily newspaper for the reading room.  Now all was in readiness for the long awaited opening of the Bement Public Library.</P>
<P>OPENING DAY</P>
<P>The Bement Library first opened its doors to the public on Saturday, April 13, 1940.  Miss Minnie Barrington, who most recently had been the librarian at  Rodney B. Wilson High School, was in charge.</P>
<P>The work of cataloging books had been going on for weeks. &quot;There are fifteen separate entries and operations necessary before a book is available to the public,&quot; Miss Barrington had explained.  &quot;This must be done carefully and accurately in order that the patron may find the wanted information with a minimum of delay and to assure that the whereabouts of any book may be known at all times.&quot;</P>
<P>One of the first donations received by the new Bement Library was a gift of $50 from the St. Johns Woman's Club.  The first 500 books were largely works of fiction and biography.  Miss Winifred Daboll, a member of the Library Board, said that the reading tastes and habits of the patrons would be studied and used as a guide for future purchases.  </P>
<P>Because the furniture for the children's corner had not yet arrived, the juvenile books would not be placed in circulation until a week later.</P>
<P>Right from the beginning children were an important part of the Bement Public Library.  Of those first five Library Board members, three had spent their lives in the education of Saint Johns children.</P>
<P>FRANK P. BUCK</P>
<P>Board Chairman, Frank P. Buck, was a home town boy.  His family home was located at 207 Breckenridge Street in Emmonsville.  This would later become 507 W. Baldwin.</P>
<P>Frank Buck graduated from the St. Johns High School in 1892 and returned as principal in 1899.  Later he was made Superintendent of Schools, an office he filled until 1931.  He stayed on as principal of the high school until his retirement in 1939. </P>
<P>On October 8, 1937 the high school athletic field at the new City Park was named the Frank P. Buck Field.  Two high school seniors, James Kelly and Robert Ebert, had first proposed naming the field in his honor.  Phyllis Osgood was the Athletic Queen.</P>
<P>In June, 1944 the Library Board sent a bouquet of flowers to Mr. Buck who was ill.  A month later he was dead; and the Board Secretary, Miss Winifred Daboll, was named Chairman of the Board.</P>
<P>WINIFRED C. DABOLL</P>
<P>Winifred Campbell Daboll was also a long-time Saint Johns resident.  Her father, Judge Sherman B. Daboll, was something of a self-made man.  In his Past and Present of Clinton County, Michigan Daboll recounted how he had made his own way in the world beginning at the age of nine years.  He had served in the Civil War with a regiment from New York.  </P>
<P> After the war, the young Daboll had studied law with various upstate New York law firms.  In 1869 he had married Elizabeth Campbell who was descended from the clan Campbell on one side and Governor William Bradford of Plymouth colony on the other.  Daboll and his wife had come to Saint Johns in 1879 with their only child, six-year-old Winifred, who had been born on September 29, 1873.</P>
<P>The family home was a 206 N. Mead, and Winifred had graduated from St. Johns High School two years after Frank Buck in 1894.  After earning a Master's Degree from the Michigan University in Ann Arbor, Winifred returned to St. Johns High School to teach Latin and English.</P>
<P>Although she spent the rest of her life in her little home town, Miss Daboll was well-respected as an educator outside her own small sphere.  When Gordon Frank and Howard Charles Wickes, the twin sons of foundryman Frank Wickes, tried to enter the University of Michigan in 1909, they were told that their small high school had not qualified them for entrance.  Miss Daboll simply sent a letter to the admissions office stating that she believed the boys were well-prepared and could succeed at the University.  In 1914 both graduated from the University of Michigan with degrees in Civil Engineering.</P>
<P>Like her father, Miss Daboll was passionately interested in history.  In  1937   she wrote a history of her home parish, St. Johns Episcopal Church, which today has become a collector's item.  In 1945 she suggested adding a Department of Local History to the Bement Library.  She offered to work on the collection herself in her leisure time.  A year later the Board commended her for her work in cataloging an unwieldy work, the History of Free Masonry which had been donated by the estate of the late attorney, William Smith.  The Board had been stunned by the magnitude of the work involved and could only thank her for the uncounted hours she had put into this &quot;tremendous task.&quot;</P>
<P>Following her death on June 5, 1952, the Board was at a loss as to how to honor the memory of Winifred C. Daboll.  At first they had hoped to place a photograph of her next to that of the retired Minnie Barrington, but the only known photo of her had been taken at her graduation from the University.  Finally a set of books, The Life of Washington by Freeman was purchased with money donated by her East Walker Street neighbors.  Delbert Clark also donated a set of 12 phonograph records on the subject of democracy in her honor.</P>
<P>TERESA MERRILL</P>
<P>Teresa Merrill served as the Secretary of the Library Board for more than 25 years.  She was married to attorney Robert Merrill and taught in Saint Johns for many years.  In 1958 she retired from teaching after having been the principal of East Ward School for 26 years.  In 1976 the school was named Teresa Merrill School in her honor.</P>
<P>As time went on the next generation began to run for office and take over their fathers' businesses.  After having taught for so many years, Mrs. Merrill began to believe that she actually had taught every younger person in the community.  And whenever she began to speak about them, she inevitably recalled that each had been her special favorite.</P>
<P>Mrs. Merrill was a faithful Catholic.  She attended Mass every Sunday without fail; and every Sunday without fail she would greet the pastor on her way out, pat him on the cheek and say, &quot;That was just wonderful, Darlin'.&quot;</P>
<P>Then one Sunday, when even the pastor himself had not been too pleased with his homily, Mrs. Merrill greeted him at the door, patted him on the cheek and said, &quot;Just couldn't get it together this morning, could you, Darlin'?&quot;</P>
<P>Mrs. Merrill lived alone for some years after the death of her husband.  Finally the day came when she could no longer stay in her own home.  At the local nursing home some of the employees, who had been raised in a different era, were dismayed by her behavior.  At each meal Mrs. Merrill insisted upon presiding at the head of the table with her hair freshly done, dressed for dinner.</P>
<P>MINNIE BARRINGTON</P>
<P>Still another beloved local educator, Librarian Minnie Barrington, was born in Bourbon County, Kentucky.  Her father, William M. Barrington, had died when she was only three months old.  Her mother, Sarah Hulse Barrington, later married Dr. S.M. Post, a physician at Eureka.</P>
<P>Minnie had graduated from Elsie High School and began her teaching career in Saint Johns.  She later attended Michigan State Normal College in Ypsilanti and even taught in Colorado and Pontiac, Michigan.  Soon she returned to Saint Johns and resumed her local teaching career.  Her specialty was junior high school history.  When she retired from teaching, she was the principal of Central School.</P>
<P>In the Library Miss Barrington had the ability to make little children feel like she and the Library were there only to serve them.  There was a child-sized round wooden table with matching chairs in the Children's Corner, the northwest corner of the main room.  Here there were low shelves full of wonderful friends including Snip, Snap, and Snurr; Babar with his little old lady and his elephant family; and poor old Jonathan Bing who just couldn't manage to visit the king.</P>
<P>Once in a while there was an adult, a former student, who still didn't quite feel like a grownup in Miss Barrington's presence.  One such individual was Police Chief Everett Glazier.</P>
<P>&quot;Why you know,&quot; exclaimed a bewildered Minnie.  &quot;He almost acts like he is afraid of me.  Imagine!&quot;</P>
<P>Miss Barrington knew how to make each child feel special.  She always called one little girl her twin because they both had been born on March 16.  As to just how many years apart the two had been born, no one was ungracious enough to inquire.</P>
<P>&quot;Everybody knows how old I am,&quot; Miss Barrington had said at the time of her retirement in July, 1950.  &quot;Just don't describe me as 'the aged librarian.'&quot;</P>
<P>In explaining her retirement Miss Barrington had said, &quot;I'm just tired.&quot;  She died ten years later following a fall at her home.  She was 87 at the time of her death - and it was revealed then that she had been 71 years older than her little &quot;twin.&quot;  City employees purchased a swinging wing bulletin board to be placed in the Library in her memory.</P>
<P>  In her &quot;Book Shelf&quot; column in the Clinton County Republican-News, Elizabeth Millman reminisced about &quot;Aunt Minnie&quot; after her death: </P>
<P>She loved to tell the story of her experience in the Durand railway station.  While waiting for a train there she fell into conversation with two young men.  </P>
<P>Since she was a baseball enthusiast, that was the subject of their conversation.  In its course she mentioned that she was a friend of Van Patrick, sports announcer for many years.</P>
<P>&quot;Why you're Aunt Minnie,&quot; the boys said, greeting her like a long-lost friend.  In the course of some of his broadcasts, Van Patrick had often sent &quot;Greetings to Aunt Minnie!&quot;</P>
<P>Her interest in sports was only one facet of her personality.  She had  a wide range of interests and could answer questions on many subjects, from the most obscure one on history to which horse won the Kentucky derby in any given year.</P>
<P>She will be greatly missed by her many friends in St. Johns.  There never will be another just like &quot;Minnie.&quot;</P>

