<HEAD><TITLE>The Bement Family</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pastel.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF0080">
<P>

<P><h3>The Bement Family</h3></P>
<P><h4><FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>
n 1873 Louisa Jane Huston Bement had joined the Ladies Library Association.  Soon her sister, Eliza Ann Hicks, and her children also joined.</P>
<P>The Huston sisters were born in Vermont and were the daughters of Matthew and Arabella Pierce Huston.  In 1850 the Huston family had moved to Michigan with eight children.  Four of the children died that year in DeWitt during an epidemic of black diphtheria.  That year one last child, Henry Boyd Huston, was born in DeWitt.</P>
<P>Eliza had married John Hicks in the Huston home in DeWitt on February 11, 1855.  Immediately following the wedding, the Huston family and their four remaining children moved to Gratiot County, near Ithaca.  </P>
<P>After the county seat was moved to Saint Johns, Eliza and John Hicks established the Hicks dry goods store in Saint Johns.  They lived in the house on the northwest corner of Walker and Brush Streets.  </P>
<P>In the meantime on March 6, 1856 Matthew Huston died.  Soon Arabella and her children, Louisa Jane, Lominda Arabella, and baby Henry Boyd Huston all moved to Saint Johns to live with John and Eliza Hicks.  The remaining son, David Thomas, stayed on the farm near Ithaca.  Later the Huston family moved across the street to 201 Brush Street.</P>
<P>Louisa Jane Huston married Edward Grilley Bement on June 21, 1861.  Their only child, Jennie Louise Bement, was born on April 5, 1868 at her grandmother's Brush Street house.</P>
<P>In 1872 John Hicks purchased property on State Street at Ottawa and built the family's permanent home.  When they moved into their new home, Grandmother Arabella accompanied the family.  By that time John and Eliza had three children, Ida Eliza who had been born in 1866, John Clayton who was born in 1869, and baby Jennie Marinda who had come along in 1871.</P>
<P>Soon Edward Bement established a store in Maple Rapids and moved his family there.  The family gathering place, however, was still at the Hicks home where Grandmother Arabella lived.</P>
<P>According to her niece, Ida Eliza Hicks Bishop, Louisa Jane Bement was a very energetic person and a good businesswoman.  She was graciously considerate of others; and as the years passed, her only daughter became the center of her life's interest.</P>
<P>Jennie Bement was seen by her cousin as gentle and thoughtful.  Her attractive personality, Ida said, was &quot;heartfully beloved by every member of the family.&quot;</P>
<P>&quot;She was 'at home' at 205 State Street,&quot; Ida continued.  &quot;Thus in speaking of her, I speak as one of our own family.&quot;</P>
<P>Edward Bement was said to have been especially book minded.  Thus it is not strange that his daughter was an unusually good student.  In 1886 Jennie graduated from Maple Rapids School.  At the age of 18 she had attended the University of Michigan.  </P>
<P>In 1889 she graduated from the State Normal School in Ypsilanti.  The next year she became the Preceptress of the high school in Sand Lake, Michigan.</P>
<P>In the summer of 1890 Jennie and her mother traveled in Europe.  Later that fall Jennie reentered the University of Michigan.  She graduated in 1892.  The following summer Jennie spent the months of August and September in Colorado.  </P>
<P>Jennie was engaged to marry.  Then in May, 1893 she contracted spinal meningitis and died.  Jennie died on May 31 and was buried from the Maple Rapids Christian Church on June 2, 1893.  She was later interred at Mount Rest Cemetery in Saint Johns.</P>
<P>It was then that Louisa Bement began planning a suitable memorial for Jennie.  She wanted, said cousin Ida, to think of something beautiful that would be in accord with Jennie's beautiful life.  Soon she settled on the idea of a library.</P>
<P>In 1938 Mrs. Bishop reminisced,  &quot;Frequently talking this consideration over with the members of our family, I recall one day telling Aunt Louise that I could think of nothing more befitting Cousin Jennie's life and character or more needed in Saint Johns.&quot;</P>
<P> Louisa Bement's will, executed in 1904, read in part:</P>
<P>I, Louisa J. Bement of Windsor, Ontario, Canada, being of sound mind and memory, do make, publish and declare this to be my last Will and Testament, in manner following, viz:</P>
<P>Sixth, I give and bequeath to the First Congregational Church of St. Johns, Michigan, the sum of Five Hundred Dollars to purchase a library for said church.  And I also give to the St. Johns Episcopal Church of St. Johns, Michigan the sum of Five Hundred Dollars with which to purchase a library for said church.</P>
<P>Tenth, I give, devise and bequeath all the residue and remainder of my estate to the City of St. Johns, Clinton County, Michigan, to establish a Public Library in said City, in whole or to assist therein.</P>
<P>I hereby appoint Charles M. Merrill, of St. Johns, Michigan Executor of this, My Last Will and testament.</P>
<P>In 1921 after bequests had been distributed to family members and other heirs, there was still $24,166.27 left to be placed in the &quot;Jennie Louise Bement Memorial&quot; fund. This fund was administered by Louisa's nephews, John C. Hicks and  Coleman C. Vaughn, who had married Jennie Marinda Hicks.</P>
<P>Over the years the family members discussed the question of when and where to build the Jennie Louise Bement Library.  Shortly before he died on April 10, 1935 John C. Hicks had visited with his sister, Ida, to consider once again the alternatives.  Both regretted that the government was considering the property at the corner of Brush and State Streets for the new post office.  John C. Hicks and Coleman Vaughn had previously purchased this lot for the erection of the desired Memorial Library.  By this time no one could recall what had happened to Jennie Bement's books which were to have been included in the library.</P>
<P>John C. Hicks was dead and Coleman C. Vaughn was away, so the fund was placed in trust with the National Bank.  Now that the prime site on State Street was no longer available, Ida Bishop hoped that the City of Saint Johns would try to purchase the lot at the corner of Brush and Walker, the site of the old &quot;St. Johns House&quot; hotel.  She wanted the Memorial Library to remain in the old neighborhood where the family had lived and where Jennie had been born.</P>
<P>In November of 1938 Schuyler Marshall, the editor of the &quot;Clinton County Republican-News&quot; wrote to Ida Bishop concerning the proposed new Municipal Building and Library building:</P>
<P>I hardly know how to approach the subject of your letter of November 7th.  It has been one which has caused discussion from time to time, often by people who had little knowledge of its background.  I have heard it discussed in times past by your brother and Mr. Vaughn.</P>
<P>Perhaps the best I can offer is a recital of my own limited knowledge and understanding of the bequest based upon what I have heard from others and my knowledge of present existing conditions.</P>
<P>To begin with, whatever the intentions of Mrs. Bement, the donor, may have been, the actual language of the paragraph in her will which transferred the money to the City of St. Johns for library purposes was very broad.  As I recall it, there were no explicit instructions as to how or where the money was to be spent so long as it was used for &quot;library purposes.&quot;</P>
<P>As time went on a very adequate library was established in the new high school building and a librarian employed.  The public are free to use this library and, if I recall rightly, some of the books of the now defunct Ladies' Library Association were transferred to the high school library.</P>
<P>More recently, increased municipal costs and the depression seemed to make it highly improbable that a separate and distinct building should, or would, be erected exclusively for library purposes as this would entail the cost of maintenance, the salary of a librarian, janitor and heating costs upon the city and would, in a measure, be a duplication of library facilities and expense which would not be warranted in so small a city as St. Johns.</P>
<P>Finally in recent months came consideration of the wisdom of combining in one building the library and much-needed city offices.  Mr. R.V. Gay, architect, whom you must remember as the son of Mr. and Mrs. Richard Gay and a local man, was engaged to submit plans.  Mr. Gay's plans called for a corner location with the entrance of the city offices on one street and a separate and suitable library entrance on the other street.  The plans also included, in addition to a large library room on the first floor, adjoining commodious rooms for women's clubs.</P>
<P>This plan was approved by the City Commission and application was made to the federal government for PWA funds to make such a building possible.  The approval by the government came recently and the matter of a site had to be settled in a relatively short time. </P>
<P>This week the city Commission purchased the site directly across the street from the Republican-News office, formerly known as the Fildew corner, and with it an adjoining building which was once the St. Johns News office, and at the time of purchase owned by the American Legion.  It is the plan to have the city office entrance on Walker street and the library entrance on Spring Street.</P>
<P>Because of its proximity to other city property and with economy of operation and maintenance in mind, it seemed to be the most practical and suitable for several reasons.</P>
<P>The old &quot;St. Johns House&quot; site was considered, but because of absentee ownership, because it involved two parcels of land; be cause of back taxes, mortgages, etc., it was impossible to acquire this property in time to satisfy the demands of the federal government.</P>
<P>After examining the plans for the new building and taking into consideration the ability of the city to carry on whatever they start, I am convinced that the best and most practical use has been made of the fund which was given by your aunt.</P>
<P>I realize that it does not offer the most as a memorial . . . at least, not as much as a building located separately on a plot of ample ground and landscaped . . . yet, it will be very serviceable and furnish library and club room facilities for many civic and cultural groups of women and a practical public library.</P>
<P>At home Eula has expressed gratification and a keen favorable anticipation of the use of the quarters which this money has made possible. I believe she voices the sentiment of a great many St. Johns women who have for years been without these facilities.</P>
<P>It had been 45 years between the time Jennie Bement died and the library her mother had hoped would be built in her memory was finally started.</P>

