<HEAD><TITLE>The Early Years of the Bement Library</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pastel.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF0080">
<P>

<P><h3>The Early Years of the Bement Library</h3></P>
<P><h4><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>
he first order of business for Minnie Barrington and the Library Board was the purchase of books.  One night in May, 1940 a Mr. Lindstrom driven by his black chauffeur, Mike, pulled up in front of the Library in his Car Library.  Lindstrom represented the Follette Book Company and was offering to sell anything in the car for 33% off the list price.  That evening the Board added 49 books to the Library's collection.</P>
<P>By July there were 381 patrons registered at the Library.  During that month 987 visitors withdrew 723 books from the Library's stock of 1919 volumes.  Meanwhile the Library Board had granted Miss Barrington two weeks vacation with pay, part of which was to be spent at a Library Convention in Mt. Pleasant.  </P>
<P>The Board also voted in July to purchase an electric fan for the Library.  For many years, summer and winter, that black metal table fan sat on the top of one of the low shelves in the northwest corner of the Library. </P>
<P>Miss Barrington first complained to the Board about the way the Library was overheating in the fall of 1941.  R.G. Benson was called in, and the Board paid to have the problem corrected.</P>
<P>The next winter Myron Ward, the Library Board's liaison with the City Commission, decided that he would see that the problem was taken care of.  This time he went down in person to see to it that the heating plant was repaired correctly.</P>
<P>In the winter of 1945 it was Rex Sirrine, the Library Board liaison with the City Commission, who took the problem in hand.  There was still a problem with the Library room overheating.</P>
<P>By the time Hila Bross had become Librarian the problem had developed a new twist. The old black fan had long since been retired.  Technological advances had made it possible to keep the Library cool summer and winter.  And every winter the Library would get so hot that the air conditioner would come on automatically.</P>
<P>Nearly every year someone new would try his hand at correcting the problem.  By 1972 the Librarian was complaining that the room was overheating - but only in the fall, winter, and spring.  This time Fraser MacKinnon, whose wife Barbara was a long-time member of the Library Board, suggested some corrective measures.  Mrs. Bross reported that the results were encouraging.</P>
<P>Early on the Bement Library Board had made contact with other libraries in the area.  In the spring of 1941 the Board hosted the District Convention in the new Municipal Auditorium.  Nina DeWitt was in charge of the dishes and tea service.  Cora Buck, Frank Buck's wife, was to set out the cookies and help serve coffee.  Teresa Merrill purchased the refreshments and presided over the tea table.  Everyone else was assigned to the reception committee.  Patrolman Reed Hall remained on duty and was reimbursed for his services.</P>
<P>Miss Barrington's first annual report disclosed that there were 2400 books in the library and that there had been a circulation of an average 51 books per day for a year end total of 14,791.  There were 915 registered patrons, and 1136 people had visited the Library during its first year of operation.  </P>
<P>There was a total of $1,450.60 in the treasury, and a bulletin board and new clock had been added to the Library.  A few months later the Board sent a letter to St. Clair Pardee thanking the American Legion for the new flag.</P>
<P>About six weeks after the bombing at Pearl Harbor had dragged the United States into war, the Library Board sponsored a campaign to collect books for the boys in the Service.  Containers were placed at Parr's Drug Store, the Smith Shopping Basket, and City Hall.  When the campaign was completed the City truck was sent out to deliver the books.</P>
<P>Asked by the editor of the Clinton County Republican-News what she thought about the war, Miss Barrington replied:</P>
<P>What do I think about the war?  I wish I could forget it.  It looks to me as if this is the start of a worldwide revolution that cannot be stopped short of its logical conclusion.  Eventually -- I have faith -- the world will reestablish a better civilization.  Oh, the hopeless old men, women and children trudging away from their wrecked homes.  Why hasn't our local Red Cross drive started?</P>
<P>The question arose in June of 1942 as to just what should be done with books which had been taken into homes in which someone was suffering from a contagious disease.  At that time the Board decided that there was nothing to do but ask the users to pay some or all of the cost of the book.  The Librarian was instructed to collect the best way she could.  Miss Barrington solved that problem by sending out  Reed Hall.  She found this also worked pretty well for recovering past due books.</P>
<P>Two years later the Board formalized the policy. The Health Department agreed to notify Miss Barrington of all quarantines, and no books were to be loaned out to homes until the quarantines had been lifted.  </P>
<P>The Library's 1942 share of the State Library Fund, $322.55, was used to purchase more books, increase the number of hours the Library was open, and to provide added services.  The City Commission was still funding the operation of the Library.  For that reason the Board denied a request that 15 or 20 books at a time be sent to Maple Rapids.</P>
<P>A $500 Series GD Bond was donated to the Library in the name of Alice Streeter in July, 1943.  The interest from the bond was to be placed in the Bement Fund, and for many years this money was used to purchase children's books.</P>
<P>Mrs. Edward Earhart donated books and book cases to the Library that September.  That same month the books and book cases from the Frank and Eva Spaulding Estate were also donated to the Library.</P>
<P>Then at the end of September, 1943 Nora Ball Wilson and Leah Fowler Hunt stepped forward.  For many years they had been the Trustees of the late Ladies Library Association.  The Library Board accepted with gratitude the $1335.17 which the women had held in trust for over forty years.</P>
<P>This money was invested in Treasury Bonds and placed in a safety deposit box at the National Bank in the name of the Bement Library.  Winifred Daboll was named custodian of the bonds.</P>
<P>Chinese Book Week was celebrated in April, 1944.  The displays were contributed by Drs. Foo and Ho and Mrs. Donovan Smith.  Miss Barrington reported that 538 adults and children had visited the display.</P>
<P>About that same time Eleanor Trask became ill.  Laurita Allison took over briefly as Assistant Librarian in her absence.  It was Elizabeth Millman, however, who joined Miss Barrington in attending the Library Conference at Higgins Lake that year.  The Library Board paid their expenses of $25.</P>
<P>Early in June the Library Board sent a bouquet of flowers to the ailing Frank Buck.  He died on June 16.  The next month Winifred Daboll was made the new chairman of the Board.  In September the City Commission appointed attorney Edward Fehling to succeed Mr.Buck.</P>
<P>The 1944 annual report indicated that in 1943 Bess Osgood had begun a story hour for the children, and the Library had displayed a creche at Christmas.  The Library was also beginning to cooperate with the local schools on the use of books.  </P>
<P>By the Christmas of 1944 the Library was closed from December 18-23 for its first redecoration.  The wall were being tinted.</P>
<P>Commissioner Rex Sirrine succeeded Myron Ward in January, 1945.  Six years later after Mr. Ward died, Mrs. R.V. Gay donated $10 to the Library.  A book was purchased in his memory.</P>
<P>In 1945 the Rev. Lewis Dion, pastor of St. Joseph Catholic Church, donated a large assortment of the latest Book of the Month Club selections.  The collection was worth $240.</P>
<P>General Spaulding in Washington donated a book entitled Real Soviet Russia by David J. Dallin.  Four other books were donated by Colonel Thomas M. Spaulding.</P>
<P>A picture map of Saint Johns as it had looked in 1868 was presented to the Library by Theodore Townsend.  It had come from a collection of pictures taken from the home of the late John Hicks.  Later Mrs. John Hicks and Ruth Jane LeBaron donated 67 books.</P>
<P>Circulation dipped slightly early in 1945 when libraries opened in each of the town's elementary schools.  Nevertheless the Board granted Miss Barrington a couple of extra vacation days so that she could take her annual blossom time tour of Michigan.</P>
<P>A special meeting of the Board was called on October 8, 1945.  At that time Winifred Daboll stepped down as chairman in favor of Edward Fehling.  It was also at this meeting that Elizabeth Millman was named the new Assistant Librarian.  The Board sent Laurita Allison a book in appreciation of her work at the Library. </P>
<P> A year later Miss Barrington's salary was raised from $800 a year to $1000.  Mrs. Millman was paid $.60 per hour.</P>
<P>The Soldiers Exhibit in the fall of 1945 brought 308 visitors into the Library.  Soon the Librarian warned the Board to choose war books sparingly.  Right then the market was flooded with books on the subject, and the quality of many of them was not up to Miss Barrington's high standards.</P>
<P>Library Board members included Edward Fehling, Winifred Daboll, Teresa Merrill, Nina DeWitt, and Commissioner Joe Matthews in 1947.  That spring the Board hosted a $1.25 per plate District Convention Luncheon at the Steel Hotel.  Mr. Kerns' high school music class entertained at an afternoon Tea held in the Library.</P>
<P>In the fall of 1947 high school principal Bennie Pocuis had asked Miss Barrington to instruct students in the use of the library.  She reported excellent participation on the part of that first group; and the project was continued for many years by her successors.</P>
<P>Minnie Barrington went on the radio in 1948.  She recounted a history of Clinton County over radio station WLS in Chicago.</P>
<P>By January of 1949 the Library's circulation was averaging 82.41 books per day, and $70.43 in fines had been collected.  There had been an excess of money in the budget in 1948, and the Board turned $50 back to the City.  Commissioner Dorr Anderson had replaced Joe Matthews on the Board.</P>
<P>The Morning Musicale donated the first phonograph records to the Library in the spring of 1949.  In order to accommodate the new medium the Board authorized Miss Barrington to spend $30 on the purchase of a display case and record player. </P>
<P>Minnie Barrington retired from the Library on July 1, 1950.  Elizabeth Millman was chosen to replace her as Librarian, and Laurita Allison was back on staff as Assistant Librarian.  </P>
<P>Laurita Murray Allison was a local girl.  Her family lived on South Clinton; and her father's bakery was located on East Walker Street, not far from the place where the Municipal Building would eventually stand.</P>
<P>After graduating from St. Johns High School, Laurita continued to work in the bakery until 1930.  She was married to C.W. Allison.</P>
<P>Mrs. Allison brought a quiet dignity to the Library.  She was restrained, almost shy, around strangers.  She did have, however, thoughts and opinions of her own.  When she did begin to express herself, she said exactly what needed to be said -- nothing more and nothing less.</P>
<P>Laurita was a tiny, dark woman; and she was always chilly.  Summer and winter a sweater hung on the back of her chair at the table next to the office.  The advent of air conditioning in the Library would have brought her agony.  Secretly she probably appreciated the constant overheating to which the Library was subject every winter.</P>
<P>In the fall of 1950 Mrs. Allison's hours were increased from 18 to 21 hours per week at $.68 per hour.  At the same time instead of being open from 2 p.m. to 4 p.m. on Tuesdays and Fridays, Library hours were extended from 2 p.m. to 5 p.m. on those days.  </P>
<P>Board members Buelah Ballantine, who had succeeded Winifred Daboll, and Nina DeWitt were asked to help the Librarian in the selection and purchase of books.  The next January Commissioner Charles Coletta took a seat on the Board, replacing Dorr Anderson.</P>
<P>Elizabeth Millman introduced the concept of a rental library to the Board in the Spring of 1951.  At the time there were 8,000 volumes in the Library, and Mrs. Millman explained that the rental system might be a good way to keep popular books in circulation without a large investment in money or space.  A few months later the Board voted to try out the American Lending Library for a short period of time.  The average cost of the service turned out to be about $.18 per book withdrawn from the local Library.</P>
<P>In June, 1952 Mrs. Millman announced the beginning of the first Summer Reading Club.  There also was a story hour on Tuesday and Thursday mornings from 10-11.  The story hour was sponsored by the Child Study Club.  There were three winners of the book report awards that year.  Brooks Jones received a prize of $2 for first place.  Cathy Jopke and Kay B. Munro each won $1.</P>
<P>In her annual report Mrs. Millman noted that there had been 287 books purchased, 82 donated, and 7944 books in circulation throughout the year 1951.  Of these, 13 had been lost.  Of the 26,552 books which had been withdrawn that year 10% had been non-fiction, 43% were fiction, 39% were children's books; and periodicals represented only 8% of total circulation.  Of the 1952 registered patrons, 1475 were adults and 477 were children.</P>
<P>During that year Mrs. Joseph Gasser had been hired as an assistant.  Rigoletto had been added to the record collection.  And Mrs. Millman's &quot;Book Shelf&quot; column had been appearing almost weekly in the Clinton County Republican-News.</P>
<P>During the years that she wrote her newspaper column Mrs. Millman received personal notes from several authors.  In April, 1964 author David Westheimer wrote: &quot;Many thanks for your kind review of Von Ryan's Express.  I am always especially pleased when a lady reader likes the book.&quot;</P>
<P>A note from Norwalk, Connecticut said, &quot;I do thank you for the mention of the Lonely Man on July 24 -.&quot;  It was signed &quot;Faith Baldwin.&quot;</P>
<P>Mrs. Millman and Mrs. Allison reported to the Board in November, 1952 on the Michigan Library Association Convention they had recently attended.  The speaker had been Norman Cousins, and his topic had been Adult Education.</P>
<P>At that same meeting the Board voted to change its policy regarding rental books.  From then on patrons would be entitled to the first three days free.  They would be charged 5 cents for each day they kept the book beyond the first three days.</P>
<P>The Library was closed in February, 1953 for its second redecorating.  In April it was closed again for four days for varnishing.</P>
<P>A year later in February of 1954 the City Commission offered to lend the room vacated by Justice of the Peace Charles A. Speer to the Library.  The new room was to be used as a Children's Library and was to open May 1, 1954.</P>
<P>That summer a teacher, Miss Evelyn Putnam, and Mrs. Ethel Clark offered to take charge of the Story Hour.  Student helpers assisted in the children's room.  Each year a senior girl was selected for this job.  At first high school credit was given from the vocational training program, and the student was able to leave school one hour early.  This program was later abandoned.  Beginning in 1960 credit was no longer given, but the student was dismissed early.</P>
<P>THE CHILDREN'S LIBRARY</P>
<P> Sherri Mitchell became the first in a long succession of high school girls to take charge of the Children's Library.  Others included:</P>
<P>Caroline Gasser     1954-55</P>
<P>Rosalie Fink  1955-56</P>
<P>Janice Gasser  1956-57</P>
<P>Felice King  1957-58</P>
<P>Maralyn Fink  1958-59</P>
<P>Nancy Gaskill  1959-60</P>
<P>Jean Robinson  1960-61</P>
<P>Susan Wirick  1961-62</P>
<P>Gladys Motz  1962-63</P>
<P>Lynda Stephenson 1963-64</P>
<P>Molly Sapp  1964-65</P>
<P>Robyn Hudson  1965-66</P>
<P>The Children's Library was open from 3 p.m. - 5 p.m. weekdays and  1 - 5 p.m. on Saturdays during the school year.  Summer hours were 1 - 5 p.m. daily, Monday through Saturday.  These hours were the same as the open swimming hours at the city park pool; and on opening day at the pool and on especially nice summer days, business was slow. </P>
<P>The routine was invariable.  The student librarian threw her books from her last class into her locker, grabbed a coat, and bolted for the front door of Rodney B. Wilson High School.  She could save a few seconds if she used the well-worn path across the grass on the courthouse lawn.  On the coldest days it was always a relief to walk under the outdoor heater at the National Bank's walk-up window on East Walker.  On sunny days the radiometer in the window of the Police station would be spinning.</P>
<P>There was a quick trip through the south door of the Municipal Building and on into the Library to check in and pick up the tarnished key from the ladies in the main library.  If the girl should happen to be a few minutes late, she was met with silent disapproval.</P>
<P>Retracing her steps through the Municipal Building, she would return to the main stairway, race on past the public rest rooms, and carefully turn the key in the reluctant lock.  Flipping on the light switches at the left of the doorway, she would head straight towards the east well windows in search of oxygen for the stuffy little room.  In the summer the room was pleasantly cool but dank.</P>
<P>Quickly she would pick up from her desk any books which might have been returned overnight.  If luck were on her side, she could have the cards back in them and have them reshelved before the afternoon's hord of cherubs descended.  Otherwise some of those books would go right home with the little ones without having the original cards replaced.  This not only left no accounting of the book's whereabouts; it messed up the circulation count.  This was to be avoided at all cost.</P>
<P>Then the afternoon began.  If it were a rainy day, there would be large numbers of noisy, good-natured children hanging around the library all afternoon.  </P>
<P>One little boy, the son of sober and high-minded school teachers, was a constant companion to the librarian.  His parents were edified by his frequent trips to the public library and never guessed that he spent his days happily devouring all of the comic books he was not allowed to read at home.</P>
<P>If it happened to be opening day at the Veterans Memorial Pool, the librarian could plan a relaxing afternoon of dusting shelves.  The children's shelves were no problem because little hands passed over them so frequently that the dust rarely had time to settle.  </P>
<P>The storage shelves on the north wall were another matter.  These contained many wonderful old novels and history books.  One especially grimy and fascinating set included photos taken during World War I.  All of the cutlines and the entire text were in German - and not only German, but fractur at that. Reading these was surely more fun than dusting, but there had to be easier ways to learn German.</P>
<P>Student librarians were forbidden to eat on the job.  One such girl nearly starved to death while reading The Good Earth one sunny Saturday afternoon.  Upon arriving home she startled her poor mother by practically demanding that she cook up a rice dish for supper that night.</P>
<P> Wildlife abounded in the basement of the Municipal Building.  All sorts of bugs and rodents were especially attracted to the floor of the Children's Library where peanuts occasionally dropped from contraband candy smuggled in by young readers.  One wily mouse had been eluding both the student librarian and the janitor, Howard Castler, for quite some time.  </P>
<P>Day after day conventional mouse traps stood vacant.  Chewed up papers could be seen on the floor, but the mouse himself remained invisible.  Then one evening he made the mistake of running across the floor just as Laurita Allison made an unscheduled visit to the room.</P>
<P>From then on the word was out.  Get that mouse!  The crafty student librarian set out to capture the beast herself.  Carefully she smeared bits of a Baby Ruth bar in front of her desk.  Then she added a couple of pieces of broken peanut just for effect. The door was closed, and the lights were turned off.  Then the librarian returned to her desk to wait.</P>
<P> Eventually the creature scuttled across the floor towards the candy.  Wham!  Before he knew what had hit him, he found himself in total darkness - under the wastebasket.</P>
<P>&quot;Now what?&quot; thought the captor.  Placing several heavy books on top of the wastebasket, she ran to fetch the janitor.  He would have to do the dirty work.  Howard promptly removed the mouse but never would say exactly what had happened to it.  One rumor around the Municipal Building had it that Chief Everett Glazier had taken the poor animal out and shot it with his service revolver.</P>
<P>Chief Glazier was among the many adults who frequented the Children's Library on their way to the boiler room to have a smoke.  Each day, some times several times a day, these men would pass by the library and poke their heads in to say hello or to tell a story or two.  </P>
<P>Sometimes the librarian smiled and sometimes she cringed.  Often she learned to tell the visitors apart by the sound of their footfalls in the corridor.  If she expected one of her more tiresome visitors, she could always be straightening shelves on the far wall.  And if she happened to recognize one of the ladies from upstairs - why, she could always be found dusting those eternal storage shelves.</P>
<P>At closing time the ritual reversed itself.  Children were encouraged to leave by 4:55.  This gave the librarian a few minutes to pick up things and alphabetize the day's cards.  This was especially important on the evenings when the upstairs library would be open.  For then, especially if everything were not in order, someone would be sure to bring down a child during evening library hours.  And the next day the student would be greeted with those silent looks of disapproval.</P>
<P>A running tally of circulation from the children's section was kept daily by the librarians in the main library.  These women were always ready to close at 5 p.m. on the dot and were frequently impatient if a last minute rush should keep the student assistant from closing and reporting in on time.</P>
<P>Rural school teachers were frequent clients of the Children's Library.  Since many schools were located in the outlying areas, teachers often arrived late in the afternoon.  Several teachers could be counted upon to arrive about five minutes before closing time.  Of course they would select as many as 20 or 30 books to take back to their students; and the women in the main library would be circling around the south door of the darkened room, waiting.</P>
<P>The cards counted and alphabetized, the windows would have to be closed.  If that were not done, there would surely be some sort of monsoon that would strike the town overnight.  Then the window wells would flood, and it would be all over for the poor librarian.  </P>
<P>Finally the lights were switched off, and the door lock was coaxed closed.  This was accomplished by holding ones face in just the proper expression while the key was turning in the lock.</P>
<P>Upon returning the key the student would be greeted with a smile from Mrs. Millman and quiet acceptance from Mrs. Allison.  Or if things were not going according to schedule, there would be that deafening silence.</P>
<P>Regularly there would be a paycheck.  At Christmas and Easter there was a turkey or a ham from the City.</P>
<P>Another thing student librarians had to remember was that they always had a ride home.  It didn't matter if the girl had to hurry down the street and wait for a few minutes in her mother's empty office.  She had a ride home.  Otherwise Mrs. Millman would insist upon driving her.  </P>
<P>Mrs. Millman was the type of driver who could talk, or she could drive.  And although she should have been driving, she frequently preferred to talk.  She also firmly believed that the new &quot;Yield&quot; signs that were appearing on side streets meant &quot;Look straight ahead and gun it.&quot;  Yes, the experienced student always had a ride home.</P>
<P>In 1957 the Library Board gave Jan Gasser $5 for her high school graduation.  Twenty years later Sharri Desprez received a nice little bracelet charm.  Others had not been so fortunate.  One graduating senior had nearly bolted from her own party in embarrassment when, in front of all of her guests, she opened her gift from the Library Board and found silky little baby doll pajamas. </P>
<P>Late in 1965 Mrs. Millman's successor, Hila Bross, began making plans for improving the Children's Library.  Stickers were pasted onto the cover of children's books reminding parents that destroying books was punishable by law.  </P>
<P>Limits were imposed upon rural teachers regarding the number of books they could check out at one time and the length of time they could keep the books.  Each child in that teacher's room had to be registered at the library in order for the teacher to take books back to her class.  Walter Nickel called to say that his rural teachers were unhappy, but the Board upheld the new policies.</P>
<P>Red, white, and blue were chosen for the new color scheme.  The blue carpet came from St. Johns Furniture.  Mrs. Bross asked the city to paint the walls.  Sheer white curtains were to replace the Venetian blinds.  Later Hila had the old carpet from the children's library cut up for runners in the main library.</P>
<P>Beginning on November 6, 1967 Cleo Desprez took over as the Children's Librarian.  A former teacher, Mrs. Desprez had joined the staff in July of that year.  </P>
<P>One day she had been talking with Elizabeth Millman in Glaspie's Drug Store.  When Mrs. Millman offered her the job of Assistant Librarian, Cleo knew just what she wanted to do.</P>
<P>&quot;I guess I've always liked children,&quot; Cleo told a reporter for the Clinton County News.  &quot;For me library work is the next thing to teaching school.&quot;</P>
<P>Less than two years later financial constraints forced the Board to have the Children's Library moved back upstairs.  </P>
<P>There simply was not enough money available to pay someone to be in the basement all of the time.  Literature and biographies were placed in the basement room, and the Children's corner was again located on the first floor.</P>
<P>When she retired in 1981, Cleo Desprez recalled that she especially had hated to see the passing of the basement Children's Library that she and Hila had so carefully decorated.</P>
<P>&quot;Room is the whole thing,&quot; Cleo declared.  &quot;Hila's dream was to have our own library building.&quot;</P>
<P>1956-1980, YEARS OF RAPID EXPANSION</P>
<P>It was Saint Johns' Centennial year; and Library circulation in 1956 totaled 24,495 with 2069 adults and 701 children registered.</P>
<P>The next year the face of the Library Board began changing.  John Bond came on to represent the City Commission.  Then on August 10, 1957 former Board Chairman Edward W. Fehling died.  For some time before his retirement the Board had been meeting in his office.  After his retirement Fehling had spent many hours in the Library at the magazine table.  His special interests were travel and history, and the women in the Library began to await his comments about the stories he had read or the trips he had taken.  The Board purchased a subscription to the American Heritage Magazine in his memory.</P>
<P>Former Commission representative to the Board, Joe Matthews, replaced Fehling.  The new 1957 Board officers consisted of Nina DeWitt, Chairman and Joe Matthews, Vice Chairman. Teresa Merrill was still Secretary.</P>
<P>Elizabeth Millman completed her college courses at Central State College and received State Library Board certification late in 1958.  The Library Board had paid for half of the cost of the courses.</P>
<P>That same year the Library received yet another facelift.  Walls were painted, and a couple of years later new lights were installed.  Now readers would enjoy 50 candle power instead of the original nine over each table. </P>
<P>In 1974 this lighting arrangement was adjusted downward.  The reduction resulted in a 33% cut in the use of electricity in the main Library room.</P>
<P>Joseph G. Matthews died on January 18, 1962 in Holmes Beach, Florida.  The January 22 Board meeting had been a somber one.  The Board met briefly after returning from the funeral.  The only motion that was passed that day was a resolution to place a book in the Library in his memory.  A few months later Basil Deibert was chosen to replace Mr. Matthews.</P>
<P>In the meantime new staff members were being added to the Library.  Mrs. Dunkel began to work 8 hours per week.  Mrs. Walter Nickel was made an assistant, and Mrs. Welch was hired as extra help.  Later that summer Virginia Dietrich came on staff and began serving as clerk.  Mrs. Beatrice Cook conducted the summer story hour.</P>
<P>Because of the rules and regulations that accompanied the City's insurance plan, Mrs. Millman was forced to retire automatically after her 65th birthday in the spring of 1965.  The Library board went on record as saying that they hoped that the rules might be suspended so that Mrs. Millman could be reinstated.  They were not, and the Open House that was held on Sunday April 25, 1965 coincided with the Silver Anniversary of the Bement Library.  </P>
<P> The next year Mrs. Harold Millman was the guest of honor at a reception held in her honor during Library Week.  Girl Scout Cadet Troop 429, lead by Mrs. Gail Goetze, armed themselves with cloths and soapy water to clean the Library in preparation for the event.  Diane Kanaski, Patricia Mabie, Karen Kohls, Jane Thrush, Sandra Bovee, Mary Lou LeFever, Christin Idzkowski, Joanne Kanaski, and Mary Ann Kanaski scrubbed for about three hours to finish this community service project.</P>
<P> A photograph of Mrs. Millman was presented to her by Library Board Treasurer Beulah Ballantine and by Mrs. Manning Bross.  The picture was hung in the Library beneath that of her predecessor, Minnie Barrington.</P>
