<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>The Ladies Library Association</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pastel.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF0080">
<P>

<P><h3>The Ladies Library Association</h3></P>
<P><h4><FONT SIZE=+2>S</FONT>aint Johns was not yet 15 years old when Mary Strickland offered to let the Ladies Library Association use a room in her home for their first library.  Across Linden Avenue the county courthouse stood partially built on the village green.</P>
<P>In those early years merchants, attorneys, physicians, and clergymen had moved their families into the village.  These men usually had their daily employment to provide a sense of accomplishment and companionship.  At the same time their wives, many of whom were well educated and accomplished young women, found little opportunity to improve themselves in this alternately muddy and dusty little town.</P>
<P>Then shortly before the end of the Civil War, the State Legislature passed an act which provided for the &quot;formation of corporations for Library and scientific purposes.&quot;  A few years later ten Saint Johns women decided to take advantage of the new legislation.   </P>
<P>Early in 1870 Mrs. George W. Tuthill, Mrs. Marvin Babcock, Mrs. Robert McFarlan, Mrs. Samuel S. Walker, Miss Frances E. Tuckerman, Mrs. John B. McLean, Mrs. H. M. Lee, Mrs. C.S. Wells, Celia C. Smith, and Mrs. James H. Collins joined to form a corporation named the &quot;Ladies Library Association of Saint Johns, Michigan.&quot;  Under the terms of the law the association would be incorporated for a term of thirty years.  After that time, any and all assets were to be distributed to some organization in the area having a similar purpose.</P>
<P>The plan, as outlined in the February 3, 1870 issue of the &quot;Clinton Independent,&quot; was to purchase books with the annual fees collected from the members.  These books were to be selected to meet the needs of all ages. Of course there would be &quot;works of History, Travel, Science, Art and Fiction of an elevating and healthful order.&quot;  The extent of the library would naturally depend upon the number of its members.  Donations of books of &quot;merit and interest&quot; were gratefully received.  It was expected that the library would be ready for circulation within the next two weeks.</P>
<P>The Association was managed by ten directors who were chosen from among the active membership.  Officers included a President, Vice President, Secretary, Treasurer, Librarian and Assistant Librarian.</P>
<P>The first officers of the Association included:</P>
<P>President - Mrs. Randolph Strickland</P>
<P>Vice President - Mrs. L.W. Earl</P>
<P>Secretary - Mrs. J. L. Paldi</P>
<P>Treasurer - Mrs. J. Wilkinson</P>
<P>Librarian - Mrs. J. H. Cranson</P>
<P>Assistant Librarian - Miss M. Paine.</P>
<P>On the Executive Board were:  Mrs. Strickland, Mrs. Cranson, Mrs. Walker, Mrs. Paldi, Mrs. Tuthill, Mrs. McFarlan, and Mrs. McLean.</P>
<P>Each year the Association published a little directory.  Ten years later, in 1880, the officers were:</P>
<P>President - Mrs. Marvin Babcock     </P>
<P>Vice President - Mrs. R. Strickland</P>
<P>Secretary - Mrs. S. S. Walker</P>
<P>Treasurer - Miss Frances Tuckerman</P>
<P>Librarian - Mrs. C. E. Ball</P>
<P>Assistant Librarian - Miss C. Shaver</P>
<P>Other members of the Association in 1880 included Mrs. G.E. Corbin, Mrs. S. S. Woodruff, Mrs. C.E. Grisson, and Mrs. Jesse Dunn.</P>
<P>It is interesting to note that the first names of many of these intelligent and well-read women would be lost completely were it not for census data taken throughout the years.  Local contemporary histories frequently made mention of the husbands and fathers of these women and carefully noted their achievements.  Rarely, however, were the accomplishments of their wives and daughters recounted.</P>
<P>The first President of the Ladies Library Association, Mary E. Strickland, was 41 years old in 1870.  She was married to a local attorney, Randolph Strickland.  Five years after the county seat was removed to Saint Johns, the family had moved from their home on the banks of the Looking Glass River in DeWitt.  </P>
<P>Shortly after coming to Saint Johns the family purchased and improved the residence of Dr. Crawford.  This Italianate structure was the first brick residence built in Saint Johns and stood at the corner of Linden Avenue and Cass Street.  In 1907, after the death of Mary Strickland in 1905, the stately old building was razed to make way for the construction of the second St. Joseph Catholic Church building.</P>
<P>The Stricklands raised four daughters, each of whom was said to be both charming and accomplished.  All were educated at the University of Michigan, known at the time as the Michigan University in Ann Arbor.  Martha, the eldest, studied law, married a man named Sheldon C. Clark and moved to Rockford, Illinois where she later taught parliamentary law.  Alida, later Mrs. W.H. Eastman, was the head of a private school in Grand Rapids.  Jessie was the musical one of the family.  She married Dr. Herman Ostrander of Lansing and died at a relatively young age.  Hattie married J.E. Allaban and also moved to Rockford, Illinois.</P>
<P>  Mary Strickland's husband was at one time or another a U.S. Congressman and a State Legislator.  Owing to his many political interests, Strickland was often absent from Saint Johns.  These absences seem to have given Mary the freedom to pursue her own cultural interests.  Besides providing the Ladies Library Association with their first rooms, she was also an enthusiastic member of the local ladies' Reading Circle, out of which later grew the Ladies Literary Club.  </P>
<P>In their old Linden Avenue home the Stricklands gathered around them the most intellectual people of their day and often, it is said, entertained speakers of nations reputation.  Perhaps Mary Strickland was best remembered by her contemporaries as an exceptional hostess.  She was especially noted for the balls and parties she gave.  </P>
<P>In 1906 Arvilla Hunt, whose husband was the druggist A.O. Hunt, described a gown she had made for one such occasion.  </P>
<P>It was of yellow and blue changeable silk, made with immense sleeves, a full skirt to accommodate the large hoops, the neck slightly low.  Her hair was dressed in the prevailing fashion then, parted in the middle and combed low over the ears with a huge back comb.  Of course the fan, scarf and huge poke bonnet were not lacking.</P>
<P>The dances always took place in the large room back of Mr. Strickland's study.  This room extended the entire width of the house.</P>
<P>  It was this room, too, which doubtless served as the village's first library.</P>
<P>Mary W. Babcock was 48 years old when she helped found the Ladies Library Association.  She had been born in Vermont but had moved to Livingston County, Michigan in 1835.  She studied on her own until the age of 15 when she began teaching.  She was able to teach until her mother died.  Then she had to assume the responsibility of managing her father's household until he married for a second time.  </P>
<P>When she was 19 years old, Mary married Marvin Babcock.  For a time her husband had been a peddler and engaged in many speculative endeavors including following the Gold Rush to California.  Finally he began selling jewelry in Saint Johns and eventually became a successful merchant.  </P>
<P>While her husband had been a Spiritualist who published a number of tracts outlining his views on religion, Mary was noted around town for her work in temperance and church societies.  The Ladies Literary Society was founded in her home, and she served as its president for 14 years.</P>
<P>Anna Tuthill was married to the Congregational minister, the Rev. George M. Tuthill.  She had been 44 years old when the Association was founded.  She and her family left Saint Johns in 1872 when another minister took over the pulpit.</P>
<P>Sarah McFarlan was 45 years old when the Association was founded.  She had been born in Connecticut and was married to Robert McFarlan, who owned a hardware store.</P>
<P>Elizabeth Lee was 39 in 1870.  She had been born in Canada.  Her husband Henry, who had been born in Missouri, was a hotel keeper.</P>
<P>Roxy Paldi was 27 years old when she became the Association's first secretary.  Her husband, Justin, was a civil engineer and secretary of the Board of Directors for St. Johns Manufacturing, the table factory.</P>
<P>Elizabeth Wells was 28 years old at the time.  She had just  married Charles, a boot and shoe merchant, in January, 1870.  To make ends meet they were also using their home as a boarding house.</P>
<P>Minerva Walker was only 25 when she helped found the Ladies Library Association.  At the time she and her husband, Samuel, had two girls, Susie who was 5 and Eloise who was still an infant.</P>
<P>Eliza Dunn was 28 and married to a dry goods merchant, Jesse Dunn.  She also had two young children, Edith, 5 and a baby, Gertrude.</P>
<P>Mrs. James B. McLean was a newlywed, just recently married to the Register of Deeds.</P>
<P>Hattie Collins was 22 years old and a newlywed as well.  Five years later her husband, James, would become the Village Clerk. In 1880 he was the Undersheriff.</P>
<P>Celia C. Smith was 21 the year that the first library opened.  Her father was a farmer, and like most unmarried women she was described in the 1870 census as being &quot;at home.&quot;  Her married friends were all busy &quot;keeping house.&quot;</P>
<P>One member of the Ladies Library Association was neither at home nor was she keeping house.  Miss Frances Tuckerman, 40, worked as a dry goods merchant herself and boarded with the family of barber, Samuel Davis.</P>
<P>There were three degrees of membership in the Ladies Library Association.  Any woman could become an Active member through the payment of a one-time-only initiation fee of $1.  Only Active members had the right to vote and hold office.  An additional annual fee of $1.00 was charged for the privilege of drawing books from the library.  </P>
<P>In another class were the Honorary members.  Any gentleman could become an Honorary member by the payment of the $1.00  initiation fee.  Men of course had no voting rights but could draw books from the library upon payment of the $1.00 annual fee.</P>
<P>Still another membership option was the Juvenile membership.  Any youth under the age of 15 could become a member by the payment of 50 cents initiation fee and $1.00 per year for the use of the library.  This user fee was payable in advance in quarterly installments of 25 cents during the months of March, June, September, and December.  In early publicity the founders of the Association explained that the fees for use of the library had been set artificially low so that any members of the community could avail themselves of the library's services.</P>
<P>Upon attaining the age of 15 any girl could become an Active member.  Boys of that age, however, were forever relegated to the lesser status of mere Honorary membership.</P>
<P>A few years later the By-Laws of the Association were amended.  Members moving from the village and those on brief vacations could transfer to another in writing their right to draw books from the library for the remainder of the time they had paid for.  Memberships, however, were not transferable.</P>
<P>A ledger was maintained in the library.  Each member's name was entered in the ledger.  All books were given a code number; and each month when the member withdrew a book from the library, the code number was entered in the ledger on the line containing the member's name.</P>
<P>No more than one book could be withdrawn from the library at  a time.  Exceptions to this rule could be made only by the Executive Board.  Each book was to be checked out of the library for a period of two weeks.  Books held beyond that time were subject to a whopping fine of 10 cents per week.  The Library was to be open every Saturday from 3 until 5 p.m. during the winter months and from 4 until 6 p.m. in the summer.</P>
<P>During the Centennial year of 1876 library hours were expanded to Wednesdays and Saturdays during the same time periods.  The library was staffed by Association members on Wednesday afternoons and by the librarian on Saturdays.  </P>
<P>In March of 1876 the Association contracted with Orrin Munger for the front room of his building located on the west side of Clinton Avenue.  The Association agreed to pay him the sum of $75 per year for at least five years.  </P>
<P>At once members of the Association recognized the need for more storage space, and Mr. Munger allowed them to build a closet in the room.  Carpet for the new library was obtained at a good price from Mr. Dunn's store.</P>
<P>In May, 1876 the Association moved the library into its new quarters.  The next month they celebrated the opening of the new library rooms with an ice cream social.</P>
<P>In August a new catalog of books available to members was printed.   A month later on Friday evening, September 22 the Ladies Library Association proudly sponsored the first &quot;hop&quot; of the social season.  There were also a number of somewhat regular &quot;entertainments&quot; which followed throughout the winter and early spring months.  These evenings often featured local musical groups.</P>
<P>Later that same fall the members planned an Author's Carnival.  That year the ladies donned costumes and performed scenes from Mark Twain's Tom Sawyer.</P>
<P>In February of 1878 a member of the Association, Huldah Richards, was able to prevail upon her husband, the local Presbyterian minister, to give a lecture for the benefit of the Association.  The Reverend Jonathan E. Richards was a graduate of Yale College and was said to be well known throughout Michigan as a fine speaker.  Admission to the event was to be 25 cents.</P>
<P>The lecture seems to have been a huge success, clearing about $30 for the Association.  From their share of the proceeds the members purchased a step ladder, and poker, shovel and standard for the library rooms.  They also hoped to purchase an additional one dozen chairs, four of them arm chairs.  The price of the furniture would amount to $23.  </P>
<P>On February 26 of the same year another &quot;hop&quot; was held in rooms donated by Mr. Judd.  Perhaps embarrassed by the financial success of their recent enterprises, the members of the Association considered offering the Reverend Richards half of the purse, $15.  Just in case he should refuse their offer, however, members had already determined that they would use the money to purchase their new chairs.  In a further burst of gratitude the Association conferred Honorary membership for life upon both Mr. Judd and Mr. Richards.</P>
<P>The next spring members of the Association decided to hire a girl to clean the library rooms.  It was noted that special attention should be paid to the wall around the stove pipe.</P>
<P>In later years it would appear that it became harder and harder to find active members who were willing to spend the time needed to administer the library.  A number of other cultural organizations within the village began competing for the time and interest of the local women.  These included the Ladies Literary Club and the St. Johns Woman's Association.</P>
<P>As it became harder to gather members for the Association's March annual meeting, other organizations began to use the library rooms for their social events.  In April of 1899 a masquerade social was held there.  Six months later this same group held one of the ever popular milk and mush socials.  This was to be followed by a coon hunt.</P>
<P>In 1875 there had been 152 members who withdrew books from the library.  At the time the charter was due to expire in 1900 there were still 109 names inscribed on the ledger of the Ladies Library Association.  </P>
<P>When the Association was disbanded, two trustees were named to hold the money in trust for some other library purposes.  Many of the books were donated to the high school library at the Union School which was by then coming to be known as the Central building.</P></B>
