<HEAD><TITLE>The Next 25 Years Begin</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pastel.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF0080">
<P>

<P><h3>The Next 25 Years Begin</h3></P>
<P><h4><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>
s the Library Board prepared to celebrate the Bement's 25th anniversary, they were looking to  expand.  Plans to use the upper and main floors of the firehall were under discussion. Still no definite decisions had been made, and no timetable had been set.</P>
<P>As she prepared to leave the Library, Elizabeth Millman recalled:</P>
<P>Originally the library was mostly a reading library.  But now a majority come from the school-age group, and the library has become more and more a study hall, both after school and on the evenings it is open.</P>
<P>Students of high school and the elementary schools flock in to gather material for lesson assignments.  Teachers now-a-days are asking for more and more outside reference material to augment the extbooks.</P>
<P>I have enjoyed every minute of my years as librarian.  I have always loved to read, and have been able to pursue that hobby to my heart's content during my years here.  Keeping up with the latest in books has kept me young, so that I really didn't believe it when they told me I had reached retirement age.</P>
<P>Librarianship as a career is most rewarding.  I should like to see many more young people take it up.  Libraries are becoming more and more important in the educational world, and there is a great need for trained library personnel.</P>
<P>Being in a softened and forgiving mood due to our age, we are giving you a chance to return any . . . forgotten books fine-free during the Silver Anniversary Week.  </P>
<P>This is your opportunity to ease your conscience with no pain to your pocket book.  Bring back those overdue books this week!</P>
<P>The Library had always subscribed to a number of periodicals and to the Reader's Guide and Periodicals Index.  A recent federal grant to libraries was currently supplying all of the periodicals listed by the Reader's Guide, so the Library's supply had increased greatly in number and variety.</P>
<P>Hila Bross was named the new librarian.  Hila's grandfather, the Rev. G.S. Northrup, had been the Baptist preacher in Saint Johns at the time of the Union School fire in 1885.  He was recalled to Saint Johns again just after the turn of the Century.</P>
<P>Two of Hila's aunts on her father's side had been teachers but had drifted into show business.  When Hila Axtell was eight years old, her family began ten years of traveling with the Hila Morgan Stock Company and the Monroe Hopkins Players throughout Iowa, Arkansas, Mississippi, Louisiana and Texas.  </P>
<P>Hila and her sisters did manage to get some education along the way.  Mildred Axtell Countryman attended Western State College and became a school librarian and music teacher.  Mildred had met and married another show business trouper, Floyd Countryman.  Their only daughter, Virginia, married Kenneth Jack Dietrich in 1955.</P>
<P>Hila attended boarding schools until she came to Saint Johns to live with the Northrups in 1926.  She graduated from St. Johns High School in 1929.  College had to wait, so she worked for the &quot;Clinton County Republican-News&quot; and the J.C. Penney Store.  Later Hila attended Michigan State University and Jackson Business University.</P>
<P>In 1953 Hila and her husband, Dr. H. Manning Bross, opened a restaurant in their home at French's Corners, north of Saint Johns.  She called the place the Salt Box House after the architectural style of the structure.</P>
<P>Hila was a cultured and intelligent woman.  Her early show business associations seemed to have given her an added flair that made her style a welcome addition to the somewhat literal atmosphere of conservative Saint Johns.  She brought to her new position both a sense of good taste and a willingness to innovate.</P>
<P>Teresa Merrill retired from the Library Board in July, 1965.  She was replaced by Mrs. Robert L. Wohlers.  Nina DeWitt retired in September.  The next month Mrs. Ladd Bartholomew joined the Board.  The new leadership included Basil Deibert, Chairman; Beulah Ballantine, Treasurer; and Jean Mary Bartholomew, replacing Teresa Merrill as Secretary.  Jack Smit represented the City Commission on the Board.</P>
<P>Immediately after coming into the Library as its Librarian, Hila Bross proposed that Library hours be extended.  She wanted the Library to be open from 12-5 daily and also from 7-9 on Tuesdays and Fridays for a total of 34 hours per week.</P>
<P>The new Library Board appointments and Library hours were both announced in a newspaper article in October.  &quot;The board emphasized that students are not allowed to bring their lunches into the library during the noon hour,&quot; the article concluded.</P>
<P>&quot;Don't Be a Book Hog&quot; was the theme Librarian Hila Bross used one year in an effort to get overdue books back to the library.  In honor of Groundhog Day, February 2, the Library suspended book fines for books returned on that day.</P>
<P>For some time a separate library system had been developing behind and beneath the big old wooden circulation desk.  Favored patrons and Library Board members could ask to have certain books, usually the latest best-sellers, held &quot;down under the counter&quot; for them.  A new Board policy was promulgated in October of 1965.  From then on books could be kept down under the counter for no more than 24 hours. After that the coveted volumes had to be returned to general circulation.</P>
<P>As time went on the Bement Library, like many small libraries, had neither the space nor the resources to meet the increasing demand for new and more varied reading materials.  In 1966 the Board agreed to join the Ingham County Library System for one year.  This membership also entitled Saint Johns residents who were interested to apply for cards to the Lansing Public Library. </P>
<P>The next year the Board voted to join the Central Michigan Library System on a trial basis provided that State Aid would accompany the membership.  The next year they chose to remain members, and for many years the Board continued to pay the membership dues out of the relatively small yearly State Aid checks.</P>
<P>Hila Bross continued the &quot;Bookshelf&quot; column in the local newspaper.  In January, 1968 she wrote:</P>
<P>While the main business of a library is the acquisition and circulation of books . . . still there is an increasing variety of activities connected with libraries these days.</P>
<P>Bement Public Library does venture into the audio field to the extent of having a small but choice collection of phonograph records for circulation.  And we are on a &quot;hot line&quot; from the Central Michigan Library System headquarters in Mason, through which we may borrow books we do not have.</P>
<P>Most of our operation, however, is still confined to the circulation of books, magazines, pamphlets, and clippings; and the answering of reference questions.  Most of these questions are asked in the library, but some come over the telephone.</P>
<P>Sometimes the question is an easy one, such as &quot;Who's the president of the Woman's Club now?&quot; or &quot;What's the official popu lation of St. Johns?&quot;</P>
<P>Frequently the caller claims that a certain word is not in his/her dictionary or encyclopedia, and asks that we look it up in ours.  This kind of call requires tact on our part because usually the reason the word can't be found is because the caller is not combining the first two or three letters in the proper order. . . .</P>
<P>Some of our most interesting questions come by letter, and frequently they are of a genealogical nature.  The staff of Bement Library does not attempt to do genealogical research, but if it is possible to answer a simple question through the use of our own resources, we usually do so.</P>
<P>Our most recent letter of inquiry comes from the Grand Rapids regional group of the Horseless Carriage Club of America.  They want information about the Triangle Truck Co. which operated in St. Johns about the time of World War I.</P>
<P>This librarian recalls that it was the Hayes Wheel Co., but the most vivid memory connected with it is the fact that it was possible to buy their scrap material for kindling and fire wood, and that a portion of a wheel rim made a marvelous curved seat for a rope swing out under a huge elm tree.</P>
<P>Meanwhile Hila Bross was working towards certification in Library Technology at Lansing Community College.  She assumed the costs of her education.  She asked no favors, she told the Board.  In the fall of 1966 she spoke to the Rotary Club, the Jaycettes and the rural teachers of the St. Johns School district.</P>
<P>Barbara MacKinnon was appointed by the City Commission in January, 1967.  At that time it became apparent to the Board that they must begin using some of the money they were acquiring from various outside sources, or they would lose it.  Suggestions included:</P>
<P>1. A bookmobile in conjunction with Central Michigan Library System</P>
<P>2. Book processing with Lansing and Central Michigan Library System</P>
<P>3. Shut-in program with a visiting librarian and large print books.</P>
<P>4.  New updated reference books</P>
<P>They decided to sell the old dictionary to the VFW Home in Eaton Rapids for $15.  By June a visiting librarian from Lansing, Mrs. John Henry Dudley, was available to visit shut-ins in Saint Johns.  One of her first clients was Dick DeGroot who had been homebound since undergoing back surgery.  After one year the federal funding for the program ran out, and the program was carried on by volunteers sponsored by the Central Michigan Library System.  In 1968 there were 19 volunteers in the tri-county area serving 32 homebound patrons.</P>
<P>Laurita Allison resigned on July 30, 1967.  She had worked for the Library for 14 years and still retained her position as Librarian for the elementary schools in the Saint Johns system.  A gift for Mrs. Allison came from the contributions of individual City employees.  </P>
<P>Cleo Desprez had been hired to replace Mrs. Allison as Assistant Librarian.  Retired rural teacher, Alice Jumper, began working in the library part time.</P>
<P>Two Board members had resigned at the same time as Mrs. Allison.  Basil Deibert and Beulah Ballantine were replaced by Tony Kuntz and Peg Feeman.  Board officers then included:  Jean Mary Bartholomew, Chairman and Barbara MacKinnon Secretary/Treasurer.  Advisory Committee assignments included: Tony Kuntz, book acquisition; Marijane Wohlers, equipment; Jean Bartholomew, books and business; Peg Feeman, decor; and Barbara MacKinnon, personnel.  In November, 1967 Marijane Wohlers resigned and Mrs. Hugh Banninga was chosen by the City Commission to replace her.</P>
<P>Former Board chairman Basil Deibert died unexpectedly on January 2, 1968.  The Library was closed during the funeral, and two books were placed in his memory.</P>
<P>In the spring of 1968 the Board decided that they must take exception to an assignment given to the students of 8th grade history teacher, Mr. McManus.  He had asked students to research a paper on &quot;American Imperialism.&quot;  School superintendent Earl Lancaster replied that the teacher simply had used the wrong terminology.</P>
<P>At that time the paperbound books that the Library had were kept behind the desk and were only circulated by request.  Patrons had to know they were there and ask for them specifically.  Many books, the Librarian and Board members agreed, were not suitable for 8th grade readers.  So many of them, it seemed, were filled with brutality and violence.</P>
<P>The Board agreed in January, 1969 not to purchase the controversial books <I>Candy,</I> and <I>Rosemary's Baby.</I></P>
<P>The next month Cleo Desprez told the Board that she had sent a letter of complaint to a publishing company regarding two mystery books she felt were not acceptable.</P>
<P>A red band policy was instituted.  Books which the Librarian believed were not suitable for all readers were marked on the spine with a piece of red plastic tape.  These books could not be withdrawn by young people or by adults who might be shocked by their content and thus become critical of Library policies.</P>
<P>A Saint Johns father attended the November, 1972 Board meeting to complain that his young daughter had brought home <I>Such Good Friends</I> by Lois Gould.  The book had been red banded, but the girl was large for her age and she had been able to check out the book.  The Board agreed that the policy had not been adhered to.  The father objected to having such books in the Library in the first place.  Mrs. Bross explained the popular demand for the type of books he objected to, saying that most of the books on the current Best Seller lists were of that nature.  The discussion also touched on the subject of censorship.  </P>
<P>After the father left the meeting, the Board voted to continue the red band policy system for all young people below the level of juniors in high school.</P>
<P>Hila Bross took a leave of absence in the fall of 1968 to complete her course work at Lansing Community College.  Cleo Desprez assumed the role of Acting Librarian, and Mrs. Bross was paid $500 to remain as Library Consultant.  In this way she could keep her Blue Cross health benefits and other insurance.</P>
<P>The Board agreed to purchase the textbooks for Mrs. Bross' fall classes.  These texts would then be added to the Library.  Mrs. Bross did ask, however, that she not receive her Christmas ham or turkey this year since she was going to school full time and was, after all, only a Consultant.</P>
<P>In March the Clinton County News printed the list of overdue books for 1969.  There were 305 books going back as far as 1963; and Cleo Desprez was hoping her Valentine theme, &quot;Have a Heart, Bring Your Books Back,&quot; would be effective.  </P>
<P>&quot;This fine-free period is a good time to get the overdue books gathered up and brought back,&quot; Cleo explained.  &quot;All libraries would rather have their books than the money.&quot;  Most of the books were returned promptly.</P>
<P>The Girl Scouts came again in April for a thorough clean-up of the library and grounds.  They spent most of their time outdoors raking and trimming.  Girls participating that year included Cheryl Bancroft, Jennifer Ott, Sue Ludwig, Helen Buggs, Karen Pease, Connie Cornell, Makayla Good, Leona Ludwig, Andrea Boyce, Karen Kundrata and Lee Morriss.  Mrs. Doyle Bancroft was their leader.</P>
<P>Hila Bross became a certified Library Technician in the fall of 1969 and came back as Librarian.  City Commissioner John Hannah joined the Board that fall.  </P>
<P>Redecoration of the Library began that winter in preparation for the celebration of the Library's 30th Anniversary the next April.  Raymond Eick was retained to do the scraping and painting.  The color chosen for the walls was celery green.  The new gold carpeting was purchased from Al Marrah. A $30 dollar wooden clothes hamper was added as an inside book drop.</P>
<P>As the Library came to be open more often at night, Mrs. Bross asked the City Commission to equip the locked Municipal Building doors with panic bars in case of emergency.  The Commission decided that panic bars would be too expensive, but they did offer to give the Librarian keys to the doors that might be used as emergency exits.  The Board also gave her permission to hire a girl to clean the Library floors as necessary.</P>
<P>During its 1970 observance of National Music Month, the St. Johns Morning Musicale featured a display of books by American composers at the Bement Library.  Musicale president, Mrs. Jeanne Bertoldi, announced that the year's theme was &quot;Parade of American Music.&quot;  Records supplied by the group were being played daily throughout the month on the local radio station, WRBJ.</P>
<P>Early in 1970 the Librarian began to explore the need for a new charge desk.  The beautiful old wooden desk just took up too much space.  A few months later the desks from the former Children's Library were placed in the main room, and school principal Roger Feeman accepted the old circulation desk and card catalog for use in Riley Elementary School.</P>
<P>Bess Osgood had quietly begun using the Library facilities to teach English as a second language back in 1959.  In the fall of 1970 the Library Board began sponsoring the project by purchasing texts and workbooks for the students.  Exchange students from the high school were allowed to take the books back with them when they returned to their native countries.  Other texts were added to the Library's collection after the students had finished with them.</P>
<P>Mrs. Osgood met with the Friends of the Library in 1970 to explain her program.  She had brought three of her students with her.  Mrs. Marie Sukup originally had come from Czechoslovakia.  Mrs. Kyenge Hui Case and Mrs. Suki Hulett were from Korea.</P>
<P>Explaining the philosophy behind her weekly Monday night classes, Mrs. Osgood said, &quot;Anyone who has come here to live and wants the privilege of learning our language should have it.&quot;</P>
<P>Informality reigned in Mrs. Osgood's classroom, and she and her students frequently laughed together at themselves as they misunderstood one another.  When Mrs. Osgood used the phrase &quot;the frog was sitting in the sun,&quot; it brought forth giggles from the Korean students who thought they were being told a fairy tale of a frog actually sitting &quot;in&quot; the sun.  Then Mrs. Osgood explained that she really meant that the frog was sitting &quot;in the sunshine.&quot;</P>
<P>Most of the lessons were based upon the students' daily lives.  Sometimes the students swapped recipes, and Mrs. Osgood believed that she learned as much or more than her students.</P>
<P>In October, 1972 Hila Bross attended a State Library Conference on &quot;Reaching out to the Spanish Speaking.&quot;  Two years later several women from the community took advantage of a State Aid project called the Lauback Literacy workshop.  This was a workshop designed to train instructors to teach English as a second language.  It also proposed ways of teaching Spanish to the children of the Spanish-speaking parents in the community.</P>
<P>The Nuguyen family sent a letter to the Library Board in December, 1975 expressing their appreciation to Mrs. Osgood and to the Library Board for supplying them with text books.</P>
<P>The Board received a request in October, 1977 for a class to be held in Fowler.  The request was denied because the cost of the materials would have been born by the Bement Library.  The materials for the current six teachers and 11 students cost $181.26 that year.</P>
<P>By November there were four adults and three high school students working with Mrs. Osgood's program.  There were also two elementary students, a fifth grader and a first grader.</P>
<P>Margaret Rademacher tutored French exchange students.  Mrs. Max Calder worked with two Chicano adults.  Bea Barnum worked part time with students. </P>
<P>The program was growing rapidly, and the Library Board expressed the hope that some service clubs would step forward to help with the expense.  They decided to talk with Bill Swears, Bob LaBrie, and Lois Barnes at the high school to see whether they might be able to offer copying services to the program. </P>
<P>Ironically it was this shift of responsibility to the St. Johns High School which eventually proved to be the program's undoing.  One afternoon Bess Osgood ventured out into the halls of the high school just as classes were changing.  It had not been the fault of the students, she smiled later.  It was just that she couldn't move fast enough to keep up with the flow of traffic.  She was accidentally knocked down, and her hip was broken.  She was never able to return to working with her foreign-speaking students.</P>
<P>In June of 1970 Page Marie Geller received a raise to $.90 per hour.  She soon worked her way up to $1.00 when Joan Rosekrans left and Marie took over her position.</P>
<P>By the spring of 1973 Marie was working 11 hours per week and announced that she was soon to be married.  In June Marie Geller Foote thanked the Library Board for the $5 they sent her for a wedding present.</P>
<P>In the fall Joan Rosekrans returned from Ferris State where she had taken a Library Technician Course.  She was hired to replace both Marie Foote and Marsha Eckerly.  A few months later Rosekrans announced that she was marrying and moving away.  High school students Caren Dietrich and Sharri Desprez were hired to replace her.</P>
<P>Extensive weeding was already in progress in the fall of 1973 when the Library received word of a proposal from the Central Michigan Library System.  The Library could receive $500 worth of books with the stipulation that for each new book added .cb</P>
<P>to the collection an old one must be discarded.</P>
<P>At their January meeting in 1974 the Library Board pledged moral support for the proposed new Clinton County Historical Society at their upcoming organizational meeting on February 28.  One of the spark plugs for the new society was Librarian Hila Bross.</P>
<P>The following May an abandoned car was found in Council Bluffs, Iowa.  In it the police found a number of books from the Bement Library with the cards still in them.  The Library Board took that opportunity to address the larger problem of unreturned books, many of which were badly overdue.  Board member Jean Bartholomew moved that such patrons be denied library services for three months.</P>
<P>The salary of Library Clerk Virginia Dietrich was raised to $2 per hour that June.  The City also began to extend Blue Cross coverage to family members as well as eligible employees themselves.</P>
<P>The next June the Board received two applications.  Marie Geller Foote wanted to return part time.  Betty Moore asked to be considered for the position of Librarian after Mrs. Bross retired.  Both were told that there were no vacancies at the time, and Mrs. Moore's application was tabled.</P>
<P>In December of 1975 Hila Bross tendered her resignation effective July 4, 1976, her 65th birthday.  Cleo Desprez wanted to stay on as Assistant Librarian but was not interested in the Librarian's position.  It was at that same meeting that the Board marked a phonograph album as a memorial to Ladd Bartholomew.</P>
<P>In preparation for her departure Mrs. Bross began making an extensive inventory of the Library's holdings.  Work manuals and job descriptions, which had first been written in 1969, were updated.  </P>
<P>An old newspaper telling of the death of George Washington and published in January, 1800 had been donated to the Library by Ruth Smith Sirrine.  Since there was no room for the Library to display it properly, the newspaper was placed on indefinite loan to the Clinton County Historical Society Museum until such time as the Library had the proper facilities.</P>
<P>Back in 1972 a former resident, Edward S. Davis, had donated $10 to the Library for use in a museum fund.  For several years the Board had held the money hoping that a museum department would materialize.  Finally in 1976 the Board turned the $10 over the Historical Society's Museum.  A Pioneer Society book was also placed on indefinite loan at the Museum.</P>
<P>Jean Mary Bartholomew applied for the position of Librarian in February, 1976.  The Board planned to interview both Mrs. Bartholomew and Betty Moore.</P>
<P>In April Jean Bartholomew resigned from the Library Board, and John Hannah was appointed to take her place.  At the time he returned to the Board Mr. Hannah was the first City Commissioner to sit on the Board in a number of years.  All other cities, it was noted, had Commission members on their boards of directors.</P>
<P>Jean Bartholomew was appointed on April 1, 1976 to replace Hila Bross.  Mrs. Bartholomew enrolled for the Spring Term at Lansing Community College for a course on Technical Services for Libraries.  The new Librarian's starting salary was $6,360, and the Assistant Librarian was to receive $4,585.  The Librarian was to get a $5 raise at the end of each 12 hours of college credit she earned.  All other workers were now being paid at least minimum wage.</P>
<P>When asked about her successor, Hila said, &quot;I am sure she will bring a fresh approach to the library.&quot;</P>
<P>Then she continued, &quot;I have enjoyed the work in the library enormously.  You use all the brains, knowledge and energy you have.&quot;</P>
<P>When asked what she planned for her retirement, Mrs. Bross said that she wanted to clean out her attic and continue teaching piano lessons.  She also hoped to do some writing about the history of Clinton County.</P>
<P>&quot;She has everything up here,&quot; Cleo Desprez added.  &quot;When she retires, she will take all of this stored up information and knowledge with her.&quot;</P>
<P>The Board gave a dinner for Dr. and Mrs. Manning Bross.  They received a gift of three heavy pewter plates with ceramic centers picturing scenes from the American Revolutionary period, commemorating the bicentennial.  One of the plates was appropriately engraved.  These plates matched another the Board had given Dr. and Mrs. Bross on the occasion of their 40th wedding anniversary.</P>
<P>The Library was painted again in the fall of 1976, and the Board was again accepting applications for the position of page.  Gerald Good, Marcia Geller, and Jackie Plowman all applied for the position being vacated by Sharri Desprez.  Jackie Plowman was hired.</P>
<P>Meanwhile the new Librarian canceled the Junior Guild books and continued inventorying the rest of the fiction section.  Library employees were also weeding the vertical file and inventorying the record collection.  The Librarian suggested that magazines in the basement be kept for 10 years and then sold.  A few years later Nancy Drew and the Hardy Boys were replaced as a part of the updating process.</P>
<P>The old red band policy of keeping some books from open circulation was soon abandoned.  &quot;Our library is somewhat unique with open shelves on sex material,&quot; Mrs. Bartholomew explained.  &quot;All of our books are available to all people.&quot;</P>
<P>In November of 1976 Board Chairman Tony Kuntz resigned from the Library Board.  Leon Brewbaker was named to replace him.  Officers of the Board included Lynn Banninga, Chairman and Peg Feeman, Treasurer.  Librarians had been acting as the Board's secretaries since about 1972.  This had become the custom with libraries in the area, Hila Bross had explained at the time.   </P>
<P>In 1976 a new 4-H group had been formed.  Members of the Tailwaggers Club began raising and training puppies to be sent to the Lions Leader Dog training.  When the pups became old enough, it was the responsibility of the young club members to take the dogs out and teach them how to behave in public buildings.  At first the Board informed the 4-Hers that dogs would be welcome in the basement room if they used the downstairs entrance.  Even then staff members were to be notified first, and no other dogs were to be allowed in any other parts of the building.</P>
<P>Mrs. Marge Webster attended the December Board meeting in 1977 to protest that the Board's policy was unreasonable.  All dogs who were kept under control were welcome in the Ovid Library, she added.</P>
<P>Peg Feeman moved and John Hannah supported the motion that all properly identified Leader Dog Trainees, under control, be allowed in the Library accompanied by their trainer.  Trainers could take only 15 minutes for research, and then they had to sign out their materials and leave.</P>
<P>Hila Bross was contacted in February, 1977 and asked to have an 8x10 black and white portrait made at Fitch Studios as soon as possible.  Of course the Board wanted to add her photograph to those of the other former Librarians in the Library.</P>
<P> In November of 1978 Hila was again asked to have her picture taken.  Finally in March of the next year Hila was said to be looking over the proofs, but she was never really satisfied with any picture she had ever had taken.  She insisted that she always looked too wooden in photos, and in a way she was right.  Only a candid shot of Hila could have captured her intelligent and expressive face and eyes.  And as far as we know, no one was ever able to get a truly candid photo of Hila.  She was too astute to be taken unaware and too self-conscious not to freeze at the first sight of a camera lens.</P>
<P>In March, 1977 the Library received a new coat of paint.  The curtains were cleaned, and fresh plants were added.</P>
<P>By the fall of 1977 the Bement Library had become a Class IV library in the Cooperative.  Under their rules the Librarian must have a five year or Masters Degree and the Assistant Librarian needed a four year college degree.  Present library employees were to be grandfathered in, but all employees to be hired in the future needed that amount of accreditation in order for the Library to remain in the Cooperative and receive aid.</P>
<P>Leon Brewbaker resigned in November of 1977, and a month later Mrs. Robert Barnes was appointed to take his place.</P>
<P>A blizzard struck Saint Johns on January 26 and 27, 1978.  On the second day, a Friday, Board Chairman Lynn Banninga and Page Jackie Plowman hiked in to the Library and opened it for the snowed-in travelers who were being housed upstairs in the Municipal Auditorium.</P>
<P>The next spring the Librarian asked the Library Board to establish a chain of command.  Henceforth no staff member other than the Librarian or the Assistant Librarian would be allowed to approach Board members with a problem.  This policy, she hoped, would eliminate communication break-downs and patron complaints.  Board members included John Hannah, Barbara MacKinnon, Peg Feeman, Marta Giesecke, and Lynn Banninga.</P>
<P>Visitors to the Library included the DeWitt Brownies, Mrs. Lashaway's first grade class, and the Adventist School.  The next summer Mrs. Dorothy Bakita complained that her class had not been allowed to visit the Library during the last week of school.  That was just too late in the year, explained Librarian Jean Bartholomew.  &quot;. . .We are not babysitters nor live entertainment for the last week of school,&quot; she added.</P>
<P>Summer Reading Club rules were still quite strict.  Each student first was asked to register at the Library desk.  Each participant was then expected to read 15 books: 5 fiction, 5 non-fiction, and 5 biographies between June and September.  Then each was asked to write a book report and turn it in early in September.</P>
<P>Award winners in the Summer Reading Club for 1978 included: 3rd grade - Amanda Koenigsknecht, Mary Worrall, and Adam Coffman; 4th grade - Charlene Busenitz and Pam Boehlke; 5th grade - Teresa Koenigsknecht, Richard Kirby, and Tracey Hundley; and 6th grade - Alice Puetz.  A quilt raffled off by the Keepsake Quilters Mrs. John Hannah, Mrs. Jim Hansen, Mrs. Terry Scranton, Mrs. Jim Martindale, and Mrs. John Giesecke, brought the Library $500.</P>
<P>That summer Jackie Plowman resigned.  Marie Foote was hired to replace her.  Carroll Furry was contacted to be trained as a substitute Page.  The next December Evelyn Henning resigned, and Carroll Furry was hired full time.  Janet Smalldon then became the substitute Page </P>
<P>The adequacy of the Bement Library again came under discussion when Alta Reed of the Clinton County Historical Society complained that historical materials were being inadequately housed and poorly preserved and that the workroom provided was unsuitable.  Among the materials under discussion were scrapbooks from several sources and papers and photographs from the Millman and the Arthur Wilson families.  There were also a number of unbound newspapers from the 1800's.  </P>
<P>In the fall of 1978 the Library Board discussed the possibility of preserving the newspapers in some way.  The next spring Betty Moore, representing the Historical Society, again contacted the Board about the condition of the old newspapers which were still being stored in a closet in the basement.  Another Historical Society member, Betty Minsky, agreed that they should be better preserved.  The Board replied that there was no money in the budget to care for the newspapers.  By summer the Board learned that the State of Michigan would bind the old newspapers free of charge if they were allowed to microfilm them first.  </P>
<P>After Geneva Wiskemann of the County Historical Commission complained about the condition of the materials, the Board agreed to use money donated by the Friends of the Library to purchase two lockable files.  These were to be placed in the Blue Room.</P>
<P> Meanwhile the Historical Society was embarked upon an immense project of its own.  Members were compiling and publishing a companion volume to the old 1880 <I>History of Clinton and Shiawassee Counties.</I>  This tome would cover the years 1880-1980 in Clinton County. One of the prime movers behind the project was former librarian Hila Bross.  She finally had the opportunity to put her knowledge of Clinton County history into writing. </P>
<P> As a part of the project, Shirley Karber was reading all of the past editions of the <I>Clinton Republican, Clinton County Republican-News, and Clinton County News</I> on microfilm using the Library's microfilm reader.  In July the Board received a letter from the 1980 History Book Committee which read in part: &quot;Please consider this check a donation to your Microfilm Reader Bulb retirement fund.&quot;  Shirley had already burned out two of the bulbs, and her task was not yet completed.</P>
<P>As the 1980 History was going to press Geneva Wiskemann, representing the Clinton County Historical Commission, again contacted the Librarian regarding the condition of the historical materials in its holdings.  Later Mrs. Wiskemann telephoned Peg Feeman and Lynn Banninga at home.  Privately she asked the Board members about the qualifications of their Librarian.</P>
<P>By way of reply both Board members assured Mrs. Wiskemann of Mrs. Bartholomew's qualifications.  Then they in turn questioned Geneva Wiskemann about genealogical materials which had come up missing from the Library's closet.  Further discussion of the subject was tabled.</P>
<P>In the summer of 1980 Barbara MacKinnon and Peg Feeman resolved to begin sorting materials to be put in files.  Later they decided to put off the genealogical work until after school began.</P>
<P>In November another member of the Historical Society, Arlynn Gantz, offered to index and separate the historical materials.  In return Lynn Banninga and Marta Giesecke from the Board offered temporary storage in the closet and reference library to the Clinton County Historical Society's new Genealogy project.</P>
<P>The next summer Mrs. Bartholomew asked the Board to restate an earlier policy.  No non-circulating genealogy materials were to be loaned to anyone for any length of time.</P>
<P>The Library was closed on the day of Manning Bross' funeral in the fall of 1979.  An old fashioned funeral wreath was placed on the Library door.   The next winter the Library closed from 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. for the funeral of Tony Kuntz.  Again the funeral wreath was hung on the door.  The Board voted to subscribe to the large print edition of the Readers Digest in Mr. Kuntz's memory.</P>
<P>In the spring of 1979 Cleo Desprez had undergone gallbladder surgery and missed six weeks of work.  The next October she suffered a coronary.  At that time she was told that she would be paid for three months sick leave, and then her employment would be terminated if she were still unable to return to work.</P>
<P>Carroll Furry, who had recently received her State Certification, was appointed Acting Assistant Librarian.</P>
<P>By February Cleo Desprez was back at work, but she decided to retire following her 70th birthday on February 28, 1981.</P>
<P>Carroll Furry was offered and accepted the position of Assistant Librarian.  Janet Smalldon came on as Page.  A vacation chain of command was established whereby staff members could ask for vacations days in the following order:  Librarian, Assistant Librarian, Clerk, and Pages.</P>
<A HREF="ch4-a.htm"><IMG SRC="tealprev.gif"></a><A HREF="friends.htm"><IMG SRC="tealhome.gif"></a><A HREF="ch5.htm"><IMG SRC="tealnext.gif"></a>
