<HEAD><TITLE>Building the New Library</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pastel.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF0080">
<P>

<P><h3>Building the New Library</h3></P>
<P><h4><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>
he Bement Library had first opened its doors to the public on Saturday, April 13, 1940.  It wasn't until November of the next year that Minnie Barrington decided that space in the new library was inadequate.  She needed more storage room and asked for the middle room in the basement.  What she finally got two years later was a room in the old City Hall.</P>
<P>A year later the Board first discussed joining the State Board of Libraries.  The advantage to joining was that State Aid  money would be available to the Library for the first time.  </P>
<P>Winifred Daboll disagreed vigorously.  She believed that this step was the &quot;beginning of an intervening wedge by the State.&quot;  In the end the Board voted to join but agreed to withdraw if too many demands were made.</P>
<P>  As a Class II Library, the Bement Library was entitled to $423.17 that year.  A few months later the Board began looking into the possibility of obtaining a share of the penal fines set aside for library purposes.</P>
<P>In the meantime a store room in the old City Hall was secured and put to good use.  Later that fall the Board asked the city to clean the walls and pay for it.  Mr. Keiser was contacted to build a $50 partition in the storage room.</P>
<P>On September 6, 1944 the Board voted to remain members of the State Library because of the money and other benefits they had enjoyed over the past year.</P>
<P>Statistics that year showed that 31% of the patrons of the Bement Library were coming from outside the City limits.</P>
<P>In October of 1945 the Chairman of the Library Board went before the City Commission to ask for more funding.  Three years later the Board was assured of State Aid equal to the amount of funding they received from the City.</P>
<P>Early in 1948 the Library was given a new storage room in the basement of the Municipal Building, and the Board paid $117.20 to have shelves built in the new area.  Two months later the Board took a tour of their fine new storage area.</P>
<P>In August of that year the Board presented the mayor, Mr. Palmer, with the annual report and a copy of the constitution which had been revised to meet the demands of State Aid.</P>
<P>Soon the Board received word that the Library had been approved for State Aid until July, 1953.  This meant that they could draw money from the state equal to the amount of money given by the City.</P>
<P>Miss Daboll was still decidedly opposed to the Library's receiving State Aid.  Four months later she resigned from the Board of Directors.  She was replaced by Beulah Ballantine.</P>
<P>During the same month that Miss Daboll resigned over the financial dispute, the Library had received its annual $132.66 in State Aid.</P>
<P>Late in 1949 the Library lost its downstairs storage facility.  It seems that for some time there had been continuing pressure from a group who wanted to use the downstairs kitchen facilities.  A new storage facility was needed.</P>
<P>The balance on hand in the Library Board treasury was $1,772.42 on February 26, 1952.  And the Board was still discussing the benefits and weaknesses of State Aid.  A year later the question was still being discussed.  This time the Board voted to reject State Aid at least until November of 1953.</P>
<P>The Board invited a representative from the State Board to attend their September, 1953 meeting.  She explained to them that as a Class II library they could expect to receive $275 from State Aid that year.  In order to qualify, she noted,  their Librarian must hold a second grade certificate or be working toward it and must attend two workshops.  The Assistant Librarian needed to have a first grade certificate and would be required to attend two workshops within three years.  </P>
<P>Since the Board knew that both Mrs. Millman and Mrs. Allison could qualify, they decided to go ahead and apply once again for State Aid.  In April, 1954 the Board applied; and in July the Library received $261.03 from State Aid.</P>
<P> </P>
<P>As time went on, space continued to be at a premium.  Then in 1954 the City Commission had voted to lend the old Justice of the Peace office to the library for a Children's Library.</P>
<P>In 1956 the Library received $173.39 in State Aid and $3,885 from the City of Saint Johns.  The next January the Board granted raises to all Library employees in accord with the raises given to all of the City employees.</P>
<P>The 1957-58 budget of $4,700 was assured by the City.  A year later the Board again hoped to acquire some of the penal fine money distributed to libraries.  Since the money was being distributed through the schools, the Board contacted Superintendent of Schools Earl Lancaster.  He agreed to purchase $500 worth of books for the Bement Library if the Librarian would make the selections.  The Board agreed to accept the books.</P>
<P>At the same time the City Commission began requesting the removal of the Children's Library to another room in the Municipal Building.  The Board did not approve of the move and tabled the matter.</P>
<P>By 1961 the Board had acquired the penal fines for Saint Johns and was beginning to invest the income with a view to expanding the library or building a new one.  In a note to the City Manager, Ralph Precious, the Board enclosed the following 1951 opinion of the Michigan Attorney General:</P>
<P>Penal fines may be expended by authorities of participating libraries for any purposes involved in the establishment, maintenance and operation of libraries, including the acquisition of sites and buildings, purchase of equipment, including books as well as the general operating expenditures incident to libraries.</P>
<P>That year the penal fines invested in savings certificates amounted to $4,145.</P>
<P>The 1963 Library budget stood at $5500.  Penal fines amounting to $3,513 were placed in time certificates.   At the same time the City Manager suggested charging non-residents for the use of the library.  The Board rejected the idea unanimously.</P>
<P>Board Chairman Basil Deibert suggested in June, 1964 that the $10,500 which had been set aside by the Board for improvements or a new building be set aside as a contingency fund for possible use in a building or improvement program for the future.  The subsequent motion was approved unanimously.</P>
<P>Almost a year later Deibert asked the Board to call in a consultant from the State Library Board to make suggestions about how the Library could be enlarged.</P>
<P>On June 11, 1965 the Library Board met with the City Manager, Ken Greer, to discuss the possibility of remodeling the present library.  They discussed the amount of money that they had managed to save for the project, but it was the opinion of the consultants that Federal money would not be available for the plans they had drawn up.  The project was tabled.</P>
<P>Six months later  Greer returned for a special meeting to discuss liquidating the Library Board Building Fund.  Auditors, he said, had suggested that the money become a part of the City Treasury.  In the future penal fines would go directly to the City but would be earmarked for the building fund.  In the future all moneys would go to the City, and bills would be paid directly by the City Clerk.  In closing, the City Manager reminded the Board that they were appointed by the City Commission and could be removed at any time by that body.</P>
<P>City Commissioner Ray Kentfield promised the Library Board that from then on penal fines would go to the City but would be placed in a special building fund for the library.  Greer gave a tentative time period of five years before the Library expansion could begin under Urban Renewal.  The present funds, he said, were to be put in Treasury .pa</P>
<P>bonds and earmarked for the building fund.</P>
<P>Mayor Charles Coletta moved that the money the City was holding for the Library be ear-marked for a special building fund account.  The motion carried.</P>
<P>On February 1, 1966 the Librarian presented a cashier's check for $25,899.52 to the City Treasurer.  The Board had held out $200 to purchase a new rug and lamps for the Children's Library.</P>
<P>In order to keep the penal fines coming into the library, Board members were told that the City must contribute .3 mil to the support of the library.  The Board also began to look to the outlying districts for support.</P>
<P>Board Chairman Basil Deibert advised Coletta and Kentfield that the Board had received a penal fine check for $20,124.60 in October of 1966.  Board members still had many questions in their minds.</P>
<P>What kind of budget money could they expect from the City in the future?  Could the Librarian still order books and supplies direct instead of having to go through the City Clerk?  Why was there suddenly a delinquency of payment on some of the Library's accounts?  Would the City still continue to fund the Library at a high enough rate to keep them eligible to receive penal fines?</P>
<P>The fiscal year 1966-67 was the first year in its history that the Library operated without any local tax support, and none was expected for 1967-68.  The Library's chief source of income was from penal fines.</P>
<P>Penal fines for the past few years had been unusually generous, being $20,123.60 for 1966-67.  State Aid had totaled $281.45, book fines brought in another $285.69 and interest from bonds had equaled $101.45.  </P>
<P>By January it had been determined that the City must contribute .3 of a mil towards the support of the Library in order for the library to continue receiving penal fines.  The Board was hoping to be able to add Fowler to the Library's service area to increase penal fine income.  The Librarian was given a $100 limit on purchases.  And the Board received an inquiry from the County Library Board asking if the Bement Board was having any trouble with the City Commission.</P>
<P>The Board received a letter from City Manager Ken Greer in February, 1967 billing the Library for operating expenses, building maintenance, and administrative expenses.  In asking for payment he wrote:</P>
<P>Our auditors some years ago pointed out that the cost to operate the municipal building should be charged to those departments housed in the building also that the cost of our administrative expenses must be charged to the various departments and services of the City if the City were to have a true picture of its total operations.</P>
<P>The City Attorney at my request recently researched all the laws and has ruled that it is illegal for the library board to have funds in its own name also it would be illegal for the bank to disburse these funds contrary to law.  I am sure that this was not the intent of the Library Board in failing to turn into the City Treasurer all revenues.</P>
<P>A month later the Board was asking for clarification.  Mayor Coletta suggested that the City Commission and the Library Board have at least one joint meeting per year.  Commissioner John Furry said that the $22,000 must be kept in a separate fund to make the Library eligible for future penal fines.  City Manager Greer informed the Board that a lump sum of $15,981 had already been taken out of the $22,000.</P>
<P>Library Board members were stricken.  Basil Deibert demanded to know why they were suddenly talking about $22,000 when nearly $26,000 had been turned over to the City to be invested.  Deibert further went on record as stating that he would never accept any resolution that did not start with the original $25,899.52 - with an accounting given for all amounts.  In the end the retroactive rent was not collected, but no accounting was ever given either.  </P>
<P>Everyone agreed that the Library Board needed legal help.  At the time the Dearborn Library was having similar problems.  The Michigan Attorney General had issued an opinion that the Library Board had control over endowed funds.</P>
<P> Board members Basil Deibert and Beulah Ballantine and Assistant Librarian Laurita Allison resigned.  Consultants from the State Library and the Central Michigan Library System were called in.  They suggested that the Board turn the matter over to the  State Department of Education and the Attorney General.  </P>
<P>One consultant suggested that the Library should not have to pay rent because more than half of the money for construction of the Municipal Building was earmarked for &quot;library purposes.&quot;  In fact only about 58% of the City's share of construction costs or $20,428.88 came from the original Bement fund.  That figure represented only 32% of the total cost of the building. </P>
<P> The City had taken $6,593.87 from its General Fund at the time application was made for the Federal grant.   Money for other expenses incurred by the City throughout the course of the building project, including the purchase of the different properties, came from the City's water fund.  Therefore .pa</P>
<P>following the State consultant's logic, the Municipal Building could be said to belong about equally to the Library and the City Water Department.</P>
<P>With the specter of back rent removed the Board turned once again to the administration of the funds they no longer held in their own bank accounts.  The City Attorney, Harold Reed, was of the opinion that it was against the law for the City to levy the suggested 1 mil for Library services if the Library already had enough money to meet expenses.  </P>
<P>The penal fines for 1967 amounted to $23,142.  Right then the Bement Library was spending about $1.35 per person served whereas the State average was closer to $2.75 per person.  So a representative from the State Library suggested that the Library Board increase their budget and their services.   </P>
<P>That fall new Board member Tony Kuntz suggested that the Board invest $15,000 in each of the two local banks.  The Board was incensed once again to find that they were not going to be given the original copies of the time certificates for these investments.  They decided to ask the City Manager who replied:</P>
<P> I cannot direct that our City Treasurer violate either our City Charter or the statutes of the State of Michigan, which would be the case if the City Treasurer turned over these time certificates to the Library Board.</P>
<P>. . . State Law gives [the Library Board] the exclusive control of the expenditure of all monies collected to the credit of the Library Fund, but it does not proceed and make them responsible for its deposit or storage . . .  The City Treasurer is bonded but Board members aren't.</P>
<P>Doubtless the City Commission had been right to insist that the City Treasurer oversee the large sums of money being administered by the Library Board.  As the City Manager had pointed out, Library Board members were not even bonded.  And the Board was a creature of the City Commission in much the same way the Park Board had been back in 1940 when the Library Board was first created.</P>
<P>The problem was primarily one of degree.  While the City Commission continued to fund other City departments, it seems that the Commissioners suddenly had to take another look at the Library Board.  The Library didn't appear to need financial assistance from the City.  They were, in fact, generating some pretty good-sized revenues. </P>
<P>In the end it would appear that Winifred Daboll had been right to be afraid to take outside money -- if only for the wrong reasons.  Miss Daboll had been concerned about undue control coming into the Library from outside the community.  As it turned out, just the opposite had occurred.  So much money had begun coming into the Library from outside the City of Saint Johns that the City Commissioners may have begun to lose track of their obligation to support their own Library financially.  </P>
<P><B>FRIENDS OF THE LIBRARY</B></P>
<P>In June, 1967 Mrs. Millman announced that the St. Johns Woman's Club was forming a new organization called &quot;Friends of the Library.&quot;  A nationwide organization, Friends was designed to encourage understanding and appreciation of the work of the library and to help in its future development.  The larger organization was also instrumental in obtaining bequests and gifts of books, manuscripts and other appropriate materials such as works of art, rare books, musical recordings and magazines for each public library with which it was affiliated.</P>
<P>The charter group was chaired by Mrs. Rolan Sleight.  Other members included Mrs. Roy Davis, Mrs. Lawrence Fish, Mrs. Cerelda Hicks, Mrs. Van Hoag, Mrs. K.L. Jones, Mrs. James Postlethwaite, Mrs. Leo Pouch, Mrs. William Richards Sr., Mrs. John Rumbaugh, Mrs. Joseph Spousta, Mrs. Marion Walling, and Mrs. Brandon White.  Men and women alike were invited to join the organization.</P>
<P>The new group met for the first time on September 21 at 7:30 p.m. in the Library.  Fifty-one families signed up at that organizational meeting.   Their purpose they said was to
 foster closer relations between Bement Public Library and the citizens of St. Johns; to promote knowledge of the functions, resources, services and needs of the library; to lead in the development of a program for the extension and improvement of library services and resources; and to aid in the provision of adequate housing and other facilities of the library.  </P>
<P>In essence, the Friends of the Bement Public Library was an auxiliary to the Library Board and the Library. </P>
<P> Dues in the new organization were set at $1 per family per year, and the group was headed by a 15-member board of directors.  Mrs. Brandon White was named the new president of the Friends of the Library Board.  Other officers included: Mrs. Rolan Sleight, vice president; Mrs. Lawrence Fish, secretary, Mrs. Millman, corresponding secretary; and Jack Davis, treasurer.  Other directors included the Rev. Gerald Churchill, Kurt Becker, Mrs. Maxine Parmelee, the Rev. Hugh Banninga, Mrs. Keith McDowell, Mrs. Marion Walling, Mrs. Erma Robinson, Mrs. Gordon Iacovoni, William Kemper, Mrs. Keith Bovee, and David Pocuis.  Ex-officio members of the board were Librarian Hila Bross and &quot;Lansing State Journal&quot; reporter Betty Jane Minsky.  </P>
<P>Members of the Friends of the Library were entitled to purchase books at reduced prices by ordering them through the library.</P>
<P>One of the first projects undertaken by the Friends was the keeping of a book of &quot;Memory.&quot;  In this book were to be recorded all of the books and special gifts donated to the Library over the years in memory of friends and family members.  Mrs. Jerry Stone headed this nearly overwhelming project.  The undertaking was made especially difficult since some of the gifts went back to 1939 before the Library was even opened.  </P>
<P>On October 29, 1967 the Friends hosted a reception for the departing Library Board members, Beulah Ballantine and Basil Deibert and the outgoing Assistant Librarian, Laurita Allison.</P>
<P>The next month the Friends of the Library debated the possibility of taking books to nursing homes and the county farm.  Soon the Clinton County Infirmary was getting a visit from one of the Friends of the Library about every two weeks.  Mrs. Leon Brewbaker was in charge of that project.  Residents of area nursing homes and the Infirmary thus were able to sign out books just as a patron would at the main library.</P>
<P> A book drop was installed at Rodney B. Wilson High School to aid students there in returning library books on time.  This project was overseen by a high school student, Medina Parsons.  She saw to it that books left at the high school for the Library were returned on time.</P>
<P>By January, 1968 the Friends also had decided to try to institute a book cart service at Clinton Memorial Hospital.  In preparation for the new project, Elizabeth Millman, Hila Bross, and Friends Board President Annette White spent a day at Sparrow Hospital in Lansing studying the library set-up provided there.  </P>
<P>&quot;It is a bigger deal there than we could ever hope to have here,&quot; Mrs. White pointed out, &quot;because I doubt if we could ever have a paid librarian.  But we learned how to set up this service, what books we would need, and how to get them ready.</P>
<P>&quot;These books have to be screened.  With Mrs. Millman in charge of it, we are quite fortunate because she was a librarian and is familiar with a lot of books.&quot;</P>
<P>The library service at the hospital was to be handled by volunteers, and they had to be people who were not squeamish about working in the hospital.  Hospital administrator Harold Reed readily approved the plan. Books were to be stored in the doctors' library at the hospital, but .pa</P>
<P>they were carried from room to room on a cart.  Long term patients at the hospital were able to order books to read that weren't a part of the collection at the hospital. </P>
<P>The first selection of about 107 books needed to be bound and marked.  Two workshops were held at the Library for that purpose.  Among the participants were Mrs. Brandon White, Mrs. John Rumbaugh, and Mrs. Gordon Iacovoni.  Whenever a jacket was not available, one was made of wallpaper.  Heathman's and Glaspie's donated two large catalogs of wallpaper samples for the purpose.</P>
<P>There was already a collection of books which the Hospital Auxiliary had used as part of their service.  Later these were sorted and processed to be added to the others.</P>
<P> The hospital book cart service was the largest of the organization's early projects.  Among the first volunteers to work at the hospital regularly were Kay Arehart, Shirley Casler, Adelaide Mikula, Mrs. Pat Kelly, Mrs. Erma Robinson, and Mrs. Lloyd Campbell.  Books were distributed on Tuesdays, Thursdays, and Saturdays.  Patients could return the books at the hospital or through the Bement Library.</P>
<P>In May, 1968 the Friends group sponsored a Library Art Exhibit at the Central National Bank.  Paintings included &quot;Lakeside&quot; and &quot;Quiet Sea&quot; by Warren Anderson, &quot;Daffodils&quot; by Georgianna Kelly, &quot;Countryside&quot; by Gladys Schueller, &quot;Driftwood With Bottle&quot; by Betty Penix, &quot;Fruit Still Life&quot; by Joan Ernst, &quot;Paysage on Alsace&quot; by William Morriss and &quot;Owl&quot; by Romaine DeCamp.</P>
<P>Of course the Friends of the Library were as anxious as the Library Board members were to see the Library settled in its new building.  During Sidewalk Days in the summer of 1968 the Friends workers collected $75 on their used book sale.  Eighty discarded library books were sorted into paper bags for the event.  Helping with the project were school children Jim Smith, Bill Brewbaker, Marty Brewbaker, Caren Dietrich, Janice Flermoen, Kathy Piper, Danny Piper, and Lori Piper.</P>
<P>The next year the Friends Board, headed by Adelaide Mikula, added a book discussion group to their list of activities and continued to sell books during the annual Sidewalk Sales.  </P>
<P>In April the Friends of the Library donated money to the Library in memory of Dr. Franklin W. Smith.  The next month Librarian Hila Bross and Mrs. Franklin Smith attended a District meeting of the Friends of the Library.</P>
<P>  </P>
<P>The Friends group took over sponsorship of the summer reading program.  At the end of each summer they gave a reception for the winners of the essay contests and awarded prizes.  Library Week celebrations also became a part of their involvement in the workings of the Library.</P>
<P>When the local Jaycettes began sponsoring a Lunch With Santa each December in the Municipal Building Auditorium, the Friends began sponsoring a story hour.  In 1972 Mrs. Robert Barnes and Hila Bross were assisted by other members of the Friends of the Library and the Drama Club of St. Johns High School.  For three Saturdays in a row they entertained children.  This year the groups were divided according to size and age to prevent the overcrowding that had nearly swamped the program in 1971.</P>
<P>The speaker for the 1973 annual meeting of the Friends of the Library was Roy L. Dodge, the author of <I>Michigan Ghost </I><I>Towns.</I>  After he spoke, prizes were awarded as usual for book reports completed during the summer Children's Reading Club.</P>
<P>In January, 1975 the Friends of the Library sponsored a Crafts Fair in the Municipal Auditorium.  At their annual meeting in September the Board reported that they had held their annual used book sale as usual in August. In addition to these activities, the Friends were planning to sponsor a sale of First Editions in conjunction with the Clinton County Historical Society's upcoming Home Tour.</P>
<P>In August, 1976 the Friends of the Library netted $70 during the Sidewalk Sales.  The books which they had not been able to sell in August were sent for distribution to Veterans hospitals.</P>
<P>At Christmas time in 1976 Mrs. H. Garapetian and Mrs. John Arehart did a Christmas reading program for a small but attentive group.  The next month 138 children's books were discarded, and 246 were purchased to replace them.  The Friends of the Library hoped to sell the discarded books during the next Sidewalk Days sales.</P>
<P>On April 5, 1977 the Friends of the Library collaborated with the Library Board to sponsor a Film Festival.  A projector was borrowed from the St. Johns Episcopal Church.  Library Board members Barbara MacKinnon and Peg Feeman chose the films, &quot;One Wish Too Many&quot; and &quot;The Little Engine That Could.&quot;</P>
<P>The winners of the 1977 Summer Reading Program and their parents were honored guests at a punch and cookies party.  Cash prizes and certificates were awarded as usual.  By December of 1977 the Friends of the Library turned to the Library Board looking for new members and new ideas.  </P>
<P>Library Board member Lois Barnes, who had been active in the Friends organization, told the Library Board that she believed that the problem with the Friends of the Library was a lack of direction by the old Board.  Ten members had left.  </P>
<P>Reorganization and reactivation of the Friends group became the pet project of Sue Cerney and Patricia Smith.  They needed, some said, someone other than the Librarian to serve as a liaison person between their Board and the Library Board.</P>
<P>Mrs. Cerney suggested that the organization be dropped for six months and then reorganized.  Kay Arehart was anxious to establish a new Board.</P>
<P>In the summer of 1978 the Friends of the Library did not hold their annual used book sale during Sidewalk Days.  There were not enough workers.  Still they hoped they might be able to get a sale together in time for the Historical Society's annual Home Tour.</P>
<P>On September 6, 1979 Sue Cerney, representing the Friends of the Library, turned over $438 to the Library Board to be used to purchase something for the Library sometime in the future.  All of the records and scrapbooks from the organization were placed in the Library for safekeeping.  The Board turned the money over to the City where it was placed in a separate account.  It was this money which had been used to purchase the storage cabinets in the Genealogy room.</P>
<P>As usual, in January of 1968 the Library Board began to look for more storage space.  The cupboards in the upstairs kitchen were suggested.  It was estimated that a new library would be needed in about six years, and the Chairman of the Board suggested that having the City levy one mil in taxes for the library would be a painless way to get it.  In the end the Library didn't even get to use the cupboards.</P>
<P>In September, 1968 the Library Board began entering into general contracts with the neighboring townships.  Bingham and Bengal were the first.  Penal fines that year amounted to $19,630.44.  The Board had another $34,605.59 on hand.</P>
<P>That same month the Board discussed using the old Grand Trunk depot as a library.  They were told that it still housed the telegraph key and that it would be too expensive to move it.  The Librarian thought that it was too small anyway and would need a fence to protect patrons from train traffic.</P>
<P>Towards the end of 1969 several building sites were discussed including the two that the Bement family had favored all along, the post office and A&amp;P Store lots.  Another site mentioned was the old Hicks mansion itself.</P>
<P>Consultants from the State Library were asked to visit the Hicks house which was being placed on the market by Mrs. Franklin Smith.  She had asked that the entire Board not tour the place unless they were really serious about purchasing the property.  The consultants reported that it would be impossible to use the old home effectively as a library.</P>
<P>The Board decided that perhaps they would do better to look into enlarging the present Library by remodeling the back of the Municipal Building.  Therefore the Board returned to the City to ask that 1 mil be levied for the support of the library.  </P>
<P>Board members agreed that there was no use purchasing a new charge desk until they knew whether they were moving.  Two months later they voted to go ahead and look at new desks.</P>
<P>Early in 1971 a Federal fund of $260,000 became available.  All the Board needed was a building site, a building plan, and a payment plan.  Sites available at that time included Kurt Becker's store, the old Richards Dairy, the DeRose property, a vacant lot at the corner of Cass and Wight Streets across from St. Joseph Catholic School, the Hicks house, the old Chevrolet garage on Higham, the City Park complex, Matthews Dairy, Miller Furniture, and the parking lot north of the Municipal Building.  Also under consideration was Dr. Burkhardt's old office, the original Hicks house on Brush Street.</P>
<P>Librarian Hila Bross told the Board that they must consider population growth and should be planning ahead for an area population of about 10,000 people.  In order to serve this population Mrs. Bross added that the Library would need a 20,000 volume collection of books with 2,500 linear feet or an allocation of one foot for each 8 books in the collection.  In addition there would be a need for 2,000 square feet of floor space; 1,200 square feet of reader space; 1,000 square feet of staff space and an addition 1,800 square feet of space needed for equipment.  The total amount of space required would be about 7,000 square feet.</P>
<P>Areas which would be needed in the new Library included historical, audio visual, children's, and reference departments, study areas, work areas for staff members, office space, and wall and counter display space.</P>
<P>The Richards property on Brush Street was 50 feet wide by 165 feet deep and was available for between $18,000 and $24,000.  The Burkhardt office, located on a piece of land 110 feet square, would cost $21,000 in cash.</P>
<P>The Board had $36,825.54 in savings, but the State Library Consultants told them that it would be almost useless to ask Bingham Township for millage since the City of Saint Johns did not support the Library financially.  The Board agreed to investigate the possibility of writing open-ended contracts between the Library Board and the Township Boards.</P>
<P>A piece of land at the corner of Higham and North Oakland Streets owned by James McKenzie came to the attention of the Board.  The site was 77 feet by 150 feet and was valued at $7,000.</P>
<P>On December 9, 1972 an emergency meeting of the Board was called because the word was out that the A&amp;P store was closing.  Board Chairman Tony Kuntz attended the next City Commission meeting in the company of Barbara MacKinnon and Hila Bross.  Friends of the Library members Donald Isbell, Jessie Finch, Orientis Fish, Olive Conklin, Adelaide Mikula, Robert and Lois Barnes, Pauline Torpey, the Rev. Francis Johannides, and Mildred Countryman also attended.  Commission members present that evening included Mayor Robert Wood, John Hannah, Jeanne Rand, Roy Ebert and Dr. James Grost.  Also in attendance were City Manager Harvey Weatherwax, City Clerk Thomas Hundley, and City Zoning Administrator Randy Humphrey.</P>
<P>Mr. Weatherwax and Mr. Humphrey, a representative from the Fire Marshall's office, and an engineer from the firm of Williams and Werkes of Grand Rapids went out to look over the place.  The Library Board was asked to prepare a plan for the use of the building and to present a possible budget.  Two contractors, Norm Rademacher and Ben Wieber, were asked to submit construction bids on a new roof, fire-resistent ceiling tiles, and rehanging the doors.  </P>
<P>The Board took a $1 option on the property and voted to purchase it - provided the City would support the Library with millage or a tax appropriation.  The Commission failed to approve the purchase, did not agree to support the Library financially, and the matter was dropped.</P>
<P>Meanwhile more and more townships were entering into contracts with the Library.  In March, 1973 Bingham, Bengal, and Dallas signed.  Each agreed to turn over their penal fines in exchange for library services for their residents.  The next month Olive and Riley Townships agreed to turn over half of their penal fines.  The other half was to go to the neighboring DeWitt Library.</P>
<P>Again in 1973 the Board Chairman returned to the City Commission to ask for the 1 mil levy.  The Board still hoped to be able to spend most of the newly acquired penal fines for a building or a building site.</P>
<P>Lynn Banninga and Board Chairman Tony Kuntz were sent to the City Commission to ask about the possibility of using the Municipal Auditorium as a Library.  In June, 1973 the Commission postponed action on giving the Auditorium to the Library.  By October the Library Board still had not received any answer from the Commission.</P>
<P>The Library had not qualified for State Aid in 1972-73 because City funds did not equal the required minimum of .3 mil of equalized valuation.  That year the Library stood to lose $3,426.  If they did not qualify for a second year in a row, they risked being dropped from the Central Michigan Library System.</P>
<P>Mayor Robert Wood announced that the City would give the Library $10,000 the next year.  This together with the penal fines should, he said, insure eligibility for State Aid.</P>
<P>Finally the State Board for Libraries reconsidered and sent the Library Board a check to be placed in a special account.  Librarian Hila Bross suggested that the money be used first to pay the Central Michigan Library System dues as usual.  The rest she hoped the Board would put into the Library's audio visual department.</P>
<P>In the spring of 1974 Peg Feeman moved that Chairman Kuntz be sent to the City Commission to &quot;request them to levy up to one mil for Library support in the event that the Board decides to spend most of the Library's funds for a building or a building site.&quot;</P>
<P>The City Commission declined.  Meanwhile half of Westphalia Township's penal fines were added to the support of the Library.</P>
<P>New library sites became available late in 1975.  These included the old Steel Hotel lot and Boron's Store.</P>
<P>A month or so later the old Clinton County News building on the south side of Walker was offered to the Library.  Editor Harold Schmaltz and the Staffords from Greenville gave the eager Board members a tour of the place.  Board members suggested asking contractors Norm Rademacher and Wayne Dush to look it over with an eye to remodeling the 75 year old building.  A State Library consultant said, however, that the building was inadequate and that any remodeling and repairs would be both extensive and costly.</P>
<P>The next June Mayor Roy Ebert and the City Commission allocated only $5,000 instead of the $10,000 that the Library Board had been promised.  If Federal Revenue Sharing Funds came through, though, the Board would receive the entire $10,000, they promised.  The City Commission was said to be ready to institute a special study committee to explore the Library's space problems, and the Board was hopeful.</P>
<P>In November, 1976 the grant request for the City's new Safety Building came through.  At one time the Board had hoped that a new library might be included along with the fire and police departments in this project.  Now they merely hoped for the old police office downstairs.  They received neither.</P>
<P>Meanwhile the City's 1977 Federal Revenue Sharing Fund money came through, and the Library received the additional $5,000 they had been promised.</P>
<P>Still the Library did not qualify for the full amount of State Aid because the penal fines were down.  They needed additional funding by June 30.  A State Library consultant advised the Board that the City Commission could not cut line items in the Library's budget.  The Bement Library would be placed on probation with the Central Michigan Library System until its money problems could be resolved.</P>
<P>Finally on June 22 Treasurer Eugene Simon told the Board that they would need an additional $4,000 to qualify for State Aid.  The Board needed to ask for another $5,000 from the City to make it look like the Library was receiving more local support.  &quot;This amount would be paid back in the form of Administrative fees and Maintenance,&quot; Librarian Jean Bartholomew explained to the Board.</P>
<P>Early in 1978 the old Ford garage became available.  The Board discussed it, and the matter was tabled.</P>
<P>In 1982 the Board lost $6,000 in State Aid because of a lack of local funding.  According to the minutes of the March meeting, &quot;the Board agreed that if the library [were] to continue functioning, there [would] have to be some support.&quot;</P>
<P>Letters were sent out to the Supervisors of Bengal, Dallas, Greenbush, Olive, Riley, and Westphalia Townships explaining the need for their share of the .3 mil of state equalized value.  The Board followed up the letters with personal visits to give the supervisors more detailed information.</P>
<P>Petitions were prepared for township residents to send to their local officials.  They read in part:</P>
<P>As a supporter and patron of the Bement Public Library, I want to express to you my support for the library, and to request that you contribute to the library the amount prescribed by the State of Michigan formula, and that you adopt this practice annually.</P>
<P>One float in the first annual St. Johns Mint Festival parade in 1986 featured a wagon full to overflowing with books.  The float, entitled &quot;The Great Library Chase&quot; also boasted a sign crying, &quot;Help!  We need room!&quot;  This parade entry was sponsored by a citizen's group called the &quot;St. Johns Area Library Project.&quot;</P>
<P>By 1987 when the question of a new library came up again, the Library Board was headed by Sheryl Plowman.  Other members included Barbara MacKinnon, Lynn Banninga, Tom Sullivan, and the Board's liaison with the City Commission, Robert Wood.</P>
<P> The St. Johns Area Library Project began trying to put together a plan.  It was suggested that perhaps other organizations might share space with the library in a new arts building.  </P>
<P>Rumors were flying that ground would soon be broken for a new post office.  Other sites the group was considering included the City Park complex, a building on north US-27 and the old bus depot on Railroad street.  The Library Board requested 10,000 square feet of usable space and 2,500 square feet of shared space.  </P>
<P>The new library to be built by the St. Johns Area Library Project would not belong to the City or the Bement Library, explained spokesman Joe Latoff.  The corporation would control all aspects of library operations including choosing the librarian and paying all bills and expenses in the new facility.</P>
<P>Library Board member Tom Sullivan was made the chairman of the Fund Raising committee.</P>
<P>Librarian Jean Bartholomew retired on July 8, 1988.  In parting she wrote:</P>
<P>I expect to live to a ripe old age, turn into an irascible, white-haired old lady with a lavender shawl and a cane carrying the banner for all kinds of causes.</P>
<P>There will be changes in the library.  The new person will be full of different, innovative ideas he or she will be anxious to implement. This is a mark of healthy progress.  An important aspect of any public service.</P>
<P>The board has the best interests of the library at heart and are trying hard to choose the ideal person for the position.</P>
<P>  </P>
<P>[Board] members have given unstintingly of their time and expertise for many years to keep this facility operating. This must be a labor of love because there is no pay and no glory.</P>
<P>Said Board trustee Lynn Banninga, &quot; You'll never replace Jean's personality.  [The Board] feels badly that she has worked so hard, unsuccessfully, for a new library.  It's just a shame that we weren't able to realize her goal before she retired.&quot; </P>
<P>In their search for the next Librarian the Board received responses from 20 applicants from Michigan, Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Iowa, and West Virginia.  In the end Board members were the most impressed with the qualifications of Mary Hutchins of Rockford, Illinois.  She assumed the position of Librarian on September 6, 1988.</P>
<P>&quot;We liked the ideas she had to go along with our ideas.  Together we feel we can make progress,&quot; explained Board Chairman Sheryl Plowman.</P>
<P>In January of 1991 the Bement Public Library was still squeezed into the limited space available to it in the Municipal Building, and the Library Board began mailing out post cards to library patrons inviting them to a &quot;Public Town Meeting.&quot;  The City Commission had indicated, the post card said, that the Library Board needed to show a groundswell of support for more funding for the Library.  </P>
<P>The town meeting was set for Monday January 21, 1991 at 7:30 p.m. at the Capitol Federal Savings Bank meeting room.  The bank was located on the site of the old Steel Hotel building, just one of the Library's many former potential building sites.</P>
