<HEAD>
<TITLE>Village</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Yelgrain.gif">
<P ALIGN="center"><IMG BORDER="0" SRC="Depot.gif" ALIGN="right"></P>
<P ALIGN="center">&nbsp;</P>
<P ALIGN="center">&nbsp;</P>
<P ALIGN="center">&nbsp;</P>
<P ALIGN="center"><FONT SIZE="4">Welcome to the small village of<BR>
 </FONT><FONT SIZE="+7"><B>Gaines, Michigan.</B></FONT><FONT SIZE="4"><B>
<HR>
<DEL></DEL></B></FONT><FONT SIZE="5">
</FONT>

</P>
<P ALIGN="center">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE BORDER="1" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="22%">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP"><FONT SIZE="+3">Check out the area</FONT>
<P><IMG SRC="sph0052.gif" HSPACE="5"><B>St.Joseph Church</B></P>
<P><IMG SRC="sph0052.gif" HSPACE="5"><B>Downtown</B></P>
<P><IMG SRC="sph0052.gif" HSPACE="5"><B>History</B></P>
<P><A HREF="index.htm"><IMG SRC="sph0052.gif" HSPACE="5" BORDER="0"></A><B><A HREF="index.htm">School</A></B></P>
<P><IMG SRC="sph0052.gif" HSPACE="5"></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+3"></FONT></P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<B>
<TABLE BORDER="0" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="50%">
</TABLE>
</B>
<TABLE BORDER="2" CELLSPACING="4" CELLPADDING="6" ALIGN="DEFAULT" WIDTH="75%">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
<P><FONT SIZE="4"> </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="4">HISTORICAL SIGNIFICANCE OF THE GAINES STATION: </FONT></P>
<P> * One of the oldest structures still standing in Gaines, 
 and among the oldest railroad depots in Michigan, the Gaines 
 depot was built in 1884 by the Detroit, Grand Haven &amp; 
Milwaukee Railway, according the records of the Grand Trunk 
 Western Railroad. </P>
<P> * The railroad is the principal reason that Gaines became a <BR>
 community. In 1848 a line vas proposed by the Oakland &amp; <BR>
 Ottawa Rail Road Company from Pontiac via what was then 
named Fentonville to some point on the Lake Michigan shore. 
 The following year the Oakland &amp; Ottawa purchased the
 Detroit &amp; Pontiac and in 1855 formed the Detroit &amp; Milwaukee 
Railway. It was this company that constructed the line  through Gaines, probably reaching Gaines in the spring of  1856 and Owosso by July of that year. In 1856 the Detroit &amp;  Milwaukee completed its 189-mile line through Grand Rapids  to Grand Haven in 1858 where connections were made with  boats to Milwaukee. The Detroit &amp; Milwaukee became the  Detroit, Grand Haven &amp; Milwaukee Railway in 1878 and was  merged into the Grand Trunk Western in November 1928.  Today, the Grand Trunk Western is known as CN-North  America. Since the late 1850s the companies have largely  been controlled first by British and later Canadian  interests. </P>
<P> * The Gaines depot was constructed using an uncommon type  of yellow brick from Owosso, Michigan. This same brick can  also be seen at depots in Fenton and Holly on the line  toward Pontiac. </P>
</B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
