<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Clinton County Courthouse Brief History</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="backgnd.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800040">
<P>
<BODY>

<H1>Clinton County Courthouse</H1>
<IMG SRC="courth2.gif" HSPACE=1.5 ALIGN=right ALT="old courthouse">
<H2>A Brief Early History</H2>

<H4>  In the October, 1855 session of Clinton County's Board of
Supervisors, the question of moving the county seat from DeWitt
to St. Johns first arose. One supervisor favoring moving the county
seat to St. Johns. Another said they should &quot;strike out&quot;
St. Johns from the motion and insert &quot;center of Muskrat Lake.&quot;
No action was taken.</H4>

<H4> A year later the St. Johns supervisor, called for the move
to his community, providing residents there made a one-and-one-half
acre building site available. St. Johns residents raised $2,000
to help with the moving expenses.   In December, 1857, county
offices were moved from DeWitt to Plumstead Hall at the northeast
corner of Clinton Ave. and Walker Street in St. Johns.</H4>

<H4>In 1858 a 20 x 25 foot brick county building was erected on
the northwest corner of the public square. County offices were
housed there.  Courts met at Plumstead Hall until 1861.  Other
locations included George Stephenson's Clinton Hall on the east
side of Clinton Ave., Newton Hall on East Walker, and the Hicks
building on the west side of the second block of Clinton Ave.
</H4>

<H4>In January, 1869 supervisors discussed submitting a $25,000
building proposal to taxpayers. This was later approved, 1,734
to 1,170, A building committee composed of William L. Hicks, George
R. Hunt, Benjamin F. Shepherd, David Clark, Moses Bartow and John
Hicks was appointed and given authority to enter into contracts.
</H4>

<H4>In October, 1869 the committee adopted a plan similar to the
Bay City, Michigan courthouse designed by Oliver Hidden. Foundation
work contracts were awarded. The cornerstone laid in the fall
of 1869, and the foundation was completed the next month. Construction
came to a halt with supervisors rejecting all bids for the balance
of the work.  The committee believed that the low bidder had &quot;made
his estimate too low, and that in order to get through his job
and not lose money, he would be apt to slight his work . . . 
 Therefore, they wrote: Resolved that all bids for erection of
Court House be rejected, and that the Building Committee proceed
to procure materials for the erection of the same, and that Messers
[John] Hicks and Hunt of the of the committee are hereby authorized
to act for the committee in the purchase of the proper material.
</H4>

<H4>On March 15, 1871 the courthouse dome was struck by lightening,
tearing out the southeast corner completely and destroying all
of the glass.  Damage was estimated to be between $250 and $500.
</H4>

<H4>The Building Committee submitted a report to the Supervisors
on October 11, 1871.  In it Chairman John Hicks wrote:</H4>

<H4>The committee have exercised their best skill and judgment
to get the best of material and employ the best of workmen in
the construction of said building, and . . . think for the amount
expended the county will have the best building in the state.
</H4>

<H4>The Committee's final report was issued on January 8, 1872.
 &quot;The whole amount appropriated for building a Court House
was thirty-six thousand dollars as follows:</H4>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD><H4>Village of St. Johns</H4> </TD><TD><H4>Oct. 3, 1868</H4></TD>
<TD><H4>$ 5,000</H4></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Clinton County</H4> </TD><TD><H4>Jan. 7, 1869</H4></TD>
<TD><H4>$25,000</H4></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Clinton County</H4> </TD><TD><H4>Oct. 4, 1870</H4></TD>
<TD><H4>$ 1,000</H4></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>    Clinton County</H4>  </TD><TD><H4>Jan. 6, 1871</H4> </TD>
<TD><H4>$ 5,000</H4></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P><H4> Since then the building has been improved and modernized
through the years.  A $1,000 Seth Thomas clock in the tower rang
in the New Year in 1905.  In the spring of 1927 there was extensive
remodeling done to the interior including the addition of a fireproof
vault.</H4>

<H4>In August of 1957 a general renovation costing $20,000 took
place.  The entire exterior was sandblasted.   Other alterations
include a new entrance built in 1958 for $59,089.51; a west wing,
built in 1965 at cost of $165,765.56; and a matching east wing,
constructed for $246,000 in 1966. The latter included a civil
defense operating center in the basement, and part of that added
cost was matched by federal funds.</H4>

<H4>  Early in 1969 a supervisors room in the west wing was transformed
into a District Court and supervisors moved into the east wing
basement civil defense area.</H4>

<H4>Judges chambers had been added in 1958.  As a Centennial celebration
was being held in 1969, construction was being completed in the
Circuit Court, removing rows of rear seating to make way for conference
and office rooms.</H4>

<H4>The 65th Judicial District, 2nd Division, was established
January 1, 1969.  For a time the west wing was occupied by the
District Court, but  in 1974 it was moved to a separate building
on Whittemore Street. </H4>
<P><A HREF="chouse.htm"><IMG SRC="tanhome.gif"><B>Back to the Courthouse green</B> </a><A HREF="chtime.htm"><IMG SRC="tannext.gif"><B>To the Timeline</B> </a><P>
<HR>
<a href="http://www.miserybay.com/mbay.htm"><H3>Where is Misery Bay anyway?</H3></a>
</ul>
<P>
<H4><center> <I>Page Design by</i><A HREF = "http://www.miserybay.com"> Misery Bay Publications</a><BR>
</center></H4><IMG SRC="bay.gif">
