<td VALIGN=TOP>
<CENTER><h1>Mission Statement</h1></CENTER>


                                                 <h3><i>We, the Secular Franciscans of
                                                 lower Michigan, and Toledo,
                                                 Ohio have drawn together as
                                                 the Region of Divine Mercy to
                                                 bring greater communication,
                                                 harmony and evangelization to
                                                 all people. We are committed to
                                                 living the Gospel values of our
                                                 Lord Jesus Christ, in our time
                                                 according to the Way of St.
                                                 Francis of Assisi. <P>
                                                 In this community we will
                                                 strive to bring forth worthy
                                                 fruits of penance through
                                                 faithful adherence to the spirit
                                                 of gospel poverty. <P>
                                                 We intend to let prayer be the
                                                 soul of all we do while we live
                                                 as lay persons in the Church,
                                                 bearing peace and love, justice
                                                 and dignity to all people. In our
                                                 endeavors we devote ourselves
                                                 to prayer, that Almighty God
                                                 will guide and direct us as we
                                                 trust in His Divine Mercy. <P>
                                                 We are each called by Baptism
                                                 and Confirmation to holiness.
                                                 By Professing the Rule of St.
                                                 Francis, we acknowledge our
                                                 call to rebuild the Church
                                                 through the help of Mary and
                                                 the Saints and in imitation of
                                                 Jesus Christ, our Lord. <P>
                                                 We will foster fraternal spirit,
                                                 common activities, and
                                                 communication and provide
                                                 direction and resources to local
                                                 fraternities for understanding
                                                 and implementing the Rule, the
                                                 Constitutions, and the
                                                 National Statutes of the
                                                 Secular Franciscan Order. <P>
                                                 We Franciscans go out to those
                                                 to whom Franciscans have
                                                 always gone: the forgotten, the
                                                 unwanted and the spiritually
                                                 hungry, seeking them out and
                                                 ministering to their needs,
                                                 trying to bring them back to the
                                                 full love of God. As followers of
                                                 St. Francis, we strive to
                                                 promote harmony within our
                                                 families, within our
                                                 communities, and with all of
                                                 Creation. </I></H3><P><HR><P>




<h1>Divine Mercy Region</h1>
<h4>of lower Michigan and Toledo Ohio</h4><IMG SRC="logosm.gif" HSPACE=1.5 ALIGN=right>
<h2>Secular Franciscan Order</h2><P><HR><P>
<h2>Chapter One</h2>
<H3>The Regional Fraternity</H3>
 <B>1. The Regional Fraternity of Divine Mercy is an organic union
of all of the local Fraternities officially established by the
Directive Board of the National Fraternity of the United States
of America in the lower peninsula of the state of Michigan and
Toledo, Ohio.
<BR>
2. The Regional Fraternity shall have a Regional Council made
up of Regional officers and representatives of the canonically
established local Fraternities of the Region.
<BR>
3, The Regional Fraternity shall have a Regional Executive Council
made up of its officers and a regional spiritual assistant.
<BR>
4. Once constituted, The Regional Fraternity of Divine Mercy may
recommend the establishment of new local Fraternities, according
to the provisions of the General Constitutions and the General and National Statutes.
<BR>
5, Regional Guidelines may be amended from time to time by an
absolute majority vote of all of the members of the Regional Council.
<BR>
<H2>Chapter Two</H2>
<h3>The Regional Council</h3>
<BR>
6. The Regional Fraternity is represented most fully in the Regional
Council.  
<BR>
a. The Regional Council is composed of:
<BR>
1) the Regional Executive Council;
<BR>
2) local Fraternity Ministers;
<BR>
3) the members of the Regional Council of Spiritual Assistants.
<BR>
(This Council represents a collegial union of those who have been
appointed by their various Ministers Provincial to represent the
three First Order Obediences within the Region.)
<BR>
b. The Regional Council shall meet at least once a year to promote
the life of the Regional Fraternity and the local Fraternities.
<BR>
c. The Regional Council suggests and approves policies to be implemented
by the Regional Executive Council.   
<BR>
7. At the time of election of the Regional Minister, the Regional
Council shall also function as the Chapter of Elections. 
<BR>
a. The National
<BR>
Minister or his/her delegate shall preside at and confirm the
election of the Regional Minister. 
<BR>
b. The Regional Minister may not, at the same time, hold the office of Minister at two levels. A local Fraternity Minister may be nominated
for Regional Minister; but if elected, (s)he must resign the former
office.
<BR>
c. The Regional Council shall determine nomination procedures
in accordance with the provisions of general and particular law.
<BR>
d. Election procedures shall follow the norms of general and particular
law. Therefore, there shall be only one vote allocated to each
local Fraternity.
<BR>
8. Fifty percent plus one of the membership of the Regional Council
constitutes a quorum for doing official business at any meeting.
<BR>

9. The common fund of the Regional Fraternity is supported financially
by its canonically established local Fraternities. The Regional
Council shall determine the annual contribution made from the
common fund of each local Fraternity for each of its active Professed
members.
<BR>
<h2>Chapter Three</h2>
<h3>The Regional Executive Council</h3>
<BR>
10. The Regional Fraternity is animated and guided by the Regional
Executive Council. The Regional Executive Council is composed
of the following voting members:
<BR>
a. The Regional Minister, the Regional Vice Minister, Secretary,
Treasurer and at least four elected Councilors, each of whom is
elected according to the norms of applicable law at the Regional
Fraternity Council. This is held every third year. 
<BR>
b. The Regional Minister of Formation, shall be elected by the Regional Executive Council subsequent to its own election, which
officers shall then be added as voting members to the Regional
Executive Council.
<BR>
c. The President of the Conference of Regional Spiritual Assistants.
<BR>
11. Together with the Regional Executive Council, the President of the Conference of Regional Spiritual Assistants
<BR>
a. Provides for the spiritual welfare of the Regional Fraternity,
<BR>
b. Assists in achieving the purposes of the Regional Council and
provides such other assistance and advice as may be requested
from time to time.
<BR>
c. is exempt from voting on financial matters.
<BR>
12. The purpose of the Regional Executive Council is as follows:
<BR>
a. To foster cooperation and communion among the local Fraternities,
to suggest helpful policies to the Regional Council and to carry
out the decisions and policies of the Regional Council. 
<BR>
b. To foster contact with other branches of the Franciscan family within
the Region;
<BR>
c. To make the Charism of our Seraphic Father present in the life
and mission of the Church wherein the Region is located; 
<BR>
d. To promote knowledge of the Franciscan way of life and commitment
to it;  
<BR>
e. To approve formation programs for the instruction of Inquirers
and Candidates in the local Fraternities;  
<BR>
f. To provide a forum for discussion of common problems and goals;
<BR>
g. To be a voice in the public forum for Secular Franciscans;
<BR>
h. To represent Secular Franciscans in contacts with other church
or civil organizations, and to promote mutual relationships with
such other organizations when appropriate;
<BR>
i. To make Fraternal and Pastoral V1sits to local Fraternities
when requested, and according to the provisions of general and
particular law.
<BR>
j. To provide, in general, for the life of Secular Franciscans
at the level of the Regional Fraternity. 
<BR>
k. To present the agenda for the Annual Regional Council.   
<BR>
13. The Regional Executive Council meets at least twice each year,
at a time and in a place determined by its membership.
<BR>
14. Special meetings may be called at the request of the Regional
Minister or at the written request of two or more members of the elected Councilors.
<BR>
15. Notice of Regional Executive Council Meetings shall again
be given in writing by the Regional Minister at least one month
prior to the meeting.
<BR>
16. Fifty percent plus one of the Regional Executive Council members
constitutes a quorum for doing official business at any meeting.
<BR>
<h2>Chapter Four</h2>
<h3>The Regional Officers</h3>
<BR>
17. The Regional Minister is the chief executive officer of the Regional
Fraternity.
<BR>
a, The Regional Minister shall carry out the duties of his/her
office as determined by the provisions of general and particular
law.    b. In addition to the duties prescribed by norms
of the Secular Franciscan Order, the Regional Minister shall preside
at the meetings of the Regional Executive Council and the Regional
Council.  The Regional Minister is the spokesperson for the Regional
Fraternity in all contacts with other church and civil organizations
as well as with the general public.
<BR>
18. In addition to the duties assigned by general and particular
law, the Regional Vice Minister performs such duties as the Regional
Council may designate.
<BR>
19. The Regional Secretary distributes and keeps all records of
the minutes of both the Regional Executive Council and Council;
preserves the important documents and correspondence of the Regional
Fraternity; assists the Regional Minister in sending out announcements
of forthcoming meetings of the Regional Executive Council and
Council; and performs such other duties as the Regional Executive
Council requests.
<BR>
20. The Regional Treasurer keeps accounts of all money and has
the oversee of the property of the Regional Fraternity, unless
otherwise determined by the Regional Executive Council. The Treasurer
deposits all funds of the Regional Fraternity in such bank accounts
as the Regional Council designates and in the name of the Regional
Fraternity.
<BR>
21. The Regional Treasurer shall make Financial Reports for approval
at each regular meeting of the Regional Executive Council and
Regional Council.
<BR>
22. The Regional Treasurer pays out money, by check only, as the
business of the Regional Fraternity may require on the order of
the Regional Executive Council. All checks over S300 need the
signatures of both the Treasurer and the Minister.
<BR>
23, An audit shall be conducted once a year by two Professed members
selected by the Regional Executive Council and who do not currently
serve on the Executive Council.
<BR>
<h2>Chapter Five</h2>
<h3>Relations with the National Fraternity Council</h3>
<BR>
24. Once every three years the Regional Minister and Executive
Council must invite the National Minister to make a Fraternal
Visit to the Regional Fraternity. A Fraternal Visit by the National
Minister may also be requested at other times for important reasons.
<BR>
25. Once every three years the Regional Minister, with the consent
of the Regional Executive Council, must request a Pastoral Visit
from the National Conference of Spiritual Assistants.
<BR>
26. The Regional Minister is a member of the National Fraternity
Council and is to attend its meetings. If (s)he is impeded from
attending the annual meeting of the National Fraternity Council,
(s)he shall be represented by the Regional Vice Minister or, if
necessary, by some other member elected for that purpose.
<BR>
27. The common fund of the Regional Fraternity shall pay the travel
expenses of the Regional Executive Council when on official business.
<BR>
28. The Regional Fraternity contributes annually to the common
fund of the National Fraternity as called for by the directives
of the National Fraternity Council.<BR>
<h2>Chapter Six</h2>
<h3>Process for Establishing a New Fraternity (from the Constitutions,
Art. 46)</h3>
29. For the valid establishment of a local fraternity, at least
five professed members are required. The admission and profession
of these first brothers and sisters will be received by the council
of another local fraternity or by the council of a higher level
which will have provided for their formation in appropriate ways.
 The acts of admission and profession and the decree of establishment
are preserved in the records of the fraternity. Copies are sent
to the council of the higher level.
<BR>
<h2>Chapter Seven</h2>
<h3>Process of disbanding a Fraternity</h3>
30. If a Fraternity has lost the stability it has had in the past
and thereby becomes unable to be of spiritual advantage to its
members, the Regional Minister and Executive Council, at the request
of the remaining members of the Fraternity, may declare the Fraternity
disbanded.
<BR>
31. Should a Fraternity be disbanded, provision must be made for
the remaining members to affiliate with another active Fraternity.
<BR>
32, The record books of the disbanded Fraternity shall be returned
to the Regional Executive Council as soon as possible. If anything
remains in the Common Fund, it shall be disposed of according
to the wishes of the remaining members.
<BR>
33. A fraternity does not cease to exist until 100 years after the death of its last member.
<h2>Chapter Eight</h2>
<h3>Process for Reactivating a Fraternity</h3>
34. At least five professed Secular Franciscans, at least three
of whom have been active participants in their fraternities for
a period of at least three out of the last five years, are necessary
for reactivating a fraternity. The original five should have completed
their candidacy and made profession before the official proceedings
for reactivating a fraternity may begin.
<BR>
35. In the formative stages of the reactivated Fraternity, the
interested Secular Franciscans involved shall seek the guidance
of the Regional Minister and Executive Council and shall request
the necessary materials for building the community, including
Rituals, and Formation continuing education materials.
<BR>
36. A formal request shall be made in writing to the Regional
Executive Council, expressing the group's desire to reactivate
a fraternity.
<BR>
37. After the Executive Secretary receives the request, (s)he
shall check to see whether a fraternity had been established.
 If it is found that a fraternity does already exist, at least
canonically and on paper, and the required time for canonical
dissolution has not yet elapsed, the request then is designated
the Reactivation of a Fraternity.
<BR>
38. After the above steps have been completed, the following procedure
shall take place:
<BR>
a. At least five professed Secular Franciscans are needed to constitute
a reactivated fraternity.   
<BR>
b. The reception and profession of the five members making the
request for reactivation must have been completed before the process
begins,  
<BR>
c. The level of Fraternity that is assisting the five in their
request shall confirm by letter that item b. has been carried
out. The same confirming fraternity shall include a letter of
Petition for Reactivation signed by the five. The letter of Petition
shall include the following information:
<BR>
1) Which of the professed members is to be the leader;
<BR>
2) Whom the group requests for a Spiritual Assistant
<BR>
3) Whether the old record books are still available or new ones
have been purchased;  
<BR>
4) That the records of the professed members are available and
ready to be transferred when Regional approval is given;
<BR>
5) That group members are aware of the responsibilities they must
assume as a local Fraternity with regards to the Councils of the
higher Fraternities.
<BR>
6) That an invitation shall be sent to a higher Fraternity for
a fraternal visit prior to reactivation.   
<BR>
d. The assisting fraternity shall help the newly reactivated Fraternity  in every way possible.<BR>
e. Once the group receives official notice from the Regional Minister,
there shall be no waiting period, nor is there any period of probation.
<BR>
f. The Council of Regional Assistants shall confirm by letter
the official approval or appointment of the local Spiritual Assistant
to the newly reactivated Fraternity, and the same shall see that
this local Spiritual Assistant has a copy of the Statutes for
Spiritual Assistants.
<BR>
39. Should the Executive Secretary determine that there is no
record of a Canonically Established Fraternity, then Guidelines
Chapter Six, the process for Establishing a New Fraternity, is
to be observed.
<h2>Chapter Nine</h2>
<h3>Active Members</h3>
40. An Active member is:
<BR>
a. A professed member who participates both by attending Fraternity
meetings and by providing financial support to the community
<BR>
  b, A professed member who has been dispensed (excused)
from attending Fraternity meetings, either on a temporary or permanent
basis, but does provide financial support to the community.
<BR>
c. A professed member who neither attends meetings nor supports
the community but whom the Fraternity has dispensed (excused)
from such obligations.
<BR>
<h2>Chapter Ten</h2>
<h3>Dispensed (Excused) Members</h3>
41. The term Dispensed (Excused) means that, as members of their
Fraternity, these professed members have been granted a special
status for reasonable cause by the Fraternity Council with the
approval of the Spiritual Assistant.
<BR>
a. This means that they are dispensed from attendance at the monthly
meetings due to:
<BR>
1) age
<BR>
2) illness
<BR>
3) lack of transportation
<BR>
4) incompatible working conditions
<BR>
a. other circumstances deemed acceptable to the local Council
<BR>
b. Such dispensed persons are not freed from other obligations
including: 
<BR>
1) Praying a daily Office
<BR>
2) Wearing some outward symbol of the Order
<BR>
3) Contributing to the Fraternity Common Fund. However a members
whose income or resources are so meager that (s)he is unable to
contribute to the Common Fund may be dispensed from that obligation.
<BR>
42. A dispensed (excused) member is just as much a member of the
Fraternity as is the person who does not need a dispensation from
any Secular Franciscan obligation.
<BR>
a. Therefore, the fraternity has an obligation to maintain contact
with its Dispensed Members and to visit and communicate with them.
<BR>
b. By the same token the Dispensed Member has an obligation to
keep in contact as far as possible with the Fraternity even though
(s)he is dispensed from one or more of the obligations of Secular
Franciscan life.
<BR>
43. Fraternity Councils, when determining the total membership
of their Fraternity, shall include all of their Active Members
regardless of whether or not some are dispensed from one or more
of the traditional obligations of the Secular Franciscan Rule.
<BR>
44. Dispensation should be reviewed annually by the Council of the local Fraternity.
<BR>
<h2>Chapter Eleven</h2>
<h3>Lapsed Members</h3>
45. Professed Secular Franciscans who neither attend meetings
nor support the Fraternity financially and who, after personal
invitations to return to the Fraternity, reject or ignore the
invitation, shall be termed Lapsed and shall not be carried on
the Fraternity's membership rolls. Nor shall they be reported
as members of the National Fraternity.
<BR>
<h2>Chapter Twelve</h2>
<BR>
<h3>Fair Share Contribution</h3>
<BR>
46. The Fair Share refers to the amount of money which each Fraternity
contributes, to the Common Fund of the Region in order that the
Regional Fraternity may meet its operating expenses and make its
Fair Share Contribution to the National Fraternity.
<BR>
47. The amount of money needed to operate the Regional Fraternity
each year is planned by the Regional Treasurer. A tentative budget
is then submitted to the Ministers of the local Fraternities at
the annual meeting of the Regional Council. At that time the budget
may be amended or adjusted before it is voted on and approved
by the Regional Council  
<BR>
48. The money needed to meet the annual budget is raised by asking
the Fraternities of the Region to contribute some share toward
the total amount needed. This share shall be in proportion to
the size of each Fraternity's active membership.
<BR>
49. This Gift comes to the Region from the Council of the local Fraternity.
<h2>Chapter Thirteen</h2>
<h3>Pastoral and Fraternal Visitation</h3>
50. The Goals of the Visitation include:
<BR>
a. To promote fidelity to the Franciscan Charism; 
<BR>
b. To promote observance of the Rule; 
<BR>
c. To support the life of the Fraternity.
<BR>
51. Ways of achieving the above goals through a Visitation include:
<BR>
a. Helping a Fraternity to evaluate itself;
<BR>
b. Providing inspiration and information;
<BR>
c. Providing an experience of unity within the Region and within
the Order.   
<BR>
52. The operation of Visitations shall be a follows: 
<BR>
a. Each Fraternity shall request pastoral and Fraternal Visitation
from the Regional Minister at least twelve months prior to the
due date.
<BR>
b. The Regional Council of Spiritual Assistants should plan to
provide a minimum of one Pastoral Visitation every three years
to each Fraternity.
<BR>
c. The Pastoral Visitation shall be carried out by the designated
Regional Spiritual Assistant or his delegate jointly with the
Fraternal Visitation whenever possible.
<BR>
d. Before Visitations begin the Fraternal Visitor(s) should meet
with the Pastoral Visitor(s) for a planning session.
<BR>
53. The responsibilities of the Fraternal Visitor shall be as
follows: 
<BR>
a. Carry out an evaluation of the Fraternity including:
<BR>
1) Minutes of the Council meetings
<BR>
2) Treasurer's books
<BR>
b. May also examine and discuss:
<BR>
1) Style and quality of Fraternity leadership
<BR>
2) Structure and effectiveness of monthly meeting
<BR>
3) Fraternity's response to higher Fraternities and the local
Church.   
<BR>
4) Needs of individual Fraternity members
<BR>
5) Ongoing development of spiritual life within the Fraternity.
<BR>
54. The responsibilities of the Pastoral Visitor shall be as follows:
<BR>
a. Carry out an evaluation of the Fraternity including:
<BR>
1) The register of receptions and professions to ascertain the
growth or decline of the Fraternity.   
<BR>
2) The prayer life of the Fraternity.
<BR>
3) The community life and Franciscan Charism of the Fraternity.
<BR>
4) The Formation ongoing education of the Fraternity.
<BR>
5) The ministry of the local Spiritual Assistant 
<BR>
b. May also examine and discuss:
<BR>
1) Needs of individual Fraternity members
<BR>
2) Specific areas of growth and correction when needed.
<BR>
55. Reporting
<BR>
a. The Visitor(s) in cooperation with the Pastoral Visitor(s)
shall make a written report of the Visitation and send it to the
Regional Minister, who is in charge of distribution.
<BR>
b. The report shall contain evaluative comments regarding:
<BR>
1) The prayer and community life of the Fraternity
<BR>
2) The formation and continuing education of members
<BR>
3) Rapport with higher Fraternities and the local Church.
<BR>
56. Stipends
<BR>
a. The Regional Council shall offer a stipend to members of the
Executive Regional Council and the Regional Council of Spiritual
Assistants. This stipend shall be commensurate with the cost of
transportation and other expenses incurred in the course of the
exercise of their various offices while within the borders of
the Region.
<BR>
b. The Council of each local Fraternity shall offer a stipend
to Fraternal and Pastoral Visitors. This stipend shall be commensurate
with the cost of transportation and other expenses incurred solely
within the borders of the Region. 
<BR>
c. The Regional Council shall provide transportation for the Regional
Minister or in his/her place, a duly elected delegate, to attend
annual meetings of the National Fraternity.
<BR>
<h2>Chapter Fourteen</h2>
<h3>Regional Fraternity Elections</h3>
57. A minimum of three (3) months prior to the date of elections,
<BR>
a. The Regional Minister, together with the Executive Council,
shall appoint a Nominating Committee of three members. One member
of said committee shall be appointed as Chairperson,
<BR>
b. The Fraternity Minister shall send a Request for Elections
Form or letter to the Chairperson of Elections. This communication
shall include:
<BR>
1) the time, date and location of the election
<BR>
2) the name and address of the Chairperson of the Nominating Committee.
 <BR>
58. Responsibilities of the Nominating Committee
<BR>
a. Elicit from the members of the Regional Council recommendations
for nomination for the offices to be filled. These recommendations
should be submitted to the Nominating Committee in writing.
<BR>
b. Confirm the qualifications and willingness of the nominees
to serve. 
<BR>
c. The responsibilities of the nominating committee are merely
utilitarian. Members of the nominating committee may be elected
to office.
<BR>
59. All other election procedures are to be carried out according
to the Constitutions of the Order.  </H3> 
<BR>
<I>Approved by the Divine Mercy Regional Council April 23, 1994</i>
