<A NAME="rawa">
</A>

<H4>RAWA Continues to Improve City's Water System..</H4>

<H4>Entech is in the midst of three major design efforts for the Reading Area Water Authority (RAWA).</H4><P>

These projects include the replacement of two severely deteriorated 16" water mains which hang from the Penn Street and Bingaman Street Bridges and span the Schuylkill River in the city of Reading, and the structural rehabilitation of RAWA's twin 13-million-gallon Northwest Reservoirs.  Both Entech and RAWA have placed these projects on a "fast track" due to the extent of structure deterioration which was discovered during a feasibility study that Entech performed last spring.<P>

The water main replacement projects are almost identical in that they both require the installation of a new, 18" ductile iron water main which will run parallel to the existing deteriorated and structurally unsound 16" wrought-iron water mains, and the installation of new structural support/pipe hanger systems.  Once the new mains are installed across the bridges, tie-ins/hot taps will be made on either side of the bridge to activate the new main.  With the new mains active, the old mains will then be cut out in sections and removed in order to reduce the amount of weight hanging from the bridge structures.  Entech is closely coordinating the water main replacement work, in particular, the structural support/pipe hanger system design, with PennDOT Bridge Unit officials to ensure a structurally adequate support system is obtained without jeopardizing the structural integrity of both PennDOT bridges.<P>

With respect to the Bingaman Street Bridge, Entech is also in the process of coordinating a possible joint venture between RAWA and the local gas company (UGI) as UGI has a 6" gas main on the same bridge which is also in need of replacement. Because both utilities (RAWA and UGI) need to replace their structures/mains in the immediate future and since the gas main is within a very close proximity of the water main, Entech believes it makes sense for both utilities to work together on this particular project as a sharing of the costs (if both projects are done simultaneously), will significantly reduce the cost to each party.<P>

With respect to the Northwest Reservoir project, Entech is designing the removal and replacement of unsound, severely deteriorated and/or missing sections of concrete on the roof systems of the 13 MG tanks.  The tanks have literally taken a beating over the last few winters and are in need of structural rehabilitation in order to maintain the structural integrity of the tanks and to avoid the major capital cost associated with replacement.<P>

Entech's goal is to have its design effort complete and have the projects submitted to the Pennsylvania Infrastructure Investment Authority (PENNVEST) for funding assistance by January 1997.  The combined construction cost of these projects is estimated to be $1.5 million.<P>

<H4><A HREF="mailto:SCarl@entecheng.novell.net">Scott M. Carl</A></H4>
<H5>Project Manager</H5>

<A HREF="#top">Return to Top</A><P>

