<A NAME="cac">
</A>
<H4>Community Action - We're Involved</H4><P>

<H4>CAC,  12/96</H4>

Junior Achievement held its annual fund raiser at Berks Bowling Lanes on Sunday, November 10.  Brent Estock, civil designer, assisted with the coordination of the event and also volunteered to design signs which were placed throughout the bowling alley.  Brent acted as Entech's chairperson, recruiting other employees' participation.<P>

Bright and early Sunday morning two Entech teams reported to the bowling alley and attempted to roll a respectable score. Team members consisted of the Lloyd family: Matt and Sandi  and their four children; Sue DeHaven; Danette and Erik Ernst; and the Estock family, Brent with children, Heather and Wesley.<P>

Junior Achievement raised $23,000, of which over $400 was raised by the Entech team by  soliciting pledges from their family and friends for this worthwhile association.  <P>

The teams are looking forward to participating in next year's event even though Brent's young son Wesley showed greater bowling prowess than most of the adults. However, a suggestion was made from one who prefers to remain anonymous that next year young Wesley remain at home. <P>

<A HREF="mailto:SDeHaven@entecheng.novell.net"><EM>Sue DeHaven</EM></A>, Business Development Coordinator<P>

Every year the United Way starts off its campaign with a "Day of Caring."  This is an opportunity for volunteers to see the programs that United Way funds, and the results that are achieved by this funding.  This day also allows the volunteers to get a first-hand perspective of the need that exists in our community and can voice that need to fellow employees in order to increase contributions.  Due to the generous contributions collected last year, the United Way has added six new agencies to their list this year while continuing to support its other agencies.  The financial support that is donated by Berks County residents to United Way is used locally to help Berks and other outlining counties.<P>

This year I was given the opportunity to participate in the "Day of Caring."  I spent my morning playing soccer with the children at KidsPeace, which is an alternative school for children between six years of age to nineteen years of age.  A full-time psychiatric nurse is on duty to help children cope with their feelings by one-on-one counseling, group therapy and home treatment.  The home treatment program allows the school to develop a close relationship with the family in order to pull all available resources together to help the child achieve goals.  The children earn rewards for achieving these goals in order to promote good behavior and to increase the desire for continued learning.  This school is not for permanent placement, but a structured environment, with individually developed programs that teach the student and their family the necessary tools to function as a family and achieve remarkable results...together.<P>

After spending a morning interacting with some of these children, it was comforting to know that money donated to United Way has a substantial impact on our community and helps our children learn to excel in all aspects of life...the way it should be...the United Way.<P>

<A HREF="mailto:MDelvalle@entecheng.novell.net"><EM>Melissa A. Delvalle</EM></A>, Receptionist<P>

