<A NAME="principals">
</A>

<STRONG>PRINCIPAL'S NOTES</STRONG><BR>
<A HREF="mailto:BMcMahon@entecheng.novell.net"><EM>William M. McMahon Jr., PE, President</EM></A><P>

	<STRONG>PROGRESS THROUGH EFFICIENCY</STRONG><P>

	The progress of civilization is created in part by humanity's ability to increase efficiency and overcome the problems of nature.  These increases are actually the sum effect of millions of small steps taken by individuals and organizations through learning, experimenting, risking and working.  The number of items for improvement is almost limitless.<P>

	At the leading edge of this progress have always been men and women of science, and  in one form or another, the engineers of their day.  We are proud to be in the company of such great people and we carry with great passion that mission with us today.<P>

	As you know, Entech has been one of the leaders of increased energy efficiency for clients, both large and small.<P>

	One area of our work that gets little attention is cost savings through client manpower reductions.  With each of our projects the aim is to do "more with less" by using proven technology and common sense.<P>

	As a simple example, consider the lowly exit light.  Old-style exit lights burned out several times a year, which required new bulbs and someone to make the change. This amounted to two hours of someone's time per exit light. Today with new LED technology, lights never need to be changed, and even better are the significant energy savings.  For a facility with many exit signs, efficiency gains are substantial.<P>

	Another example of reducing manpower costs is in central boiler plant operations.  Normally, there are several operators needed to cover round-the-clock operations.  When Shippensburg University approved Entech's summer shutdown strategy, six operators were then available to assist in other campus maintenance projects in the non-heating season, creating a huge cost savings.<P>

	Taking cost savings even further, Entech has found that by automating boiler plants, converting to newer boilers, or contracting for outside services (on call), college campuses, hospitals, military bases, government facilities, etc. can realize large annual cost savings, normally hundreds of thousands of dollars per year. Knowing that Entech's efforts have contributed to the reduction of our clients energy costs, totaling millions of dollars per year, is a satisfying feeling that spurs us on to do even more.<P>

	It has been estimated that the present value of one operation or maintenance worker is approximately $1 million over 20-30 years.  While efficiency improvements do dislocate workers, our experience has been that the workers are retrained and actually advance in their careers.  This becomes a true win-win situation for all involved.<P>

	I would be remiss not to mention the great efficiency gains by new central chiller equipment.  There are thousands of older units operating in the 0.8 kw/ton range, which also face serious chlorofluorocarbon (CFC) emission legal compliance issues.  By using new variable frequency controlled equipment and centralized plant operations, clients commonly see overall efficiencies fall below 0.5 kw/ton and savings as high as 50%.<P>

	The greatest enemy of progress is inaction. The energy industry generally agrees that, despite many years of improvement, 80% of energy efficiency opportunities remain to be accomplished even with today's technology.  We at Entech are looking forward to a bright, efficient, and progressive future.

<P>
<A HREF="#top">Return to Top</A><P>

<HR>

<A NAME="law"></A>

<H4><EM>ENTECH wants you to know..........DEREGULATION NOW LAW</EM></H4><P>

On December 3, 1996, Governor Tom Ridge signed into law the bill to give every Pennsylvanian the ability to choose their electrical company by the year 2001.  Ridge stated the measure will help to make the Commonwealth a more attractive place to live and work by lowering electric bills and introducing competition into the electric utility market for the first time in Pennsylvania history.<P>

Key provisions of the new law are as follows:<P>

<UL><LI>The obligation to provide customers with transmission and distribution service will continue.</UL>

<UL><LI>Programs to assist low-income families will continue.</UL>

<UL><LI>The transmission and distribution system will be required to meet established national industry standards for installation, maintenance and safety.</UL>

<UL><LI>Rates will be capped for all generation, transmission and distribution charges for at least 4-1/2 years and as long as 9 years.</UL>

 <UL><LI>Utilities can recover their transition and stranded costs by issuing transition bonds.</UL>

<UL><LI>Retail choice will be phased in as follow: 33% of all customer load on 1/1/99, an additional 33% of all customer load on 1/1/00 and 100% of all customer load by 1/1/01.</UL>

<UL><LI>The PUC can order electric utilities to conduct pilot programs beginning 4/1/97.  5% of the utility's peak load will be committed to the pilot program.</UL>

<UL><LI>All generation suppliers must be licensed by the PUC and ensure financial responsibility.</UL>
	 	
<UL><LI>Cooperatives will continue to be self-regulated and must follow the same rules as other electric suppliers.  Municipalities will maintain their current status and will operate solely within their municipal districts.</UL>
	 	
<UL><LI>The bill supports changes to federal clean air laws to protect Pennsylvania's environment.</UL>
	 	
<UL><LI>The PUC will monitor the market and take steps to address anti-competitive or discriminatory conduct.</UL>

Entech will continue to maintain its leadership role on the impact of electric utility rate structures and cost reduction strategies.  We will gladly assist those electric customers who wish to evaluate the impact of deregulation on their organizations.  It is our opinion that this piece of legislation  will influence energy costs more than any other legislation in the entire decade.<P>

<A HREF="#top">Return to Top</A>

<HR>

<A NAME="projects">
</A>

<H4>Projects We Are Working On Now</H4>

<H3>THE MARKETPLACE</H3>
<H4>12/96</H4>

<STRONG>MUNICIPAL</STRONG><P>

Entech is currently providing the Municipal Authority of the Borough of Shenandoah (MABS) with construction management, engineering support and project closeout services related to their newly constructed 3.2 MGD water filtration plant.  The plant is part of a $6 million improvement/construction project funded by the Pennsylvania Infrastructure Investment Authority (PENNVEST) which provides low interest funding and grant money for water and sewer system improvements.  This current PENNVEST project is one of many PENNVEST projects with which Entech has been involved.<P>

Additionally, Entech is providing MABS with the engineering services required for the inspection and preparation of annual dam inspection reports for Raven Run Dams #2 and #3  and Ringtown Dams #5 and #6.<P>
	 
<STRONG>GOVERNMENTAL</STRONG><P>

Entech was assigned its 150th project from the Pennsylvania Industrial Development Authority (PIDA).  PIDA provides low-interest financing to encourage companies to move to, or expand their facilities in, Pennsylvania.  Entech has performed engineering services in the amount of $400,000 to date, with an additional $142,000 of active PIDA project work in-house.  Construction costs total approximately $100 million for the acquisition, renovation and new construction of 5 million square feet of industrial space.<P>

Entech continues its efforts to reduce the energy budget of the US Army. We recently began our ninth commission to analyze, consider,  and document opportunities for government installations to either reduce energy consumption or reduce the cost of their energy. Our history of finding large savings meeting the governments strict criteria has lead to the award of this additional work. The focus of this latest effort is the Edgewood Area of the Aberdeen Proving Grounds. Edgewood is an Army research facility which consumes large quantities of electricity. Entech's mission is to find opportunities to save electrical costs, while maintaining the integrity of the Post's extensive safety systems.  As with most assignments at APG,  this one promises to be both challenging and exciting.  <P>

Entech's contract with the Department of Conservation and Natural Resources continues with the addition of office space to an existing office at the Shikellamy State Park.  Shikellamy is located at the southernmost tip of an island where the west branch of the Susquehanna joins the Susquehanna River.  Included in this project is the extension of mechanical and electrical systems to accommodate the heating, air conditioning, and lighting of a conference area, manager office, and entry vestibule.  The design allows for after-hour entry of groups who will use the conference room for community meetings.<P>

<STRONG>INDUSTRIAL</STRONG><P>

Corning, Incorporated of Corning, New York manufactures glass and ceramic products for a variety of markets.  Recently, Entech assisted Corning with the design development of a new Class 10 cleanroom at their Sullivan Park R&D Center near Corning.  Entech served as a Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) modeling consultant to Corning, studying the relationships of flow and temperature within the cleanroom during operation.  Study of process equipment geometries and the associated room heat gain sources were critical for controlling the environment.  Recommendations were made that included modifications to the raised flooring.  Investigations of local exhaust effects, etc. were also performed.<P>

Elf Atochem North America, Ltd., in Birdsboro, Pennsylvania manufactures polymer materials.  Recently, Entech assisted Atochem with reviewing a number of areas for process improvement.  Projects included an evaluation of a process cooling water system for their downstream pumps and heat exchanger packages which control the temperature of their process melters and reactors.  Subsequent findings and design changes are presently being implemented which include: new, larger pumps; side-stream filtration; balancing of flows to 34 pieces of process equipment; and additional instrumentation monitoring for improving operator control.<P>

Entech also performed a study of potential replacement fluids for their process heating medium, Dowtherm A.  Each fluid was evaluated for: heat transfer performance; system requirements such as pressure, temperature, etc.; environmental issues; health and safety; and life cycle costing.  A comparative study was presented that concluded with a recommendation to continue with Dowtherm A, while minimizing the problems associated with this fluid.<P>

<STRONG>UTILITY</STRONG><P>

Entech is pleased to be involved with recent changes at GPU Energy, including the "tenant fit-out" of space at the Berks Corporate Center which will accommodate the FMIS Group.  This work involved the relocation of lighting and ceiling diffusers and the layout of workstations and computer equipment to meet the needs of the tenant.  Unique to this project was the extremely short schedule which necessitated a "design-build" approach to the project.  Working with GPU Energy contractors, construction began only a short period after the contract was awarded to Entech.<P>

<A HREF="#top">Return to Top</A>

<H5>Posted January 23, 1997</H5>

 
