 <HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Commercial Projects</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ff ff ff" LINK="#FF 00 00 " VLINK="#FF 00 00">
<TABLE WIDTH=591 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR>
	<TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=15>
	</TD>

</TR>	
<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50>
	</TD> 

	<TD VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=100>

	</TD>

	<TD VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=290>
	<H4>Entech Facilities Projects:
	<BR>Design and Consulting
	<BR>HVAC and Electrical Renovations</H4>
	</TD>

	<TD  VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=150>
	<BR><TABLE WIDTH=150 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
		<TR ALIGN=left>			
			<TD WIDTH=10%>
			<A HREF="../index.html">
			<IMG SRC="graphics/diamond.gif" BORDER=0></A>
			</TD>
			<TD WIDTH=90%>
			<A HREF="../index.html">Main Menu</A>
			</TD>
		</TR>
		</TABLE>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50>
	</TD> 

	<TD VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=100>
	</TD>

	<TD COLSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=440>
		<HR>

<P><B>1500 Market Street; Philadelphia, PA - Renovations</B> Centre Square is a 2.1 million square foot office building located directly across from City Hall in center city Philadelphia.  The facility includes two office towers, one of approximately 1,000,000 square feet and another of approximately 650,000 square feet which are joined by a six level (3 subterranean) combination atrium/parking garage.  Placed in operation in 1974, Centre Square remains as the largest office complex in the City and is the largest cast-in-place concrete structure in the State.  With the construction of new Class A office buildings nearby, the Centre Square owners, in 1986, embarked on a major renovation program exceeding $80 million intended to maintain the pre-eminent position in the commercial market place.  A summary of projects with which Entech was involved is as follows:

<P>	1)	<EM>Parking Garage Design/Repairs - Completed: 1990</EM>

		This project included significant reconstructive structural repairs and waterproofing to a cast-in-place concrete parking garage providing parking for 450 vehicles.  Storm drainage systems were repaired and/or modified as required.  Entech considered several types of lighting fixtures and lamps for this garage which is totally underground and receives no natural light.  The entire	garage was completely renovated and new lighting, wiring and distribution system were installed.

<P>	2)	<EM>Plaza-Lobby Renovations - Completed: 1991</EM>
	
		This project was the cornerstone of the capital program since it was the most publicly visible of the many projects undertaken.  The project was broken into two broad categories of exterior (plaza) and interior (lobby) work which was scheduled into a total of thirty work phases.

		<P>The exterior phases included demolition to the extensive public plaza, sidewalks, curbs and window wall systems at street level which permitted the replacement of a complex subterranean waterproofing system.  This waterproofing system serves as the "roof" for the underground pedestrian concourse which connects Centre Square to the areas' mass transit facilities. 
 
		<P>The interior phases of the project included significant modifications to the Galleria which is a central atrium, 80 feet in height, and capped by a combination cast-in-place concrete and aluminum/glass skylight.  The Galleria is ringed by walks on all levels which provide overlooks to a new interior fountain which rises approximately 75 feet from the base of the Galleria and provides the visual focus for the project.

		<P>Entech's services included modification to existing or new fire protection, HVAC and electrical systems for each retail area, replacements and enhancements of all interior and exterior lighting systems; establishment of a new command/control center for the relocated fire alarm system, elevator control system and a new security monitoring and access system for the entire complex; design of atrium smoke exhaust system to meet present fire codes.  The glass skylight presented unique challenges to provide beam type smoke detection and supply and exhaust systems at other locations.  This system is initiated by activating any of several infrared beam detectors.

		<P>Several retail spaces at street level were restaurants which incorporated kitchen exhaust systems discharging into areas directly outside the atrium (some were not ducted to the outside at all) and entering the atrium.  Entech designed a system of kitchen exhaust ductwork common to all existing (and potential) restaurant tenants.  The nature of existing conditions required that Entech work with the City of Philadelphia Department of Licensing and Inspections to successfully obtain proper variances for this work.

	
<P>	3.	<EM>East and West Tower Renovations - Completed:  1990/91</EM>

		This project was undertaken to provide upgrades to the office towers.  Work completed under this contract for which Entech had some level of responsibility included:  conversion of the east tower's core HVAC system from constant volume to a variable air volume (VAV) system.  Central fans were modified, variable frequency drives were installed, modifications to the electrical system were completed.  Distribution ductwork modified, tested, insulated.

<P>	4.	<EM>Elevator System Upgrades and Modifications - Completed:  1990</EM>

		Centre Square possesses thirty-seven (37) high speed passenger elevators and six (6) general purpose or freight elevators.  Although the elevators had been well maintained, no significant upgrades had been made to either the aesthetics or operational aspects of the system.  Entech's responsibility included control consolidation and relocation of major components to the new security command/control center.

<P>	5.	<EM>Tenant Improvement Projects - Completed:  1990/93</EM>

		Throughout the duration of the landlord's capital program, a concerted effort was made to retain existing and encourage new tenancy.  Typically, the following projects were constructed in "raw" space devoid of any improvements beyond the base building systems.

<P><B>1515 Market; Philadelphia, PA - Law Office Tenant Renovations</B> Modifications to 18th floor of 1515 Market Street, Philadelphia, to accommodate architectural upgrade for law offices.  Mechanical and electrical design to extend existing building systems into the space for lighting, plumbing, fire protection, and air conditioning systems for new office, computer room and lunch room spaces.

<P><B>1600 Market; Philadelphia, PA - Rest Room Upgrade Program</B> Entech provided mechanical/electrical plans and specifications for upgrading existing rest room facilities to meet new ADA handicap requirements.  While the project generally encompassed replacement and relocation of plumbing fixtures, and handicap fire alarm devices, the new configuration required modifications to sprinkler, ductwork and lighting systems.

<P><B>2000 Market Street; Philadelphia, PA - Renovations</B> 2000 Market Street is a 650,000 square foot office building located on the western edge of Philadelphia's central business district.  As a result of several major lease terminations occurring simultaneously and general pressure of the market place, the owners of 2000 Market committed to a program of capital improvements to accommodate a major tenant.  Prior to and in conjunction with the tenant improvement work, significant improvements were required to be completed by the landlord on the base building systems.  Entech involvement included consulting services for both base building and several tenant mechanical/electrical systems.

<P><B>1500 Walnut Street; Philadelphia, PA - Renovations</B> Consideration was given to ice storage for this Philadelphia building.  Ongoing consulting services include fire protection, HVAC, plumbing and electrical.  Entech provided plans and specifications for a new upscale restaurant tenant as well as a fire pump for the building.

<P><B>Administrative Headquarters for the Episcopal Diocese of Pennsylvania; Philadelphia, PA</B> Entech provided renovations and upgrades to the mechanical and electrical systems for this historic structure in the Society Hill section of Philadelphia.  Formerly occupied by the Mutual Assurance Company, the facility was located in two of the finest American houses in Society Hill, located at 240 South Fourth Street and dating back to 1784.

<P>While extreme care was taken to preserve the original appearance of many of the features, a chilled water central air conditioning system and new electrical service were added.  Improvements were also made to the lighting and plumbing fixtures.  Entech provided plans and specifications detailing the building system additions and modifications.

<P><B>The Berks County Services Center; Reading, PA - Tenant Fit-out</B> Working with a local architectural firm, Entech provided plans and technical specifications for contractor bidding of the mechanical and electrical work for tenant fit-out.  With a typical floor plate of 17,000 square feet, each of the 5th, 9th and 15th floors of this new 16 story office building was upgraded to accommodate several agencies including the District Attorney, Children's Services, Mental Health Services and Employment Training.  Mechanical work included plumbing for new restrooms, coffee stations and lunch areas.  The fire protection system was modified and extended to accommodate new office arrangements.  Ductwork was extended from the base building system with a series of main and branch ductwork schemes which formed a zoned VAV air conditioning system.

<P>Of particular interest is a state-of-the-art Building Automation System (BAS) and the lighting control system.  New supporting equipment was added to effectively connect the HVAC, smoke exhaust, fire alarm and security controls to the BAS backbone framework.  The low voltage, 2 wire lighting control system was similarly upgraded to provide a series of daylight compensating photo electric cells and motion controls which provides all lighting control functions and enhances future relocation of lighting fixtures and controls.

<P><B>Foxcroft Square Pavilion Office Tower; Jenkintown, PA</B> Analysis of building HVAC and electrical systems to determine cost of utilities for the common areas.  Using the Elite Software DDE-2.1D which incorporates historical weather data for local geographical areas, we calculated energy use and generated a model of monthly utility bills specifically for the common areas.

<P><B>Meridian Bank - Headquarters Building; Reading, PA</B> The first step in the design and building of this new headquarter facility was to provided an integrated computer analysis of total building energy use which, from a baseline model reference point, compared energy, construction and life cycle costs for a variety of construction options including heating, ventilating and air conditioning systems, windows, wall and roof insulation, lighting and peak shaving.  This report served to enhance the decision making process as it affected various construction alternatives.

<P>Entech was then assigned the responsibility of providing the electrical and mechanical commercial design of a 140,000 square foot four-story building in the center of downtown Reading to be entirely leased by this banking community.  Entech interfaced the M/E engineering  (HVAC, plumbing, fire protection, electrical) with the owner, architect, and tenant A/E team and a variety of project consultants.

<P><B>PNB Building; Philadelphia, PA - Law Office Renovations</B> Modifications to various floors on an ongoing basis for upgrading to include law library, print shop, and office spaces.  Entech plumbing, fire protection, HVAC and electrical design accommodated a variety of tenant conditions in this existing building which is approximately 70 years old.

<P><B>Rittenhouse Regency; Philadelphia, PA - Tenant Improvements</B> This project included analysis and conceptual design improvements for tenant space of a single tenant occupying 5 floors of space.  In working for the tenant, Entech provided recommendations and cost estimates for improvements to the plumbing, fire protection, air conditioning and electrical system.  Our recommendations, while never implemented, served as a basis for lease negotiations with the landlord.

<P><B>The Robinson Building; Philadelphia, PA - Renovations</B> Entech provided mechanical and electrical design and consulting for renovating several floors of tenant space for this building at South 16th Street, Philadelphia as well as recommendations for upgrading base building air conditioning systems.  Tri water fire protection combining the water source heat pump with the sprinkler system was evaluated.

</p>

	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<HR>


