</DOCHDR>

<html>
<head>
<title>Entech Engineering Utility Deregulation Services</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ff ff ff" link="#7E 00 18" vlink="#7E 00 18">

<img src="graphics/entechtr.gif" width=97 height=73 align=right>
<a href="index.html"><img src="graphics/diamond.gif" border=0>Main Menu</a>

<hr width=85% size=3>



<p><br>
<blockquote><h2>Electric Utility Industry - Deregulation</h2></blockquote><p>

Entech Engineering is presently advising clients on issues related to the deregulation of the electric utility industry.  While all the answers are not yet available, it is important for large and medium size users of electrical power to investigate and plan for the future.  Our background in energy analysis and familiarity with the electric utility industry from an engineering and economic analysis point of view is available to you for your planning.  Please email <a href="mailto:SKarabin@entecheng.novell.net">Steve Karabin</a> for more information.  Or call him at 610-373-6667.

<hr width=85% size=3>

<p><b>Pennsylvania plugged into
electric competition</b>

<p>	Pennsylvania became only the fourth state in the country to plug into electric
competition when a bill that opens the electric industry to competition was passed by the
Senate 40-10 and by the House 171-28, and was signed into law by Governor Tom Ridge.

<p>	The measure will allow all Pennsylvania consumers the opportunity to shop around
for the best deal in electricity by the year 2001.  A pilot program allowing for competition
will begin in 1997.  Starting in 1999, one third of Pennsylvania electric consumers will be
phased into this new competitive arena each year through the year 2001.

<p>	Rates for generation, transmission and distribution of electric will be capped for at
least four years and maybe as long as nine years.  It is expected that electric rates may
decrease because the competitive arena will likely make each electric company find ways
to increase efficiency.

<p>	The Board of Directors of the Berks County Chamber of Commerce unanimously
approved of this legislation at its November meeting.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><br>

<p><b>Framework for Competition</b>

<p>	The new Pennsylvania law opening the electricity industry to competition provides a
framework for utilities, power providers and customers to implement it.  Hers's how it will  work.

<p>		Under the new law, customers--from the smallest homeowner to the largest
factory-- will get to shop for their electricity source, the generator.  Customers will be able
to buy from anybody selling electricity, whether an actual generator or a middleman
marketer.  Competition in the market will set the prices, subject to a temporary price cap.

<p>		That electricity, however, still will be delivered by the local utility, since nobody
wants a dozen companies' wires running down the street.  That separate delivery charge,
since it will continue under monopoly, will continue to need approval by the state Public
Utility Commission.

<p>		A third of a given utility's customers--a portion each of the residential,
commercial and industrial accounts--must have the shopping option by January 1, 1999;
another third by January 1, 2000; and the final third by January 1, 2001.

<p>		Total electricity rates are capped temporarily as of January 1, 1997.  The
generating portion is capped until 2001, when all customers have the shopping option. 
The delivery portion will be determined by the PUC.

<p>		Electricity bills will be split into several parts early on to show the cost of each,
particularly three: generation, delivery and a new competitive transition charge.  No matter
what those portions are, they may not add up to more than the current rate and possibly
will be less.

<p>	The transition charge is aimed at helping utilities pay off the expensive plants they
were required to build under the old regulated system, when they had to have capacity for
everybody in their territory running at full power, as well as a hefty reserve.  The law gives
the transition charge a nine-year lifetime, beginning January 1, 1997, although the PUC
can lengthen it or shorten it a bit.

<p>		Although not fully decided, another charge may be broken out on the bill, and
may actually rise rates slightly.  That is the cost of paying off the so-called non-utility
generators--private companies whose power the utilities have been legally required to buy,
most often at above-markets rates.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><sup>1</sup>  Reprinted from <b>Berks is Our Business,</b> January 1997, Berks County Chamber of Commerce - page updated 1/8/97 tmm<p>

<a href="http://www.entecheng.com/services.html">Return to Services Page</a><br>
<a href="http://www.entecheng.com/index.html">Return to Home Page</a>	
</body>
</html>


