	<TD COLSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=440>
		<P><STRONG>Aberdeen </STRONG>.. peak electrical demand reduction study being completed in the second quarter of 1996.  Studies included testing electrical power feeders experiencing the greatest peak demand.  Computations for payback criteria include constructions costs and energy savings to be expected for modifications to reduce the demand load at the Proving Grounds.

<P> At <STRONG>Fort Dietrick</STRONG> Entech performed a study of the central boiler plant and steam distribution system and associated auxiliary equipment, funded by the EEAP.  The central plant includes over 400,000 lbs/hr of boiler capacity, and impacted over 100+ buildings totalling1,700,000 SF of space.

<P>At <STRONG>Ft. Meade </STRONG>Entech conducted a feasibility study of the facilities energy management system which covered 83 buildings, totalling 1,900,000 sq ft.   If the recommended modifications are implemented, significant savings will accrue from more precise control of the existing heating, ventilating and air conditioning equipment. 

<P>At <STRONG>Ft. Monmouth</STRONG> Entech is conducting a study of Building 2700, a 700,000 sq ft multi-use facility.  This study will concentrate on Energy Conservation Opportunities for the central steam plant; steam distribution system; condensate return system; chilled water system; fuel supply; and environmental equipment.

<P>At <STRONG>Picatinny Arsenal</STRONG> Entech is analyzing the service water system to determine water and energy conservation opportunites throughout the entire water system.  The system includes 35 miles of water mains ranging in diameter from 2 to 12 inches. and is being supplied by two lakes within the confines of the Arsenal.  Entech is also developing a hydraulic model which will identify areas for improvement within the system.<P> 
		<P><A HREF="#top">Return to the top</A>
	</TD>
