<HEAD>
<TITLE>Industrial Projects</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ff ff ff" link="#7E 00 18" vlink="#7E 00 18">
<table width=591 border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr>
	<td align=left width=390 height=100>
	<p><img src="graphics/entechw.gif" border=0 width=300 height=100                                             vspace=0 hspace=0>
                    </td>

	<td  valign=top align=left width=150 height=100>
		<br><table width=150 height=100 border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>


     <tr align=left>			
         <td width=10%><a href="index.html"><img src="graphics/diamond.gif" border=0></a></td>
          <td width=90%><a href="index.html">Main Menu</a></td>
     </tr>

</table>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

<hr width=85% size=5>

	
<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50>
	</TD> 

	<TD VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=100>
	
	</TD>

	<TD VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=290>
	<H4>Industrial Projects:
	<BR>Plant Expansions
	<BR>HVAC and Electrical Upgrades</H4>
	</TD>

	

<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50>
	</TD> 

	<TD VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=100>
	</TD>

	<TD COLSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=440>
	<HR>
	

<P><B>Allentown Cement; Blandon, Pennsylvania</B>	The stormwater runoff at the plant was investigated in order to identify improvements that had to be made in order to meet DEP requirements.

<P><B>Ashland Chemical; Easton, Pennsylvania</B>	Architectural and engineering services were provided to prepare performance type design/build bid packages for construction of a 12,000 square foot, two-story office and laboratory building for Ashland Chemical's facility in Easton, Pennsylvania.

<P>Services included determination of HVAC loads, preliminary unit selections, schematic design including duct and chase layout, and preparation of a performance specification for use in obtaining competitive bids from design/build HVAC contractors for construction of the facility.

<P>The project also included a schematic design of electrical systems including determination of electrical service requirements, preparation of a single line diagram, and preparation of a performance specification for use in obtaining competitive bids from design/build electrical contractors for construction of the facility.

<P><B>Baker Refractories; York, Pennsylvania</B>	Numerous improvement projects have been performed to the critical process equipment at the brick manufacturer's facility in York.  Projects include: motor control center replacements, engineering and design for the installation of 5 MCC's and the removal of 3 MCC's, and the conversion and vectorizing of plant drawings, 

<P><B>Baldwin Brass; Reading, Pennsylvania</B>	An investigation was performed that analyzed the existing plant ventilation system and offered improvement recommendations.

<P><B>Berks Packing; Reading, Pennsylvania</B>	Structural and environmental services have been performed on a continuing basis for this local manufacturer.  Projects include: engineering related to the industrial wastewater discharge and pre-treatment requirements, Phase 1 property assessment, and the evaluation and design of the smokehouse structural framework.

<P><B>Binney & Smith; Easton, Pennsylvania</B>	Computer engineering services were performed that included: networking, CAD system consulting, and custom programming services.

<P><B>Brown Printing; East Greenville, Pennsylvania</B>	Entech has provided engineering services to accommodate extensive expansion projects over the past ten years.  A sample of completed projects are:  new substation and plant expansion in 1986; a complete electrical system upgrade and plant expansion, 85,000 square feet, in 1989; design of new lighting, fire alarm and paging systems during the period of 1988 thru 1991; installation of a new 60 kVA substation in 1990; electrical system upgrade and plant expansion, 80,000 square feet, in 1992; electrical system renovation and addition to accommodate a new 825 hp press in 1996.

<P><B>Burle Industries; Lancaster, Pennsylvania</B>	Entech provided the consulting engineering services required for the conversion of a substation from 69 kV to 138 kV.

<P><B>Carlisle Syntec; Carlisle, Pennsylvania</B>	An HVAC study was performed to evaluate the negative air pressure occurring in the facility's mixing room.

<P><B>Carpenter Technology; Reading, Pennsylvania</B> Plans and specifications were prepared for the installation of a 15 kV aerial leader, unit substation, building and process electrical systems for a new facility and associate waste handling system.  Additional services included: the design and preparation of drawings for the modifications of an AOD vessel top and supporting heaters; the preparation of drawings for the fabrication of a continuous casting machine mold and guide assemblies; and the preparation of plans and specifications for the replacement of a movable platform drive system.

<P><B>Crescent Brass Corporation; Reading, Pennsylvania</B>	Project included the design and construction of the renovation of a metal cast building into a new 48,000 square foot brass foundry.  Project included design of locker rooms, offices, machine shop, new electrical system and substation and the selection of new foundry equipment.

<P><B>Crompton & Knowles Corporation; Gibraltar, Pennsylvania</B>	Various mechanical, electrical, structural, civil engineering and architectural design projects were performed to accommodate a major $8 million plant expansion.

<P>Services included the preparation of plans and specifications for:
  <UL>
<LI> 1,600 square foot addition for staging of GBM blender materials
<LI> installation of a 1500 hp fire-tube boiler, steam system improvements, water treatment auxiliary equipment
<LI> installation of an in-ground waste tank and vault
<LI> renovation of the existing locker rooms and design of a new locker facility
<LI> replacement of a chemical waste manhole
<LI> parking lot and general site lighting design
<LI> installation of a public alert system
<LI> installation of a spray dryer tower, CIP system, control room, wet scrubber and building
<LI> design of a 16,300 square foot warehouse addition with rack storage
<LI> installation of three new sets of dye mixing tanks
<LI> layout designs for the location of three filter presses
<LI> relocation of the plant's main gas supply and upgrade of system capacity
<LI> relocation of 7,500 gallon alcohol tank and auxiliary equipment
<LI> design of a 2,200 square foot addition for product storage and to house future filer presses
<LI> relocation of three ribbon blenders and installation of three new tumble blenders
<LI> installation of additional 1,000 kVA transformer and overhead line relocation
</UL>


<P><B>Greene-Tweed Company; Lansdale, Pennsylvania</B>	An industrial energy analysis was completed of this 120,000 square foot manufacturing facility that produces rubber seals.  The goal of the analysis was to identify ways of improving energy efficiency and reducing maintenance costs.

<P>In order to install a new air conditioning unit, a structural evaluation of the existing roof system was performed.  Upon completion of the evaluation, Entech recommended various structural modifications to the building. 

<P><B>Harley-Davidson; York, Pennsylvania</B>	<EM>Plant Renovation</EM> - Completed facility study and assisted with the design and construction management of the plant renovation. Projects included the construction of toilet rooms, break areas, and locker rooms for the manufacturing buildings.  New work was constructed in phases to minimize downtime of rest room facilities and to distribute costs as budgeted for plant growth.  Square Footage: 33,000; Cost Estimate:  $3.2 million.

<P>	<EM>Dust Collection Project </EM>- Design and supervision of the construction of a dust collection system for the buffing and polishing operations at the facility.  The $750,000 project included five dust collectors, ductwork, electrical power, and controls.

<P>	<EM>Building No. 1 HVAC Investigation </EM>- Investigated the existing HVAC system for the main office building of the York assembly plant.  Recommendations totalling $2 million were made for upgrading the building with new equipment.  The investigation included an analysis of the expected energy and maintenance costs for each system evaluated.

<P><B>Hershey Chocolate, Luden's Division; Reading, Pennsylvania</B>	Entech was enlisted to improve the ventilation in the facility's flavoring process room.

<P><B>Herr and Sacco; Landisville, Pennsylvania</B>	Engineering services were provided for the equipment layout of a new dust collection system.

<P><B>Hopper Paper Company; Reading, Pennsylvania</B>	Entech provided a comprehensive field survey of the existing electrical distribution system and electrical system drawings.  Design for the installation of a 150 hp variable speed drive system was also provided.

<P><B>Interstate Container; Reading, Pennsylvania</B>	Numerous studies and designs have been performed over the past few years.  A sampling of projects include:

	<UL>
<LI>The existing boiler plant serving the paper plant was investigated.  Based upon the recommendations in the study, Entech designed a new boiler plant with an additional 1500 hp boiler for a total cost of $700,000.
<LI>As part of the new boiler plant project, equipment foundations for the existing roller assembly were designed.
<LI>An electrical system analysis was performed to determine present conditions and to provide recommendations for upgrades.
<LI>A RACT submission, which addressed NOX emissions, was prepared and issued to the Department of Environmental Protection (DEP). 
</UL>

<P><B>J.E. Morgan Knitting Mills, Inc.; Tamaqua, Pennsylvania</B>	On an on-going basis, environmental analyses and reporting have been performed for this knitting manufacturer.  Project examples include: Tier Two and SARA reports have been issued to the Department of Environmental Protection; an air quality system evaluation to determine required emission control and subsequent permitting applications; conducted a stormwater evaluation and investigated replacement of lagoon aerator; performed site evaluation and review of EPA reports to determine effects of site contamination.  

<P><B>Kellogg; Landis Valley, Pennsylvania</B>	Several HVAC upgrades were performed with the intention of improving various operating environments for several of the plant's essential maintenance utility areas.

<P><B>Maier's Bakery; Reading and Easton, Pennsylvania</B>	Since 1991, Entech has assisted the bakery with many environmental studies and assessments, and engineering evaluations. Over the years projects have involved: the evaluation of oven emission in accordance with DEP standards, HVAC analysis and design to increase employee comfort, the performance of VOC calculations and PED submissions for both facilities, prepared a detailed DEP submission which recommended reasonable available control technology (RACT) for the volatile organic compounds (VOCs) emissions for both plants.

<P><B>P.H. Glatfelter; York, Pennsylvania</B>	Various upgrades to the facility's electrical distribution system have been designed over the past six years.  Upgrades of the equipment have all been tied to mill-wide modernization and expansion.  Construction and changeovers of equipment are coordinated to take place during the mill's one week summer shutdown.  Work has included short-circuit studies, sizing a current limiting reactor to tie two busses together, replacement of the mill's 2.4 kV distribution equipment, and replacement of 600 and 480 volt motor control centers.

<P><B>Pennfield Corporation; Lancaster, Pennsylvania</B>	Entech presented options and cost estimates for an anticipated cyclone replacements.  Subsequently, plans and specifications were prepared for the replacement of the pellet dryer cyclones.

<P><B>R.R. Donnelley and Sons; Lancaster, Pennsylvania</B>	An evaluation was performed of the existing central chilled water system at the Greenfield Road facility.

<P><B>SmithKline Beecham; King of Prussia, Pennsylvania</B>	In 1991, Entech performed an HVAC analysis and energy study of the animal research complex. In the same year, an evaluation of the of the existing solar heating system was completed.  Other services included a structural investigation of the cage washer area and other processing areas in the complex, and a structural design for the replacement of an elevated concrete slab between buildings 4 and 5.

<P><B>Tarkett; Allentown, Pennsylvania</B>	Prepared an AutoCAD flow diagram of all systems and instrumentation associated with the facility's boiler room.  Also prepared construction drawings, including specification and instrumentation details for the installation of a new deaerator.

<P><B>United Corrstack; Reading, Pennsylvania</B>	Various structural, mechanical, and architectural designs were performed in order to improve process and maintenance activities at this paper plant.  The adequacy of existing piping supports in the stock prep portion were investigated, with improvements and replacement of faulty systems then designed.

<P><B>Warner Lambert Company; Lititz, Pennsylvania</B>	Renovation Project. Consisted of the renovation of a 6,000 square foot blister packaging area for pharmaceutical products.  Design services included the replacement of existing framed walls with masonry walls including new doorways, vision panels and conveyor openings.

<P>All interior surfaces including the ceiling system were replaced with cleanable finishes.  Existing HVAC and electrical systems were upgraded and/or replaced to meet new space use and equipment load requirements.  Structural work included the installation of above ceiling catwalks to allow access for HVAC equipment service and maintenance.  The design required planning to minimize any shutdowns which would impact an adjacent packaging area.

<P>Dust Collection System Study.  Completed a study of the plant's dust collection system serving the raw material weigh booths.  The study identified recommended modifications and upgrades to keep the dust collection system operational and efficient. 

<P><B>Webcraft Printing; Chalfont, Pennsylvania</B>	Mechanical and electrical engineering services were provided for the design of modifications to the plant computer room addition.

<P><B>W.R. Grace; Reading, Pennsylvania</B>	An investigation was performed to identify alternatives for improving process flow and expanding plant capacity in various areas.

<P><B>Yuasa-Exide; Reading, Pennsylvania</B>An HVAC analysis and study of lead levels in the plating and pasting areas were performed at the local battery facility.  Additional services included conducting a hydraulic analysis which was necessary for the preparation of a wastewater treatment plant proposal.
</p>

</TD>
</TR>
<P>
</TABLE>
