<TITLE>Collegeville-Trappe Joint Water Authority</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ff ff ff" LINK="#FF 00 00 " VLINK="#FF 00 00">
<TABLE WIDTH=591 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR>
	<TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=15>
	</TD>
	<TD WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=15>
	
	</TD>
</TR>	
<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50>
	</TD> 

	<TD VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=100>
	
	</TD>

	<TD VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=290>
	<H4>Collegeville-Trappe Joint Water Authority:
	<BR>Hydraulic Modeling
	<BR>Water System Evaluation</H4>
	</TD>

	<TD  VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=150>
	<BR><TABLE WIDTH=150 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
		<TR ALIGN=left>			
			<TD WIDTH=10%>
			<A HREF="../munic/index.html">
			<IMG SRC="../graphics/diamond.gif" BORDER=0></A>
			</TD>
			<TD WIDTH=90%>
			<A HREF="../munic/index.html">Main Menu</A>
			</TD>
		</TR>
		</TABLE>
	</TD>

<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50>
	</TD> 

	<TD VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=100>
	</TD>

	<TD COLSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=440>
	<HR>
	
<P><STRONG>The Boroughs of Collegeville and Trappe, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania</STRONG>, have experienced significant growth in the past two decades, brought about by the expanding highway systems and development of the industrial park concept, which tends to move high-tech offices from the cities into the countryside.  The communities now have a combined population of about 8,000 persons, plus a significant student population at Ursinus College.

<P>Over time, water lines which were once adequate became undersized, materials of construction changed, new wells were developed changing the hydraulic characteristics of the flows in the pipes, and storage capacity became inadequate.

<P><B>Hydraulic Model:</B> Sensing a need to better manage their water system, the Collegeville-Trappe Joint Public Works Department contracted Entech to prepare a computer model for their water distribution and storage system.  The model will be used to evaluate the performance and capacity of the distribution system, identify deficiencies due to pipe tuberculation, undersized pipes, and dead end lines.  A model can also predict the impact of future development and identify system needs before construction of water line extensions.

	<P>Entech evaluated several computer models available and selected Cybernet Version 2, by Haestaad Methods, which uses AutoCAD in the development of its database. In this manner, the computer model is directly compatible with Entech's drawings which are needed for system improvements.


<p><a href="../munic.html">Return to the Municipal list</a> </p>
</TD>
</TR>
<P>
</TABLE>
