<HEAD>
<TITLE>Honesdale Consolidated Water Company</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ff ff ff" LINK="#FF 00 00 " VLINK="#FF 00 00">
<TABLE WIDTH=591 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR>
	<TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=15>
	</TD>
	<TD WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=15>
	
	</TD>
</TR>	
<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50>
	</TD> 

	<TD VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=100>
	
	</TD>

	<TD VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=290>
	<H4>Honesdale Consolidated Water Company:
	<BR>Feasibility Study
	<BR>Regulatory Permitting</H4>
	</TD>

	<TD  VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=150>
	<BR><TABLE WIDTH=150 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
		<TR ALIGN=left>			
			<TD WIDTH=10%>
			<A HREF="../munic/index.html">
			<IMG SRC="../graphics/diamond.gif" BORDER=0></A>
			</TD>
			<TD WIDTH=90%>
			<A HREF="../munic/index.html">Main Menu</A>
			</TD>
		</TR>
		</TABLE>
	</TD>

<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50>
	</TD> 

	<TD VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=100>
	</TD>

	<TD COLSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=440>
	<HR>
	
	<P>The Honesdale Consolidated Water Company (HCWC) is a private water company that serves the Borough of Honesdale, Wayne County, Pennsylvania.  The Department of Environmental Protection (DEP) issued a Consent Order which required HCWC to filter the surface supply, or develop a groundwater supply and abandon the surface source.  In addition, all finished water storage must be covered.  Major components of this $4.1 million project include:

	<P><B>Feasibility Study:</B> A feasibility study was completed to determine present and future water demands by the year 2010.  With respect to water supply, three supply alternatives were studied: 1) adding filtration to the existing surface supply; 2) changing to an all groundwater source of supply; 3) combining the filtered surface water and groundwater supply

	The study indicated that the most cost-effective solution from both a capital cost and O&M cost would be the development of an all groundwater source of supply and the abandonment of the existing unfiltered surface supply.

	<P><B>Groundwater Testing: </B>Based on the recommendations of the study, HCWC proceeded with the drilling of test wells and pumping tests to determine if a sufficient groundwater supply could be developed to meet the water supply requirements of the system. The results of the drilling and testing program indicated there is a total safe-yield of 1.96 MGD available from two existing and four new wells.

	<P><B>Hydraulic Model:</B> Simulation was performed of the 1.0 MGD system, with 78 miles of 4" to 12" water mains, three pressure zones, six wells and four water tanks/reservoirs ranging in size from 220,000 to 450,000 gallons.

	<P><B>SCADA:</B> The system will be controlled and monitored by a 100 point SCADA system to be located at the water company.  Parameters such as well level, well flow, reservoir level, pump status, and operational alarms will be measured in the field and transmitted via radio to the water company office.  Under normal conditions, the SCADA system will operate well pumps and provide alarm annunciation to ensure a reliable system at all times.  If desired, the SCADA system can be overridden and the system operated manually.  

	<P><B>Financial Assistance:</B> Entech provided HCWC with financial assistance and guidance to apply for both private financing and PENNVEST financing.  An application and supporting documentation was prepared and submitted to PENNVEST as well as documentation for private financing.

	<P><B>Permitting:</B> Regulatory permits were prepared and submitted to: PA DEP, PennDOT, DRBC, and Soil Conservation.

	<P><B>System Improvements: </B> 
		 	
	<LI>development of four production wells and renovation of two existing wells
<LI>well pump stations and treatment facilities
<LI>four water storage tanks totaling 1.2 million gallons ranging from 220,000 gallons to 450,000 gallons
<LI>17,000 feet of 6, 8, and 12 inch distribution and transmission mains
<LI>three pressure reducing stations and two air release stations
<LI>SCADA control system
</UL>
		</P>


<p><a href="../munic.html">Return to the Municipal list</a> </p>
</TD>
</TR>
<P>
</TABLE>
