	<TD VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=290>
		<H4><IMG SRC="graphics/5x5.gif" BORDER=0>Boiler Summer Shutdown Project
		<BR><IMG SRC="graphics/5x5.gif" BORDER=0>at East Stroudsburg</H4>
	</TD>

	<TD  VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=150>
		<BR>
		<TABLE WIDTH=150 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
		<TR ALIGN=left>			
			<TD WIDTH=10%>
				<A HREF="../index.html"><IMG SRC="graphics/diamond.gif" BORDER=0></A>
			</TD>
			<TD WIDTH=90%>
				<A HREF="../index.html">Main Menu</A>
			</TD>
		</TR>
		</TABLE>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD WIDTH=50>
	</TD> 

	<TD VALIGN=top ALIGN=left WIDTH=100>
	</TD>

	<TD COLSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=left WIDTH=440>
		<HR>
		At <A HREF="http://www.esu.edu">East Stroudsburg</A>, the main boiler was running all year round, even in the summer, to supply the steam 
		for absorption chillers.  Entech designed a system for 25 buildings on campus which allowed the University 
		to shut down the central boiler plant during the summer months.  
		<P>The equipment that was replaced included: six absorption chillers with centrifugal and reciprocating 
		chillers, installation of gas and electric water heaters in the same buildings, plus installation of a gas-fired 
		steam generator for the dining hall and science building.  A pool heater, gas line installation and an electric 
		distribution upgrade were also designed.
		<P>The shutdown of the campus main steam system was completed in September 1991.
		<P>Savings associated with this project were:
		<P>Steam savings = 65 million lbs (36%)
		<BR>Cost Savings = $300,000 per year
		<BR>Construction Costs = $750,000
		<BR>Payback period = 2.5 years
		<P>
		<P><B>Boiler #6 Replacement:</B>  Evaluation of the campus utility plant which has a 120,000 lb/hr steam capacity was performed to determine improvement options for the No. 6, 40,000 lb/hr fluidized bed boiler.  Entech recommended replacing the existing fluidized bed boiler with a new dual fuel (gas/oil) 20,000 lb/hr fire-tube boiler.  Additional recommendations include upgrading and replacing the deaerator, platforms, lighting, electrical distribution, fuel oil storage (60,000 gallon) tanks, and other major equipment in order to extend the life of the plant.  Completed the design for the removal of the existing boiler and the installation of a new 20,000 lb/hr fire-tube boiler.  Equipment to be removed includes: 40,000 lb/hr fluidized bed boiler, economizer, ash silo, baghouse, coal and sorbent bunkers, combustion air blower and dust system, I.C. fan, cyclones, ash handling system, coal and ash screw conveyors and associated motor control centers.  Construction costs are $1,100,000, with completion due the end of 1996.

		<P><B>Fuel Oil Tank Replacement:</B>  Designed replacement of three 20,000 gallon underground fuel oil tanks with double-wall tanks and piping.  Landscaping and parking improvements in front of the boiler plant are also included under this project.  Estimated construction cost is approximately $400,000.  Project is scheduled for completion in 1997.

		<P><B>Dansbury Commons HVAC Study: </B> Evaluated existing HVAC systems in campus dining hall.  Improvements and replacement options were reviewed, with recommendations made in a final report.

		<P><B>Kemp Library Lighting Project: </B> Designed a lighting retrofit project to decrease electrical costs in the library.  Approximately 180 fixtures are scheduled for conversion to T-8 lamps and electronic ballasts for a cost of approximately $100,000.  Energy savings are projected to be approximately $30,000.

		<P><B>Energy Management System: </B>Designed new 1,000 point Energy Management System for entire campus.  Services included preparing specifications, review of proposals and recommendations during award of contract.  Contract was awarded August 1991, with construction costs of approximately $750,000.


</TABLE>

<TABLE WIDTH=591 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR>
	<TD COLSPAN=4 WIDTH=590 HEIGHT=20>
	</TD>
</TR>	
