<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1996 Promise to the Earth Awards</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#8e2323" VLINK="#84590c"><CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/weblogo_small.gif" ALT="The National Arbor Day Foundation" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="40"><IMG SRC="./awards.gif" ALT="1996 Arbor Day Awards" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="89"><P><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="./blank.gif" BORDER="0"></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><H2>PROMISE TO THE EARTH AWARDS</H2><P><HR><P><H3>Capital Cities/ABC, Inc., New York, New York</H3><P>The message is direct: PLANT TREES. But the way it is carried to those who need to know the importance of tree planting to the planet is critical.<P>Each year The National Arbor Day Foundation nurtures a portion of its membership contributions by investing them in development of public service educational announcements.  That investment, in partnership with the nation's media, has resulted in the planting of many millions of trees by millions of people since the Public Service Educational Program began in 1972.<P>ABC has supported the Foundation's mission since its very inception.  It has urged countless millions to plant Trees for America; to support Tree City USA in their communities; and to plant Conservation Trees on their farms and support Rain Forest Rescue worldwide.  They have provided a vehicle for Children all across the nation to learn that Trees Are Terrific from Carly Cardinal, the Foundation's colorful spokesbird. During prime time, day time, or fringe time, the  ABC network has faithfully carried the Foundation's message.<P>Thanks to ABC, more people are planting more trees than ever before. Its contribution of air time has had an impact that will last for generations.  The tree planting which it has inspired means more liveable communities, cleaner air and water, more beautiful lands, and more habitat for wildlife.  The value of those millions of trees will grow through the oncoming years.<P>For its suburb support of the Foundation's Public Service Educational Program and the inspiration of countless environmental stewards in every corner of the nation, The National Arbor Day Foundation presents its 1996 Promise to the Earth Award to the American Broadcasting Corporation of New York, New York.<P><HR><P><H3>Paul Winter, Litchfield, Connecticut</H3><P>Paul Winter's musical realm has long embraced the traditions of many of the world's cultures, as well as extraordinary voices from what he refers to as "the greater symphony of the Earth," including wolves, eagles, and several dozen other species.  Since founding his Consort in 1968, he has made music that has transcended categories, reflecting his own diverse experience in jazz, symphonic and world music.  He uses the phrase "Earth Music" to describe his aspiration to celebrate the cultures, creatures and wilderness of the entire Earth.<P>Showcase magazine wrote that, " his music lingers with you because it is inspired by what we are -- a part of nature.  The feeling he expresses is his love for the richness and diversity of the wildlife and cultures that call earth their home."  Wilderness magazine wrote, " Paul Winter inhabits a lone place in the world of music: the place where music meets wilderness.  For  decades he has been exploring sounds of nature and bringing them together with this own world of music.  At the same time he has tried ceaselessly to assist in the struggle to preserve threatened places and endangered species of the earth."<P>To benefit the National Arbor Day Foundation, as part of Greenwich Work Shop's "Art in Concert Series, Paul Winter's work was teamed with that of Bev Doolittle.  The combined work  entitled "Prayer for the Wild Things," featured a full-length audio compact disc and a signed limited-edition print.  Proceeds from the collaboration have planted 100,000 trees in Shoshone National Forest<P>For his long dedication to preservation of what is wild in our world and his kind support, The National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Promise to the Earth Award to Paul Winter of  Litchfield, Connecticut.<P></TD></TR></TABLE><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="../../join/free_trees.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/free_trees_button.gif" ALT="Get 10 Free Trees!" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/homepage_button.gif" ALT="Return to Homepage" BORDER="0" WIDTH="70" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><A HREF="../../join/rainforest.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/rainforest_button.gif" ALT="Join Rain Forest Rescue" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
