<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1996 Joyce Kilmer Awards</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#8e2323" VLINK="#84590c"><CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/weblogo_small.gif" ALT="The National Arbor Day Foundation" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="40"><IMG SRC="./awards.gif" ALT="1996 Arbor Day Awards" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="89"><P><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="./blank.gif" BORDER="0"></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><H2>THE JOYCE KILMER AWARDS</H2><P><HR><P><H3>Marguerite C. Hansen, Rantoul, Illinois</H3><P>She didn't get the nickname "Plantin' Peg" planting a few flowers here and there.  She earned it by covering the state with trees, nearly a third of a million of them, since the late 1950s when she began to re-acquaint the elementary children of Illinois with the celebration of Arbor Day.<P>No wonder a Chicago newspaper once expanded her nickname and began calling her "The 20th Century's Answer to Johnny Appleseed."  It's been said that she never met a tree she didn't like.<P>"During the Depression years," she wrote, "we could get Arbor Day seedlings for a penny, and we took them to Wisconsin with us where we planted them around the little house on our grandparents' farm." She realized later that children were no longer getting those Arbor Day seedlings.<P>After an ice storm devastated the trees of central Illinois, she went to see the superintendent of the local elementary schools, to see if he would let her start an Arbor Day celebration with the children.  He enthusiastically said yes.<P>She found a nursery to supply seedlings, and enlisted support from the local garden club and other civic organizations.<P>On Arbor Day of 1958, Rantoul school children took a nickel to school, and received a seedling and an Arbor Day button.  Most schools had assemblies for the celebration, and many teachers included information about trees and tree planting in their science classes.<P>Later she wrote, "I tried to re-establish Arbor Day with the distribution of seedling trees to school children because they are the future generation, and they needed the training and all that goes with the care and feeding of trees."<P>The Rantoul City Schools Arbor Day program became a state pilot project of the Garden Club of Illinois, and within a few years, school children all over Illinois were receiving seedlings on Arbor Day.<P>She has been named to Who's Who of American Women for her work in conservation, and honored by the Daughters of the American Revolution with a national award for her work.<P>	She says she doesn't have one favorite tree but of all the trees she has planted, she calls the first one her special memory tree.<P>"And now as I look in the backyard," she says, "all that grows there is the result of Arbor Day. When the red bud blooms in the spring and the dogwood comes out, you look back and think, yes, I remember.  There is such a nice melding of memory."<P>For her affection for trees and for the stewards of tomorrow, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Joyce Kilmer Award to Marguerite C. Hansen of Rantoul, Illinois.<P><HR><P><H3>James J. Nighswonger, Manhattan, Kansas</H3><P>He is a recognized leader in urban forestry at the state, regional and national levels.  Involved in the founding of the urban forestry movement in the late 1960's and early 70's, his  program was selected as a national model by the US Forest Service.  He has dedicated his career to educating public and  professionals alike about all aspects of urban forestry, in organizing and leading communities in the development of tree programs, and in improving the urban forest resource.<P>He has served on the National Urban Forest Council and is a technical advisor to the National Tree Trust and to the National Arbor Day Foundation's Tree City USA Bulletin.  He has been a mentor to several states in the development of their urban forestry and urban forestry council programs.<P>He provides leadership to Urban and Community Forestry Programs in 123 cities, 83 of which are Tree City USA's.  He works with 90 additional communities on various projects during the year.  His organized tree programs administer municipal forest resources of 235,534 acres with a tree value of $209 million.  Nearly 50% of the state's population lives in a Tree City USA.<P>Arborist training and certification are his vital interests.  He has provided administration and coordination of annual week-long training courses for the past 20 years.  Those schools have trained 900 arborists and groundskeepers from 10 states and Canada<P>He is a founder of his state's Urban Forestry Council.  That organization helps its members target programs to meet their local community forestry needs.  The concept is unique among Urban Forestry Councils nationally. The Council serves as advisor to the state forester and also conducts its own educational programs.<P>He has dedicated his professional life to serving and teaching people to value, plant and care for trees.  He once wrote, "There can be few careers more enjoyable than that which serves others, especially when that service involves trees and the benefits we enjoy from them.  Without a doubt, trees are a gift from God to make our world a better place and our lives more satisfying.  What a blessing it has been to work with people and with trees."<P>For his proud service in the cause of Community Forestry and in thanks for his loyal friendship, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Joyce Kilmer Award to James J. Nighswonger of Manhattan, Kansas.<P></TD></TR></TABLE><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="../../join/free_trees.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/free_trees_button.gif" ALT="Get 10 Free Trees!" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/homepage_button.gif" ALT="Return to Homepage" BORDER="0" WIDTH="70" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><A HREF="../../join/rainforest.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/rainforest_button.gif" ALT="Join Rain Forest Rescue" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
