<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1996 Lawrence Enersen Award</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#8e2323" VLINK="#84590c"><CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/weblogo_small.gif" ALT="The National Arbor Day Foundation" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="40"><IMG SRC="./awards.gif" ALT="1996 Arbor Day Awards" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="89"><P><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="./blank.gif" BORDER="0"></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><H2>THE LAWRENCE ENERSEN AWARD</H2><P><HR><P><H3>Roger Boddaert, Fallbrook, California</H3><P>He has been called a cross between Paul Bunyan, Johnny Appleseed and Merlin the magician. It's a combination which seems quite possible in light of his accomplishments.<P>In support of his nomination, urban forester Linda Romero wrote, "Fallbrook is a small community in San Diego County.  Situated just north of San Diego and just south of Los Angeles, it is encroached upon from all directions.  He had a vision of maintaining its small town atmosphere in spite of the rampant urbanization that is occurring in southern California. It seems like an unstoppable machine running at the pace of a locomotive,  I didn't it was possible to slow it down or stop it...until I went to Fallbrook.  What I saw there was phenomenal.<P>He took me downtown and talked of plans to plant trees along the storefronts, to remove exotic vegetation from stream banks, to create a community greenbelt, and to preserve open space for community gardens, native forests, and wildlife habitat.  I thought his ideas were far beyond what anyone might hope to accomplish.  By the end of the day I realized that he was not only a man of many dreams, but also a man of action.<P>His accomplishments are amazing.  Land has been acquired and restored to its native condition.  Parks have been developed featuring bands stands and gazebos and planted with trees and flowers. A demonstration planting of fire-safe landscaping has been installed.  Ancient native oak woodlands have been spared the axe and preserved for future generations. There was more, a nature preserve with creeks, ponds, riparian (Ra PAIR ee in) woodlands, large wetlands, nature and botanical trails, an amphitheater, open meadows and grasslands was almost completed, and a Master Treescape Plan had been developed and is under way.  All that I saw that day had been accomplished by volunteers with his leadership.  Who is he? Is he a city employees? A County steward?  Neither, he is simply a resident of Fallbrook who doesn't want to loose the character of his hometown to the urban encroachment and strip development that plagues so much of Souther California. By the end of the day I knew that, in spite of many obstacles, he would accomplish every one of his goals and I also knew that I, too, was committed to help in any way possible."<P>For his worthy aims, and his wonderful accomplishments the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Lawrence Enersen Award to Roger Boddaert of Fallbrook, California.<P></TD></TR></TABLE><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="../../join/free_trees.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/free_trees_button.gif" ALT="Get 10 Free Trees!" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/homepage_button.gif" ALT="Return to Homepage" BORDER="0" WIDTH="70" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><A HREF="../../join/rainforest.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/rainforest_button.gif" ALT="Join Rain Forest Rescue" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
