<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1996 Good Steward Awards</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#8e2323" VLINK="#84590c"><CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/weblogo_small.gif" ALT="The National Arbor Day Foundation" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="40"><IMG SRC="./awards.gif" ALT="1996 Arbor Day Awards" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="89"><P><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="./blank.gif" BORDER="0"></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><H2>THE GOOD STEWARD AWARDS</H2><P><HR><P><H3>Demetra May Grosseto, Damascus, Pennsylvania</H3><P>Frank and May Grosseto purchased Rambling Acres in 1964.  They each enjoyed camping, hunting, and fishing, and longed for a home in the countryside. Little did they know what was in store.<P>While surveying the property, they discovered severe soil erosion, drainage problems, and devastated woodlands.  The previous owners had cut most of the high-grade trees.  The Grosseto's contacted the local conservation district for planning assistance.  A conservation agreement was signed and a management plan prepared.  Fire roads were built as well as field terraces and a pond. Work on the home began as well.<P>Mary Grosseto has carried on stewardship of "Rambling Acres" since her husband's death in 1977.<P>She recently wrote, "We are all tenants of the land and it is everyone's responsibility to preserve the environment.  Becoming a "Tree Farmer" has made me truly aware of the natural resources which we take so much for granted.  It is a great privilege to enjoy wildlife in its natural habitat, and to share "Rambling Acres" with my children, grand-children, relatives and friends.  The farm is home to hunting, fishing, nature trail walks, nesting boxes for blue-birds, screech owls, diversified woodland, open pastures, wildlife cover, and timber production for the future.<P>Now I plan to conduct woodlot tours for prospective landowners, 4-H groups, Scouts and Civic Organizations.  They will be the future stewards of our environment".<P>For her vision of stewardship and love of the land, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Good Steward Award to Demetra Grosseto of Damascus, Pennsylvania.<P><HR><P><H3>Robert and Ilona Parker, Brush, Colorado</H3><P>Robert and Ilona Parker purchased their first tract of land in southeastern Morgan County, Colorado, in 1965, and have been adding acres since.  The farm is a mixture of irrigated cropland, dryland wheat, and pasture. Since 1967, the Parkers have planted more than 20,000 trees and shrubs.  There are 24 different species.<P>	The plantings in 35 separate locations, occupy 50 acres and comprise shelterbelts, field windbreaks, wildlife plantings, and a living snow fence.<P>The tree plantings have provided an opportunity for the Parkers to educate their friends, neighbors, and other people who come and visit the property.  They stress the benefits which trees provide, including enhanced wildlife habitat, reduced soil erosion, increased moisture retention, snow control, increased property value, and improved aesthetics.<P>They have participated in many conservation programs including:  the Forest Stewardship Program, the Stewardship Incentive Program, the Colorado Interagency Living Snowfence Program, The Agricultural Conservation Program, the Colorado Habitat Improvement Program, Pheasants Forever, and The Colorado Parks and Recreation Association.<P>They have encouraged Scouts to plant seedlings to earn Merit Badges.  They also welcome picnics, camping, and have designed a bridal path.  They have also held guided tours of their tree plantings for Boy Scouts, Cub Scouts, Church Groups, Colorado Forest Stewardship Steering Committee and students from local schools.<P>For their hard work and dedication to tree planting, the Parkers have received Landowner Of The Year Awards from the  Colorado Senate' the Colorado State Grange, the Colorado Recreational Vehicle, Sports, Boat, and Travel Show, The United Sportsmen's Council of Colorado, the Morgan County Soil Conservation District, the Colorado Division of Izaak Walton League, and the Colorado Division of Wildlife.<P>For their example of wise stewardship and their dedication to tree planting and care, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Good Steward Award to Robert and Ilona Parker of Brush, Colorado.<P><HR><P><H3>Phil Rutter, Canton, Minnesota</H3><P>His life's work has revolved around two quite different projects, but both concern the vital relationship of trees, forests, and human beings.<P>	In the late 1970's, he found himself involved in research  that could have a major effect on two important problems.   Restoration of the American chestnut and the future of world food production systems.<P>In response to the first problem, he became a founder of the American Chestnut Foundation.  The foundation now has chapters in 7 states.  The national organization has 2,500 members.  A research farm has been established in Virginia.  Hybrids that are 7/8 American Chestnut have been created, and initial tests for blight resistance indicate that some carry the necessary blight resistance.  A great deal remains to be done, but the organization is robust enough to carry the project through.<P> At the same time, he began working on the American chestnut problem, his reading convinced him that growing food on woody plants was more sensible in many ways than current agricultural practices.<P>Environmental problems caused by accepted food production systems, based on annual tillage, are many.  Any food production system which does not require constant tillage could have immediate and far-reaching benefit. To that end he is conducting cutting-edge hybridization research to create highly productive, blight-resistant hazelnuts which offer great potential to meet humankind's protein needs. The extreme droughts of 1988-89 convinced him that hybrid hazelnuts, in particular, were sufficiently advanced to begin encouraging others to plant them experimentally.<P>In the United States, where interest is in hazelnut cultivation is strongest, universities are seeking funding for specific research projects to advance a machinable hybrid hazelnut crop, and a small group of farmers are making hazelnut plantings with intention of production. His hazelnut hybrids, which incorporate a majority of native DNA which makes them highly adaptive to heat, drought, flooding, and extreme cold, are particularly suited to America's Midwest.<P>His research on woody agriculture is now spreading to several different institutions and regions and China is hosting a cooperative project for development of chestnut agriculture, based on his hybrids adapted for 3rd World hand labor systems and needs.<P>For his far-reaching vision of earth stewardship, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Good Steward Award to Philip A. Rutter of Canton, Minnesota.<P><HR><P><H3>Bill Slagle, Bruceton Mills, West Virginia</H3><P>The land and the trees have been good to Bill Slagle at his Walnut Meadow Farm, and he has been good to them.  At his 100-acre farm, which came down from his great, great, great, great grandfather, John Friend Sr., he is a stewardship pioneer.<P>"I believe in taking care of the environment," he says.  "You have to move ahead and use good policy."<P>In addition to teaching at the Preston Education Center, he intensely manages 60 acres of forest land on his farm.  As a member of the Friendsville Rotary Club, he helps plant 10 acres of white pine a year, sometimes on strip-mined lands.  As a member of the American Walnut Council, he represents landowners from 16 states.  He also raises mushrooms and ginseng for the commercial market.<P>	Mostly a self-made, self-educated man, he even built the home he and his family live in today.<P>For Bill Slagle, ideas, maybe even more than the land and the things that grow upon it, are things you put to work.<P>His life is testament that West Virginians with a little land and a lot of personal enterprise can make it.<P>	For his innovation, curiosity and love of the land, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Good Steward Award to William Slagle of Bruceton Mills, West Virginia.<P></TD></TR></TABLE><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="../../join/free_trees.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/free_trees_button.gif" ALT="Get 10 Free Trees!" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/homepage_button.gif" ALT="Return to Homepage" BORDER="0" WIDTH="70" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><A HREF="../../join/rainforest.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/rainforest_button.gif" ALT="Join Rain Forest Rescue" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
