<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1996 Project Awards</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#8e2323" VLINK="#84590c"><CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/weblogo_small.gif" ALT="The National Arbor Day Foundation" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="40"><IMG SRC="./awards.gif" ALT="1996 Arbor Day Awards" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="89"><P><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="./blank.gif" BORDER="0"></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><H2>PROJECT AWARDS</H2><P><HR><P><H3>Bog Garden, Greensboro, North Carolina</H3><P>A graceful hawk suddenly snatches up a mouse and flies to a nearby tree.  There it devours its prey in full view of startled onlookers.<P>	Walkers round a bend to see a rabbit sunning itself beside the path.  A chipmunk sprints over the hillside trail across the feet of delighted hikers.<P>Right in the middle of one of Greensboro's nicest neighborhoods is its most unusual park - the Bog Garden.<P>The bog is a wild and ungroomed place, a nature preserve in the midst of the city.<P>In 1987, as Dr. Joe Christian and his wife, Annie, strolled through the Bicentennial Garden, they followed a beautiful gleaming bass downstream to discover a dream.<P>Trash and weeds choked an old lake, its dam broken, but yellow water iris, ferns and wildflowers - elements of a natural bog - inspired Dr. Christian.  When the property was donated to the city, his dream of restoring the bog became a reality.<P>Today, boardwalks loop over the marsh.  Ducks and Canada geese feed at the edge of the restored four-acre lake, and catfish swim in the creek.  Cardinals, screech owls and woodpeckers live amid the trees, and then there are the plants, lush, and thriving plantings in their abundance.<P>"Everything out here means something," Dr. Christian says.  He and a cadre of volunteers have rescued plants in the path of development and transplanted them to the bog.  Swamp roses came from Lake Brandt, European cranberry from Sedgefield and twisted laurel from Lake Jeanette.<P>The garden bears the names of dedicated volunteers.  The Nell Lewis Trail, named for the columnist and gardener, snakes along a hillside.  At the summit, 50 feet up, is Melvin's Mountain, named for Lionel Melvin, who contributed plants and expertise.<P>Though they may not know his name and won't find it on any sign, folks who walk regularly through the Bog Garden know the sight of Dr. Christian, standing happily up to his ankles in mud.  "I spent my whole life around sterile things, wearing suits and ties," the retired physician says.  "I guess that's why I love it."<P>His reward is in knowing that other people love it, too.<P>For its realization of nature's beauty restored, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Project Award to The Bog Garden of Greensboro, North Carolina.<P><HR><P><H3>Dallas Historic Tree Coalition, Dallas, Texas</H3><P>The Dallas Historic Tree Coalition is a citizen's group which advocates protection and preservation of irreplaceable trees in the urban landscape.  It was formed in response to the threat of destruction of a large grove of historic trees on the campus of Dallas Presbyterian Hospital.  The hospital planned to destroy the trees to make room for a new power plant.<P>Citizens with ties to the hospital, its neighborhood, and the aboricultural community felt strongly that every effort should be made to save the trees.  They met and formed The Dallas Historic Tree Coalition.<P>The Coalition requested a meeting with hospital administrators and retained a hospital architect who formulated alternative plans to accommodate plant construction and save the trees.<P>After tense weeks of private contacts and Coalition-sponsored public awareness campaigns, hospital administrators announced that construction plans had been revised and that most of the grove, especially the older specimens, would be saved. Rather than increase construction costs, as had originally been contended, the hospital announced that the changes would actually reduce project costs by $500,000.  By offering suggestions in a spirit of good faith, the Coalition achieved positive results for everyone involved.<P>	Overwhelming positive response from the community built coalition membership from a core group of 12 in 1994 to more than 500 today and reflects the city's diversity.<P>The Dallas Historic Tree Coalition is thriving and looks forward to teaching the entire community the tangible and intangible benefits of preserving heritage trees.<P>With admiration, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Project Award to The Dallas Historic Tree Coalition of Dallas, Texas.<P><HR><P><H3>South San Antonio High School Science Club, San Antonio, Texas</H3><P>The South San Antonio High School Science Club, in support of the 1991 theme for World Food Day - "Trees for Life", developed a local tree-planting program to help supplement the diets of needy families.<P>Students learned which fruit and nut trees grew best in the area and then raised funds to buy trees and supplies.  Fundraising activities included bake sales, plant sales, Earth Day T-Shirt sales, and school watch sales.<P>Biology, Environmental Science, and World Area Studies classes joined the Science Club in the tree-planting work.  Other school organizations, teachers, and community members were also invited to help.  During after-school and weekend work-sessions,  volunteer work teams were given basic planting instructions, and  assigned specific addresses where trees were to be planted.<P>Through their volunteerism, participating students helped build community pride and were initiated as caring, contributing citizens.  They have, in effect, become "teachers" in their school, their community, and their own families by modeling responsible environmental and social stewardship.<P>For its sense of community and the context of its mission, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Project Award to The South San Antonio High School Science Club of San Antonio, Texas.<P><HR><P><H3>Streetscape Program of the Grand Center Partnership, New York, New York</H3><P>Grand Central Terminal was once the midtown hub of Manhattan.  Glamorous Travelers arrived by train from all parts of the country.  It was a center for gracious hotels like the long-gone Commodore, the Biltmore, where sophisticates met under the clock, and the Roosevelt, where couples danced to Guy Lombardo's music at the fabled Roosevelt Grill.<P>But the old hotels closed, and the area became soaring office towers, inter-spaced with small shops and fast-food joints.<P>Now Grand Central Terminal and the area surrounding it are due for a major face lift and general revitalization.<P>An ambitious renewal plan has been proposed by the Grand Central Partnership, which represents corporate tenants and property owners in the area.  It will include opened vistas, new cafes and restaurants, park-like places to stroll and sit outdoors, lighted building facades, and new plantings of trees and shrubs.<P>It will also feature widened walks, upgraded shops, and better signs.<P>The plan promises to give the Grand Central District "a distinct urban charisma and a sense of place that is welcoming and pleasurable."  Its aim is to restore vigor and diversity to the area through reworking the total street environment.<P>It will reduce urban blight litter, crime, graffiti, and deteriorating public structures.  To help homeless people in and around the station, the partnership plans to open a "drop-in" center that will offer food and drink, clothes distribution, counseling, and remedial services of many kinds.<P>In admiration for its vision, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Project Award to the Grand Central Partnership Renewal Project of New York, New York.<P><HR><P><H3>Trees for the City, Washington, D.C.</H3><P>A project of the L'Enfant Trust, Trees For The City was founded to foster community awareness of, involvement in, and responsibility for the urban landscape through education, training, and citizen-based tree plantings.<P> Once known as the "City of Trees," Washington, DC was losing thousands of trees each year.  Due to budgetary constraints, City Government was unable to keep pace with tree replacement and maintenance.<P>The program brings people and trees together to make Washington a better place to live.  Tree planting not only helps improve the physical appearance and health of the city, but also fosters community spirit and responsibility. It builds pride in  neighborhood and self, and it makes real the ideal that one's own actions can and do make a difference.<P>	Trees For The City, through the Elizabeth Rowe Community Tree Bank, acts as a catalyst for neighborhoods to take responsibility for the urban forest.  Through Citizen Forester Workshops, it has trained more than 75 neighborhood task force leaders how to plant and care for street trees.<P>	It works toward revitalization of the complete living conditions in a run-down, partially abandoned neighborhood in Anacostia with the help of local community leaders, church groups, and community residents.<P>In partnership with the Potomac Electric Power Company, it helped homeowners plant trees strategically around their homes to demonstrate their energy-saving benefits.<P>Trees For The City youth education programs are designed to promote community stewardship in children by providing a greater understanding of the environment and the importance of trees in the city's ecosystem.  The programs include:<P>Learning Through Trees - which is an in-school seed to seedling school beautification project.<P>Latin American Youth Corps - an after-school tree-planting program in partnership with the 15th Street Latin American Youth Center.<P>Trail of Trees - a modern "johnny mapleseed" program. Environmentalist/runner, Tim Womick spreads the tree planting message to thousands of schoolchildren and community groups as he runs through cities, counties and across states to share his message on the importance of trees and the Washington Youth Tree Corps which teaches fundamentals of horticulture and forestry through classroom-based curriculum and hands-on experience, and    the HE Volunteer Service Corps, which provides urban forestry projects in the community for high school student volunteers.<P>TREES FOR THE CITY also fosters Memorial Plantings, designed to provide friends and neighbors an opportunity to celebrate the life of a loved one.  Trees are planted along streets and in parks with a brief ceremony of remembrance.<P>For its growing vision of pride of place, the National Arbor Day Foundation  presents a 1996 Project Award to Trees For The City of Washington, D.C.<P><HR><P><H3>Youth Environmental Entrustment Project, Denver, Colorado</H3><P>The Youth Environmental Entrustment Project is an educational program geared to help at-risk youth.<P>Participants, work projects, and financial support come from many agencies, foundations, and corporations and the project is administered and strongly supported by the Colorado State Forest Service.<P>The project's mission is to provide positive work experiences, job skills, and training in urban and community forestry.  Through hands-on training and work projects, youngsters learn tree care practices, quality work ethics, and community forestry skills in a culturally diverse setting.  Work projects include tree planting, pruning, mulching, insect and disease control, and urban trail improvement.<P>Most participants admit they had given little or no thought to the environment or tree planting before their involvement.  They did not realize a community could have a forest.  They thought it was "just a bunch of trees.  Water, waste, and wildlife issues are used to demonstrate how the environment, as a whole, is important.<P>The project changes participants' views about trees and the environment, about themselves, and about others.<P>By learning wise stewardship of their community forest, many young people are becoming better stewards of their own futures.<P>For its mission of stewardship fostered, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Project Award to The Youth Environmental Entrustment Project  of Denver, Colorado.<P></TD></TR></TABLE><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="../../join/free_trees.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/free_trees_button.gif" ALT="Get 10 Free Trees!" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/homepage_button.gif" ALT="Return to Homepage" BORDER="0" WIDTH="70" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><A HREF="../../join/rainforest.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/rainforest_button.gif" ALT="Join Rain Forest Rescue" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
