<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1996 Education Awards</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#8e2323" VLINK="#84590c"><CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/weblogo_small.gif" ALT="The National Arbor Day Foundation" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="40"><IMG SRC="./awards.gif" ALT="1996 Arbor Day Awards" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="89"><P><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="./blank.gif" BORDER="0"></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><H2>EDUCATION AWARDS</H2><P><HR><P><H3>Georgia Pacific's Tree Wishes, Atlanta, Georgia</H3><P>Tree Wishes is a fast-paced, action-packed fifty minutes of Broadway-style musical fun that teaches kids of all ages the importance of America's forests, the importance of trees themselves, and the importance  of planting and care. Georgia-Pacific's talented touring troop quickly transforms school cafeterias and libraries into a setting for a studio-like game show where everyone is encouraged to participate.  Kids and teachers alike receive an fun-filled activity kit called The Tree Trunk so they can take part in projects both in and out of school.  Step-by-step instructions include how to make bird feeders and how to recycle paper.<P>In addition, Tree Wishes tunefully teaches about wildlife habitat, forest management, forest products, and recycling solid waste.<P>To salute its guaranteed good-time opportunity to learn wise stewardship, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Education Award to the Georgia-Pacific Corporation of Atlanta, Georgia.<P><HR><P><H3>ShadeKeeper, Dallas, Texas</H3><P>The SHADEKEEPER program is building a very important volunteer-based force to help care for the greater Dallas area community forest.  It provides leadership for tree planting, pruning and maintenance projects.<P>SHADEKEEPER training stresses environmental awareness and basic horticultural principles.  Through ten hours of classroom and twelve hours of workshop applications, new SHADEKEEPERS learn tree identification, site suitability, proper planting techniques, after-planting care and pruning.  SHADEKEEPERS commit to forty hours of volunteer work on tree planting and maintenance projects during the following year and also organize volunteer work days at the Dallas Parks Foundation's Elam Road Growing Center.<P>By the time SHADEKEEPERS graduate from the program, they can identify over thirty tree species and provide technical assistance at any tree planting event.  They are also the best force for winning new recruits.<P>Forty-eight SHADEKEEPERS, over the course of a single year,   provided more than $17,000 worth of volunteer value to community tree planting projects and growing center management.  The Dallas Parks Foundation has shared success of the program with various municipalities around Dallas including Mesquite, Lancaster, Grand Prairie and Highland Park.  SHADEKEEPERS have also assisted on over 140 projects in addition to Volunteer Work Days at the growing center, have become involved with the Trinity Blacklands Urban Forestry Council, and have assisted with elementary education programs.<P>In salute to its spirit and its success, the National Arbor Day Foundation awards a 1996 Education Award to the SHADEKEEPER program of the Dallas Parks Foundation of Dallas, Texas.<P><HR><P><H3>Trees and Me from Sea to Sea, Lincoln, Nebraska</H3><P>"Trees and Me from Sea to Sea" is a year-long adventure for  sixth graders.<P>Students begin their journey introspectively.  They explore opportunities for personal growth by developing an understanding of what it means to be capable, competent, and compassionate.  Along the way, they develop problem-solving skills and discover a sense of responsibility for themselves, others, and their environment--the spirit of stewardship.<P>Classroom investigations include study of Nebraska, Mexico, Central America, South America, and Canada.  Each locale is studied from historical and current perspectives as related to cultural, economic, environmental and human resources.  Pen pals from each locale share knowledge and personal viewpoints about their particular part of the world.  Information is shared  by exchange of letters, pictures, videos and gifts. Simultaneously, information is provided to Dawes students by local tree farmers and environmental specialists regarding reforestation efforts in the Western Hemisphere.  Atmospheric benefits, conservation, economic impact, and the ecological advantages of trees and tree planting worldwide are discussed at length.  This information is shared with pen pals and establishes dialogue about trees indigenous to their home.  Those relationships provide the underlying motivation for a "Grand Planting".<P>Students thank their international peers with a native tree.  Fundraisers are held and money is sent to each pen pal site so  that a tree can be planted on Arbor Day during a synchronized, continent-to-continent ceremony.<P>Kids prepare for the "Grand Planting" by keeping journals.   They develop a knowledge of Arbor Day, its history, and its significance. They have a contest to create T-shirt designs.  Invitations to the "planting" go out to everyone who has been a part of the program.  The city arborist helps students choose a location and select which kind of tree to plant.  A script for the ceremony is created from individual journals.  Kids bring a cup of dirt from home to place at the base of the newly-planted tree to symbolize community stewardship. <P>When Arbor Day itself arrives, kids greet their guests at the planting place and the appointed clock-watcher signals when it is nearing the moment for the simultaneous tree planting.  Conjecture abounds as students wonder aloud, "Did our pen pals plant their trees?  Did Mexico plant a Ceiba?  Did Brazil plant a Flamboyant?  Did Canada plant a King Maple?"  The celebration ends with a choral reading written especially for the event, as well as cookies, conversation, and a jubilant walk back to school.<P>As students transcend national boundaries to become part of the world community, they find themselves more alike than different from their peers.  Meaningful and productive learning based on activity, discovery, and human interaction underscores the potential for greater student achievement as well as environmental stewardship.<P>For fostering the insight that stewardship is an individual responsibility with world-wide implications, the National Arbor Day Foundation presents a 1996 Education Award to "Trees and Me from Sea to Sea" of Lincoln, Nebraska.<P></TD></TR></TABLE><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="../../join/free_trees.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/free_trees_button.gif" ALT="Get 10 Free Trees!" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/homepage_button.gif" ALT="Return to Homepage" BORDER="0" WIDTH="70" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><A HREF="../../join/rainforest.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/rainforest_button.gif" ALT="Join Rain Forest Rescue" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
