<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1996 Advertising and Public Relations Award</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#8e2323" VLINK="#84590c"><CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/weblogo_small.gif" ALT="The National Arbor Day Foundation" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="40"><IMG SRC="./awards.gif" ALT="1996 Arbor Day Awards" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="89"><P><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="./blank.gif" BORDER="0"></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><H2>ADVERTISING AND PUBLIC RELATIONS AWARD</H2><P><HR><P><H3>Lewis and Clark Valley Advertising Federation, Lewiston, Idaho</H3><P>In May of 1994 Mike Bowman, Urban Forester of Lewiston, Idaho, presented a program at a luncheon meeting of the Lewis and  Clark Valley Advertising Federation.  He told the urban forestry story and asked for the club's help to tell it to the entire community.<P>What was needed was a multi-faceted educational campaign--and that's just what the folks of Lewiston got.<P>	The history of Lewiston's community forest became a focus.  Poplar trees, which were planted in the 1870's by Lewiston's pioneer merchants to cool the downtown, became known as The Poplar Trees of Lewiston.  Later those trees were cut down but  in the 1980's, progressive merchants, seeking to revitalize the downtown, replanted Main Street.<P>A logo and slogan came next.  They were used in advertising and promotion to tie many activities, and projects together to further the cause of urban forestry.  "Trees for Tomorrow" became the watch words of stewardship.<P>	Action followed the call, booklets were printed, a Tree Trust Federation established, and fundraising activities fostered.  Public Service Announcements were made for television.  The spots tell taxpayers about the importance of the Idaho Income Tax Check-off for Community Forestry.  Ad Club members also wrote public service announcements for radio and sent to 54 stations.  A Pruning Guide was reprinted, and an Arbor Day Poster was produced.  A state tree grove brochure has gone to press as well as a "Rare Trees of Lewiston" map.<P>All in all, the people of Lewiston are a good deal more environmentally aware thanks to the Lewis and Clark Valley Advertising Federation.<P>The National Arbor Day Foundation proudly awards a 1996 Public Relations Program Award to the Lewis and Clark Valley Advertising Federation of Lewiston, Idaho.<P></TD></TR></TABLE><HR WIDTH=469><P><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=469 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="../../join/free_trees.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/free_trees_button.gif" ALT="Get 10 Free Trees!" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/homepage_button.gif" ALT="Return to Homepage" BORDER="0" WIDTH="70" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><A HREF="../../join/rainforest.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/rainforest_button.gif" ALT="Join Rain Forest Rescue" BORDER="0" WIDTH="193" HEIGHT="40"></A></TD></TABLE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
