<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>ARM/CHAMMP/PCMDI Workshop
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="blue_paper.gif"><center>
<IMG SRC="a_c_p_lo.gif" ALIGN=bottom></center>
<CENTER><H2>ARM/CHAMMP/PCMDI Workshop</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<P><BR>
A Workshop on Improving the Representation and Diagnosis of Solar Radiative Heating in Climate Models was held 6-7 May 1996 in Sequim, Washington.  The Workshop was cosponsored by the Atmospheric Radiation Measurement (ARM) Program, the Computer Hardware, Advanced Mathematics, and Model Physics (CHAMMP) Program,  and <A HREF="../PCMDI.html">PCMDI</A> on behalf of the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) Environmental Science Division.  
<P>
<CENTER><H3>Workshop Purpose</H3></CENTER>
<P>
For some 30 models participating in the DOE-sponsored Atmospheric Model Intercomparison Project (<A HREF="../amiphome.html">AMIP</A>), the simulated net
cloud radiative forcing exhibits systematic errors.  In a large subset of the models, these discrepancies occur principally in the shortwave component of cloud forcing.  The sources of these errors include imperfections in  modeling of cloud amount and optical properties,  as well as in the modeling of shortwave radiative transfer in general.
<P>
Because these errors are large enough to have a significant impact on climate simulation, the DOE is sponsoring the ARM Enhanced Shortwave Experiment (ARESE) and called this Workshop in order to:

<UL>
<LI>promote discussion between the modeling, diagnostic, and observational
components of DOE's Global Change Program;
<P>
<LI>present the current state of climate models and discuss their relevant
systematic errors;
<P>
<LI>inform participants of the ARM Program's measurements of shortwave radiation at the surface, including why a variety of
measurements have been and will be made;
<P>
<LI> discuss which measurements can be used to develop
parameterizations for radiative transfer calculations, and
how to use them;
<P>
<LI>discuss early results from ARESE which is collecting unique data for the examination of radiative fluxes in clear and cloudy atmospheres.
 

<CENTER><H3>Workshop Agenda</H3></CENTER>
