<html>
<head><title>Model Resolution Studies</title></head>
<body background="blue_paper.gif">
<h1>Model Resolution Studies</h1>
<hr>
<p>
PCMDI has investigated the multifaceted effects of increasing horizontal resolution (from spectral T21 to T42, T63, and T106) on 15-month climate simulations made with the European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) cycle 33 atmospheric model.  This analysis included studies of the resolution-dependence of the simulation of atmospheric dynamics (Boyle 1992, 1993) and moist processes (Phillips et al. 1993, 1995), of ocean surface heat fluxes (Gleckler and Taylor 1992, 1993), of cloud-radiative forcing (Potter 1995), and of the Asian summer monsoon (Sperber et al. 1993, 1994).  
<p>
A general conclusion of these studies was that, although increasing horizontal resolution may improve the simulation of regional climate (e.g., the Asian monsoon), it does not comprehensively enhance the simulation of large-scale climate.  In fact, model biases can be exacerbated as resolution increases, in the absence of attendant changes in the physical parameterizations.
<p>
PCMDI also has investigated the effects of increasing horizontal resolution (from a grid spacing of 4x4-degrees latitude/longitude to 2x2-, 1x1-, and 0.5x0.5-degrees) on 10-year integrations of the Semtner-Chervin global ocean model (Covey 1992, 1994).  In general, the simulated ocean climate improved with resolution, with diminishing returns evidenced at resolutions finer than 2x2-degrees.  The equator-pole heat transport at even the finest resolutions was substantially below observational estimates, however.
<p>
In addition, PCMDI has examined the effects of <em>temporal</em> resolution (i.e., the frequency of sampling/storing model variables) in a simulation of perpetual-July climate made with the ECMWF cycle 33 model at T42 horizontal resolution (Phillips et al. 1992a,b).  It was found that the time-mean statistics of <em>surface</em> climate are better estimated by sampling at time intervals that are nonintegral divisors of a 24-hour day (e.g., at 7-hour rather than 6-hour intervals) because aliasing of the diurnal cycle is thereby reduced.  However, in following such a sampling strategy, care must be taken to avoid biasing the estimates of the variances of the daily-mean surface climate.
<p>
<br>
<b>References</b>
<p>
Boyle, J.S., 1992:  Sensitivity of dynamical quantities to horizontal resolution in a climate simulation with the ECMWF atmospheric general circulation model (cycle 33).  PCMDI Report No. 6, 38 pp.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP6">Abstract</A>
<p>
Boyle, J. S., 1993: Sensitivity of dynamical quantities to horizontal
resolution for a climate simulation using the ECMWF (cycle 33) model.  Journal
of Climate, 6, 796-815.
<p>
Covey, C., 1992:  Behavior of an ocean general circulation model at four different horizontal resolutions.  PCMDI Report No. 4, 29 pp.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP4">Abstract</A>
<p>
Covey, C., 1994:  Global ocean circulation and equator-pole heat transport as a function of ocean GCM resolution.  PCMDI Report No. 19, 30 pp.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP19">Abstract</A>
<p>
Gleckler, P.J., and K.E. Taylor, 1992:  The effects of horizontal resolution on ocean surface heat fluxes in the ECMWF model.  PCMDI Report No. 3, 28 pp.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP3">Abstract</A>
<p>
Gleckler, P. J., and K. E. Taylor, 1993:  The effect of horizontal resolution
on ocean surface heat fluxes in the ECMWF Model.  <i>Climate Dynamics</i>, <b>9</b>, 17-32.
<p>
Phillips, T.J., L.C. Corsetti, and S.L. Grotch, 1993:  The impact of horizontal resolution on moist processes in the ECMWF model.  PCMDI Report No. 8, 36 pp.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP8">Abstract</A>
<p>
Phillips, T.J., L.C. Corsetti, and S.L. Grotch, 1995:  The impact of horizontal resolution on moist processes in the ECMWF model.  <i>Climate Dynamics</i>, <b>11</b>, 85-102.
<p>
Phillips, T.J., W.L. Gates, and K. Arpe, 1992:  The effects of sampling frequency on the climate statistics of the ECMWF general circulation model.  PCMDI Report No. 5, 25 pp.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP5">Abstract</A>
<p>
Phillips, T. J., W. L. Gates and K. Arpe, 1992:  The effects of sampling
frequency on the climate statistics of the European Centre for Medium-Range
Weather Forecasts model.  <i>Journal of Geophysical Research</i>, <b>97</b>, 20427-20436.
<p>
