<head><title>Climate Change Detection Studies</title></head>
<body background="blue_paper.gif">
<h1>Climate Change Detection Studies</h1>
<hr>
<p>
PCMDI is conducting research on detection of signals associated with putative externally-forced climate changes.  These include investigations of appropriate statistical techniques for signal detection (Santer et al. 1991, 1993b, 1995a), as well as  general reviews of the problem of detecting anthropogenic climate change (Santer 1994, Santer et al. 1993a).  
<P>
Santer et al. (1993b, 1994, 1995a,b) apply signal detection techniques to coupled ocean-atmosphere model simulations of transient forcing by greenhouse gases and by sulfate aerosols.  Santer et al. (1995c) consider observed changes in atmospheric vertical thermal structure and its possible associations with secular changes in concentrations of greenhouse gases, aerosols, and stratospheric ozone.  

<p>
<br>
<b>References</b>

<p>
Santer, B.D., T.M.L. Wigley, M.E. Schlesinger, and P.D. Jones, 1991:  Multivariate methods for the detection of greenhouse-gas-induced climate change.  In <i>Greenhouse-Gas-Induced Climatic Change:  A Critical Appraisal of Simulations and Observations</i>.  M.E. Schlesinger (ed.), Elsevier, Amsterdam, pp. 511-536.

<p>
Santer, B.D., U. Cubasch, U. Mikolajewicz, and G. Hegerl, 1993a:  The use of general circulation models in detecting climate change induced by greenhouse gases.  PCMDI Report No. 10, 30 pp.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP10">Abstract</A>

<p>
Santer, B. D., T. M. L. Wigley and P. D. Jones, 1993b: Correlation methods in
fingerprint detection studies.  <i>Climate Dynamics</i>, <b>8</b>, 265-276.

<p>
Santer, B.D., 1994:  The detection of greenhouse-gas-induced climate change.  DOE Research Summary No. 29, Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center, 4 pp.

<p>
Santer, B. D., W. Brueggemann, U. Cubasch, K. Hasselmann, H. Hoeck, E.
Maier-Reimer and U. Mikolajewicz, 1994:  Signal-to-noise analysis of
time-dependent greenhouse warming experiments. Part 1: Pattern analysis. 
<i>Climate Dynamics</i>, <b>9</b>, 267-285.

<p>
Santer, B.D., U. Mikolajewicz, W. Brueggemann, U. Cubasch, K. Hasselmann, H. Hoeck, E. Maier-Reimer, and T.M.L. Wigley, 1995a:  Ocean variability and its influence on the detectability of greenhouse warming signals.  PCMDI Report No. 14, 73 pp.  Also <i>Journal of Geophysical Research, Oceans</i>, <b>100</b>, 10693-10726.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP14">Abstract</A>

<p>
Santer, B.D., K.E. Taylor, T.M.L. Wigley, J.E. Penner, P.D. Jones, and U. Cubasch, 1995b:  Towards the detection and attribution of an anthropogenic effect on climate.  PCMDI Report No. 21.  Also <i>Climate Dynamics</i>, <B>12</B>, 77-100.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP21">Abstract</A>
<P>
Santer, B.D., K.E. Taylor, T.M.L. Wigley, P.D. Jones, D.J. Karoly, J.F.B. Mitchell, A.H. Oort, J.E. Penner, V. Ramaswamy, M.D. Schwarzkopf, R.J. Stouffer, and S. Tett, 1995c:  A search for human influences on the thermal structure of the atmosphere.  PCMDI Report No. 27. Also published in <I>Nature</I>, <B>382</B>, 39-46.<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP27">Abstract</A>
<p>
 
