<html>
<head><title>Ensemble Integration Studies</title></head>
<body background="blue_paper.gif">
<h1>Ensemble Integration Studies</h1>
<hr>
<p>
PCMDI scientists are studying natural climate variability, as inferred from <a href=../phillips/amipruns.html> ECMWF model realizations</a> of the Atmospheric Model Intercomparison Project (<a href=../amiphome.html>AMIP</a>) experiment with different initial conditions.
<p>
Thus far, these efforts principally include: monsoon predictability studies in cooperation with the Monsoon Numerical Experimentation Group (Sperber and Palmer 1994a,b); an elaboration of ensemble techniques for seasonal prediction (Palmer et al. 1995) in the context of the Tropical Ocean-Global Atmosphere (<a href=" http://www.atmos.washington.edu/togacoare/summaries.html">TOGA</a>) program; and investigations of the chaotic behavior/predictability of land-surface processes (Phillips and Santer 1995a,b,c) motivated by the Project for Intercomparison of Landsurface Parameterization Schemes (<a href="http://cic.mq.edu.au/pilps-rice">PILPS</a>). 
<p>
Ensemble integrations are also being utilized for the testing of the practical significance (as opposed to the purely statistical significance) of differences between <a href="AMIPgroups.html"> AMIP model</a> simulations and observational data (Santer et al. 1995).
<p>
<br>
<b>References</b>
<p>
Palmer, T.N., D. Battisti, C. Brankovic, R. Buizza, Y.-Q. Chen, and K. Sperber, 1995:  Ensemble techniques for seasonal prediction.  Proceedings of the Tropical Ocean-Global Atmosphere (TOGA) Conference, 2-7 April, 1995, Melbourne, Australia.
<p>
Phillips, T.J., and B.D. Santer, 1995a:  Accounting for chaos in land-surface model intercomparisons.  Abstracts of the XX1 General Assembly of the International Union of Geodesy and Geophysics, 2-14 July 1995, Boulder, Colorado.
<p>
Phillips, T.J., and B.D. Santer, 1995b:  Inference of the potential predictability of seasonal land-surface climate from ensemble integrations of the ECMWF model.  Abstracts of the Third International Conference on Modelling of Global Climate Change and Variability, 4-8 September 1995, Hamburg, Germany.<P>
Phillips, T.J., and B.D. Santer, 1995c:  Inference of the potential predictability of seasonal land-surface climate from AMIP ensemble integrations.  Abstracts of the 20th Annual Climate Diagnostics Workshop, 23-27 October 1995, Seattle, WA.
<p>
Santer, B.D., K.E. Taylor, and L.C. Corsetti, 1995:  Statistical evaluation of AMIP model performance.  Proceedings of the First AMIP Scientific Conference (15-19 May 1995), WCRP Report, World Meteorological Organization, Geneva (in press).
<p>
Sperber, K. R., and T. N. Palmer, 1994: Atmospheric Model Intercomparison Project: Monsoon Simulations. In Proceedings of the International Conference on Monsoon Variability and Prediction, held in Trieste, Italy, May 9-13, 1994. Vol. 2, 601-608.
<p>
Sperber, K. R., and T. N. Palmer, 1994: Monsoons: AMIP simulations of the 1987 and 1988 drought and flood regimes. In Proceedings of the Eighteenth Annual Climate Diagnostics Workshop, held in Boulder, CO, November 1-5, 1993, 122-125.
<p>
Sperber, K. R., and T. N. Palmer, 1995:  Atmospheric Model Intercomparison Project:  Variability and extreme events.  Submitted to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change: Scientific Assessment of Climate Change.
<P>
 Sperber, K. R., and T. N. Palmer, 1995:  Interannual tropical rainfall variability in general circulation model simulations associated with the Atmospheric Model Intercomparison Project.  PCMDI Report No. 28 and <i>Journal of Climate</i>  (in press).<A HREF="PCMDIreports.html#RP28">Abstract</A>
<P>
