<HEAD><title> EzGet entry page</title></head>


<BODY>
<body background="blue_paper.gif">

<H1>EzGet: A Software Library to Facilitate Data Retrieval
</H1>
<HR>

<P>
A FORTRAN library called EzGet has been developed at PCMDI to
facilitate retrieval of modeled and observed climate data stored in
popular formats including <a href="../../drach/DRS.html">DRS</a>, <A HREF="http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/packages/netcdf/">netCDF</A>,
<A HREF="http://grads.iges.org/grads">GrADS</A>, and, if a control file is supplied, GRIB.  You can specify how
the data should be structured and whether it should  undergo a grid
transformation before you receive it, even when you know little about
the original structure of the stored data (e.g., its original dimension
order, grid, and domain).

<P>
The EzGet library comprises a set of subroutines that can be linked to
any FORTRAN program.  EzGet reads files through the <a
href="../../drach/cdunif.html">cdunif</a> interface, but use of EzGet does
not require familiarity with cdunif.  The main advantages of using
EzGet instead of the lower level cdunif library include:
<P>
<ul>
<li> Substantial error trapping capabilities and detailed error messages </li>
<P>

<li> Versatile capability of conveniently selecting data from specified
  regions (e.g., oceans, North America, all land areas north of 45
  degrees latitude, etc.)</li>
<P>

<li> Ability to map data to a new grid at the time it is retrieved by EzGet</li>
<P>

<li> Automatic creation of ``weights'' for use in subsequent averaging or
  masking of data</li>
<P>

<li>Increased control in specifying the domain of the data to be retrieved.</li>

</ul>

<P>
Taken together these capabilities will simplify the process of writing
programs for accessing data stored in different formats and structures,
including all the observed data sets and the model output from various
model intercomparison projects (AMIP, PMIP, CMIP, etc.) archived at
PCMDI.

<p>  EzGet is updated and enhanced from time to time. Information on
differences between the most recent and earlier versions of EzGet along with a
description of current limitations of the software is available: see <a
href="ezget_bugs.html">updates, bugs and limitations</a>.

<p> If you wish to be informed of updated versions of EzGet (along with
a description of any bugs discovered), please  <a
href="ezget_form.html">register</a>. (If you register, you may expect
to be sent email, but not often--no more than a few times a year.)

<A NAME = "ftp">

<p>
EzGet serves a different purpose from other software tools developed at
PCMDI. EzGet is meant to be used in conjunction with FORTRAN programs
that need access to data.  For direct viewing and interactive
manipulation of data, a Visualization and Computation System (<a
href="../../williams/vcs/vcstoc.html">VCS</a>) has been developed.  To
transfer data to files, formats, or visualization systems, the Data and
Dimensions Interface (<a
href="../../williams/ddi/ddi.html">DDI</a>)
has been developed.  Neither VCS nor DDI can be called from a FORTRAN
program.

<p>
The EzGet software is currently available for the following
platforms/operating systems: Sun/SunOS 4.1.3, Sun/Solaris 2.4, IBM
RS6000/AIX 3.2, HP/HP-UX 9.0, SGI Irix 5.3.

<p>
You may obtain via ftp the FORTRAN libraries and documentation comprising EzGet:

<P>
<ul>
<li> download documentation (EzGet user's manual and an ascii README file describing how to install the software):</li>
<p>
<ul> 
<li><a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/ezget1.1.3_doc_ps.tar.Z">download postscript</a> (containing the postscript version of the documentation; <i> ~290k </i>)</li>
<P>
<li><a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/ezget1.1.3_doc_pdf.tar.Z">download pdf</a> (containing the pdf version of the documentation; <i> ~???k </i>)</li>
<P>
<li><a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/ezget1.1.3_doc_tex.tar.Z">download postscript</a> (containing the tex [latex] version of the documentation; <i> ~180k </i>)</li>
<P>
</ul>

<li> <a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/ezget_examples.tar.Z">download examples</a>  (containing sample FORTRAN subroutines that rely on EzGet to retrieve data; <i> ~1500k </i>)</li>
<p>

<li> <a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/amip_geog.tar.Z">download geography files</a>  (needed if you want to extract data from individual geographical regions, such as N. America, Africa, North Pacific Ocean, etc. for AMIP models;  <i> ~40k </i>)</li>
<p>

<li> Obtain the EzGet library (containing the EzGet, cdunif and DRS libraries)  appropriate for your platform:</li>
<p>

<ul>
<li> <a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/ezget1.1.3_sunos.tar.Z">download Sun/SunOS 4.1.3 library </a> (<i> ~450k </i>) </li>
<li> <a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/ezget1.1.3_solaris.tar.Z">download Sun/Solaris 2.4 library </a> (<i> ~390k </i>) </li>
<li> <a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/ezget1.1.3_ibm.tar.Z">download IBM RS6000/AIX 3.2 library </a> (<i> ~510k </i>)</li>
<li> <a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/ezget1.1.3_hp.tar.Z">download HP/HP-UX 9.0 library </a> (<i> ~430k </i>)</li>
<li> <a href="ftp://sprite.llnl.gov/pub/ktaylor/ezget/ezget1.1.3_sgi.tar.Z">download SGI Irix 5.3 library </a> (<i> ~550k </i>)</li>
</ul>

</ul>
<p>
If you will be reading data stored in netCDF format, you will need to
obtain the <a
href="ftp://ftp.unidata.ucar.edu/pub/netcdf/">netCDF</a> library.

<p>
Once you have transferred the EzGet files to your computer, you should
uncompress and extract the individual files from the tarred files
(<a
href="ezget_details.html">further information</a> available).

<P>
<HR>
<a href="../../phillips/PCMDIsoftware.html">Return to Software Tools</a> <br>
<a href="../../PCMDI.html">Return to PCMDI home page</a>
<HR>
<P>
Last update December 19, 1996.  For questions or comments on EzGet, contact<BR>
Karl Taylor (<a href="mailto:taylor13@llnl.gov">taylor13@llnl.gov</a>)
