Tennessee. <A HREF="http://nic.fb4.noaa.gov:8000/research/erainfo.txt">http://nic.fb4.noaa.gov:8000/research/erainfo.txt</A></P>

<P><B>Gleckler, P.,</B> (ed.), 1996: AMIP Newsletter No. 7. Available at <A HREF="http://www-pcmdi.llnl.gov/amipnews.html">http://www-pcmdi.llnl.gov/amipnews.html</A>.</P>

<P><B>Hartmann, D. L., </B>1994: Global Physical Climatology, Vol. 56,
International Geophysics Series, Academic Press, 408 pp.</P>

<P><B>Hess, G. D.,</B> R. A. Colman and B. J. McAvaney, 1995: On computing
screen temperatures, humidities and anemometer-height winds in large-scale
models. <I>Aust. Met. Mag</I>., <B>44</B>, 139-145. http://www-pcmdi.llnl.gov/amip2/docs.html, available upon request
from the AMIP Project Office.</P>

<P><B>Holtslag, A., A., </B>and B.A. Boville, 1993: Local versus nonlocal
boundary-layer diffusion in a global climate model. <I>J. Clim</I>., <B>6</B>,
1825-1842.</P>

<P><B>Hoskins, B. J.,</B> M. E. McIntyre and A. W. Roberson, 1985: On the
use and significance of isentropic potential vorticity maps. <I>Quart.
J. R. Met. Soc</I>, <B>111</B>, 877-946.</P>

<P><B>Houghton, J., </B>et al. (eds.), 1995: The Science of Climate Change.
Contribution of Working Group I to the Second Assessment Report of the
Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge,
U.K., 584 pp.</P>

