	<th>Maui 8</th>               
	<th>Lahaina 24</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>Molokai 8</th>          
<th>Lanai 8</th>              
<th>Kauai 12</th>
</tr>		

</table>


<P>
A Voice for Music Learning is hosted by Aaron Mahi, Band Master of the Royal
Hawaiian Band, with guest panelistss.  During the live broadcast, telephone
hook-ups permit any cable subscriber to interact directly with the originating
studio via toll-free 800 lines.  A Voice for Music Learning is a collaborative
project combining the resources of the Hawai`i Association of Music Societies,
the Department of Education Distance Learning Program, and the University of
Hawai`i at Manoa.  The series presents an overview of the fields of musical
education in Hawai`i, and is intended to motivate parents, teachers, and
decision makers to get involved with youth music learning.
<P>
</a>
<IMG SRC ="Images/RedFade.GIF">
<A NAME="MAY">
<IMG SRC ="Images/May.GIF">
<P>
<a name = "SCEP">
<center>
<IMG SRC ="Images/SCEP.GIF"><P>
</center>
<P>
<strong>Kalakoa Jam</strong><br>
Thursday, May 9<br>
Hawai`i Theatre<br>
For ticket information call 956-7642<br>
<P>
<BR>

<strong>The Statewide Cultural Extention Program (SCEP)</strong> proudly presents a selection of
its dazzling artists in Kalakoa Jam, a celebration of some of the very best our
islands have to offer!  

<P>
	SCEP is now in its 24th season of touring.  It provides arts and cultural
programs to every corner of the State of Aloha.  SCEP currently features some of
the Hawai'i's most dynamic and established artists, as well as some talented
up-and-comers.  SCEP's list of 60 plus artists includes the following: designer
Ann Asakura, taiko master Kenny Endo, national treasure and slack key artist
Raymond Kane, slack key virtuosso Ozzie Kotani, composer and performer Bailey
Matsuda, internationally know lecturer and dancer Halifu Osumare, and blues
musician Chris Planas.  <P>
	SCEP's primary purpose is to serve the entire state of Hawai`i, offering the
highest quality educational programs at affordable rates.  SCEP's artists
regularly tour schools, prisons, libraries, community centers, national parks,
churches, senior citizen centers and other community gathering places.
<P>
</a>
</a>
<P>
<FONT SIZE = 2>
<EM>NOTE: The University of Hawai`i at Manoa is an equal opportunity/affirmative
action institution and is committed to a policy of nondiscrimination on the
basis of race, sex, age, religion, color, national origin, ancestry,
disability, marital status, arrest and court record, sexual orientation, and
veteran status.  This policy covers admission and access to, and
participation, treatment and employment in the University's programs,
activities, and services.</EM>
</P>

