<center>
<H2>1996:<br></H2>
<strong>International Artists</strong>
</center>
<P>
Our 1996 season features artists from all corners of the globe.
<IMG SRC ="Images/RedFade.GIF"><br>
<A NAME="JANUARY">
<IMG SRC = "Images/January.GIF">
<P>
<strong>Holo Mai Pele</strong><br>
Wednesday, January 10 & Thursday, January 11; 7:00 p.m.<br>
Neal Blaisdell Concert Hall<br>
Tickets: $30, $40 & $50<br>
On sale now at Blaisdell Ticket office<br>
or call the connection at 545-4000<br>
<P>
Holo Mai Pele is the epic dance drama of the Hawaiian People, recounting the
travels of Pele and her younger sister, Hi`iaka.  The performances mark an O`ahu
premier, performed by the renowned Halau o Kekuhi of Hilo, Hawai`i.  
Co-sponsored by the Edith Kanaka`ole Foundation, Kamehameha Schools Bishop
Estate, Ofice of Hawaiian Affairs and the University of Hawai`i at Manoa College
of Continuing Education and Community Service.  Corporate sponsors are Aloha
Airlines, Outrigger Hotels and Resorts and Ala Moana Center.
<P>
<center>
<IMG SRC ="Images/RedLine.GIF"><br>
</center>
<P>
<strong>An Die Musik</strong><br>
Saturday, January 13; 8:00 p.m.<br>
University of Hawai`i at Manoa Orvis Auditorium<br>
Tickets: $18 (general) and $13 (student)<br>
On sale now at Harry's Music Store and Campus Center Ticket Desk<br>
or call 956-8242<br>
<P>
An Die Musik takes its name and inspiration from Schubert's song in praise of
music.  This ensemble is uniquely made up of oboe, piano and a string trio.  An
Die Musik will perform Jerzy Spieyevski, Aesop Suite for An die Musik;
Beethoven, String Trio in G Major, Op. 9, No. 1; Britten, Phantasy Quartet, Op.
2; and Mozart, Quartet for Piano and Strings in E-flat, K. 493.  Co-sponsored by
the Honolulu Chmaber Music Series.  An Die Musik is touring Hawai`i for the
Hawai`i Association of Music Societies with funding from the State Foundation on
Culture and the Arts.
<P>
<center>
<IMG SRC ="Images/RedLine.GIF"><br>
</center>
<P>
<strong>A Voice for Music Learning: Band and Instrumental Music</strong><br>
Monday, January 22; 7:00 p.m.<br>
Broadcast over these local cable channels:<br>
<P>
<table border=3 cellpadding=8 width="100%">

<tr>

<th>Oahu 24</th>		 <th>Hawai`i Kai 3</th>	    <th>Hilo 2</th>		

</tr>

<tr>

<th>Kona 7</th>		     <th>Maui 8</th>	 			<th>Lahaina 24</th>

</tr>


<tr>

<th>Molokai 8</th>		 <th>Lanai 8</th>				<th>Kauai 12</th>

</tr>

</table>

<P>
A Voice for Music Learning is hosted by Aaron Mahi, Band Master of the Royal
Hawaiian Band.  Guest panelists will include
Thomas Kamisato, band instructor at Pearl City High School; Mark Yosuda,
President of the Pearl City High School Band Boosters; Gerald Suyama, Principal
of Pearl City High School; and Don Tsuha, band instructor at Moanalua
Intermediate School.  
During the live broadcast, telephone hook-ups permit any cable subscriber to
interact directly with the originating studio via toll-free 800 lines.  A Voice
for Music Learning is a collaborative project combining the resources of the
Hawai`i Association of Music Societies, the Department of Education Distance
Learning Program, 
and the University of Hawai`i at Manoa.  The series presents an overview of the
fields of musical education in Hawai`i, and is intended to motivate parents,
teachers, and decision makers to get involved with youth music learning.    
<P>
</a>
<IMG SRC ="Images/RedFadeReverse.GIF"><br>
<A NAME="FEBRUARY">
<IMG SRC ="Images/February.GIF">
<P>
<strong>A Voice for Music Learning: Solo and Ensemble Competition Winners</strong><br>
Monday, February 26; 7:00 p.m.<br>
Broadcast over these local cable channels:<br>
<P>
<table border=3 cellpadding=8 width="100%">
<tr>
<th>Oahu 24</th>			<th>Hawai`i Kai 3</th>		<th>Hilo 2</th>
</tr>

