<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hawai`i English Language Program</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor ="#ffffff">
<img src ="images/helplogo25.GIF"><p>

<STRONG>The Hawai'i English Language Program (HELP)</STRONG> is a
full-time noncredit intensive ESL program designed for
highly motivated individuals who wish to improve their
English skills for academic, business, or professional
needs. For intermediate students, an intensive TOEFL
preparation course is also available. HELP is open to all
applicants 18 years or older who have completed high school
or its equivalent. The program issues I-20s for full-time
international students. 
<H3>Location</H3>
HELP is located on the campus of the University of Hawaii in beautiful Manoa
Valley in Honolulu, the capital of the State of Hawaii.
Manoa Valley is known for its frequent, brilliant rainbows.
The campus is only minutes away from the heart of Honolulu
and the beaches of Waikiki and Ala Moana. 

<H3>Quarterly Terms</H3></CENTER>
There are four 10-week terms each
year, beginning in January, April, July, and October. (See
the insert for specific dates.)  Each full time student will
be in class four hours a day, five days a week for a total
of 20 hours. All classes are conducted in the HELP facility
from 8:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.
<HR>
<CENTER><H2>Faculty and Staff</H2></CENTER>

The faculty and staff are highly qualified professionals with
many years of  teaching experience overseas and in the U.S.

<CENTER><H2>Courses and Levels of Instruction</H2></CENTER>
HELP offers
courses at five levels of instruction:  Basic, Beginning,
Low-Intermediate, High-Intermediate, and Advanced. Courses
are of three types:  core courses in Reading, Writing,
Structure and Communication skills; elective content-based
courses; and the TOEFL preparation courses. The TOEFL
preparation courses will concentrate on reading
comprehension, structural analysis, listening comprehension,
vocabulary development and test-taking strategies for TOEFL.
In addition to the twenty in-class hours per week, there are
approximately one to two hours of related outside
assignments per day. These assignments are intended to help
students extend their English language skills beyond the
regular classroom lessons. 
<CENTER><H2>Placement Testing and Orientation</H2></CENTER>
All new and returning HELP students are
required to take the HELP placement test in order to
establish their level of language proficiency. There is no
minimum score for admission to HELP. Students who score at
the basic level will probably require 6 to 8 quarters to
reach the advanced level of English language proficiency.
After placement testing, students will receive counseling
for course selection and an orientation that will offer
important information about the program and services
available at the University of Hawai'i. 
<CENTER><H2>Student Activities and Holidays</H2></CENTER>
A variety of activities are
planned for HELP students to provide opportunities to get to
know other students and their cultures and to learn more
about Hawaii and its unique way of living. HELP commemorates
all State and National holidays that the University of
Hawai'i observes. 
<CENTER><H2>Important Admissions Information</H2></CENTER>
Admission to HELP does not constitute admission to the
University of Hawaii at Manoa. Therefore, HELP students may
not register for credit courses offered by the University of
Hawaii.
<H3>Housing and Living Expenses</H3>
HELP is not
able to offer on campus student housing. Students are
responsible for their own housing arrangements. A separate
insert provides assistance in finding suitable off-campus
housing. Living expenses vary a great deal, depending on the
level of lifestyle you pursue. In order to estimate your
expenses, you should consider the cost of HELP fees,
textbooks, health insurance (if purchased through HELP),
housing, and living expenses. Please see inserted sheet for
current estimated expenses. 
<H3>Medical Insurance</H3>
All
students are required to have a medical insurance plan.
Students must show proof of a medical plan purchased in
their home country or purchase a medical plan through HELP
upon arrival. <h4>Student Visas</h4> "This school is
authorized under federal law to enroll non-immigrant alien
students." HELP issues I-20 AB forms (certificate of
eligibility) for applicants who are accepted into the
program. Applicants should take the I-20 AB form to the U.S.
Embassy or Consulate in their country to obtain a student
visa (F-1).
<H3>Application</H3>
To apply for admission to HELP 
 <A HREF = "MailTo:sakaue@serv1.arthum.hawaii.edu">
<IMG SRC = "Images/EmailButton.GIF"> Click Here...</A><BR>


<H3>Application Checklist</H3>
If you wish to apply for
admission to the Hawaii English Language Program, please use
the following checklist. <UL> <LI>Completed and signed HELP
Application Form <LI>Application Fee (non-refundable)
payable to the University of Hawai'i. Enclose  a cashier's
check or an international money order <LI>Financial
Statement dated within 6 months of application
<LI>University of Hawai'i Confidential Health Form
(Physician must include a chest X-ray report on this form.
Do not send X-ray film.) <LI>I-20 Requirements Form
<LI>Assumption of Risk and Release Form/Medical Consent
Form, signed by student <LI>Two passport-sized photographs
<LI>Proof of medical insurance (or this can be purchased at
the HELP Office after you arrive in Hawai'i) </UL> 
<HR>
<ADDRESS>
Hawai'i English Language Program<BR>
University of Hawai`i-CCECS<BR>
1395 Lower Campus Road, MC 13-1<BR>
Honolulu, HI 96822<BR>
</ADDRESS>

</BODY>
