<strong>REGISTRATION PROCEDURES FOR HILO COURSES</strong><p>
<font size = 2>
<strong>Teacher In-Service Courses</strong><P>

Teacher in-service (500-level) courses are offered on a mandatory
credit/no-credit basis and are not applicable toward baccalaureate and
graduate degrees. Prerequisite: Teaching experience and baccalaureate
degree.<P>

Walk-in registration at the UHH-CCECS office begins on April 1, 1996.
To avoid a late fee of fifty dollars ($50), you must be registered by
the last working day before the class begins. Please complete all
items on the 
<a href ="HILO_FORM.HTML">registration</a> and residency declaration forms, date, sign
and submit both forms with your payment to:<P>

<pre>
	UHH-CCECS
	200 W. Kawili Street
	Hilo, HI 96720-4091
	Attn: Teacher Registration
</pre>

Mail-in Registration is accepted; however, incomplete registration
forms will not be processed. Approval letters must be attached to
registration form for all funded courses that require an Intent to
Register form. Class sizes are limited so early registration is
recommended. Registration is accepted up to one month prior to the
start of your course without a late fee. Walk-in registration is
accepted at the CCECS office only (Building 397 on the Manono Street
campus).<P>

<strong>Course Cancellations</strong><P>

Courses with insufficient enrollment will be cancelled. Cancellation
decisions based on class enrollment are made two weeks prior to the
first day of class. If you are registering after this deadline please
contact CCECS at (808) 933-3555 to verify that the course will be
held.<P>

<strong>Course Changes and Withdrawals</strong><P>

To add a course or withdraw from a course, complete a Change of
Registration form available from the CCECS office. It is the students
responsibility to process all official forms. There is a $5 change fee
for any changes (addition or withdrawals) made to a students
schedule.<P>

<strong>Tuition, Fees, Refunds</strong><P>

Tuition is refundable but fees, including College Administration Fees
(CAF), are not. All tuition refunds follow the general refund
schedule.
<P>
For additional information contact Corinne Tamashiro at UHH-CCECS,
(808) 933-3555.<P>

Complete the Intent to Register form (one per course and only for EdCI
563U, 564U and 564W). Mail to the office listed in the description.
This is not a registration formyou still need to register with CCECS
after you receive an approval letter.<P>

The UH Hilo College of Continuing Education and Community Service
reserves the right to cancel a course if registration does not justify
its continuance.  Any information contained in this schedule,
including statement of fees, course offerings, schedules, etc. is
subject to change without notice or obligation. The University of
Hawai'i and the UH Hilo College of Continuing Education and Community
Service are not responsible for any change/cancellation charges
assessed by airlines or travel agencies.<P>

All courses are subject to approval by the appropriate academic
department.<P>

<P>
<hr>

<strong>PICD: BILINGUAL/BICULTURAL</strong><P>

<strong>EdCI 563-U, Issues in Multicultural Education: Traditional
Asian-American and Pacific Island Values in American Classrooms (1
credit)</strong><br>
The historical and cultural background of various Asian/Pacific ethnic
groups will be identified in the context of the American school
culture. Inter and intra-ethnic differences between and within
Asian/Pacific American communities will also be shared. Send Intent to
Register form by May 1 to Matilde Narido, P. O. Box 4160, Hilo, HI
96720.<br>
Instructor:	Rolando Santos<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTWhF, 8 am-12 noon, July 1-5, (except July 4) DOE
Annex Conference room 2, $35 (CAF) non-refundable<p>

<strong>EdCI 564-U, Issues in Multicultural Education: Culturally Responsive
Education-Culture in the Classroom (2 credits)</strong><br>
Learn to create an environment that nurtures and respects cultural
differences in the classroom. Certain aspects of culture and
cross-cultural education which is directly related to behaviors in the
classroom will be defined and clarified. Develop appropriate
strategies to help you deal with differences in your classroom. Send
Intent to Register form by April 24 to Matilde Narido, P. O. Box 4160,
Hilo, HI 96720.<br>
Instructor:	Gregory Trifonovitch<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTWThF, 8 am-3 pm, June 24-28, Manono Campus, Bldg
379, MPR room, $35 (CAF) non-refundable<P>

<strong>EdCI 564-W, Issues in Multicultural Education: Cross-Cultural Guidance
and Counseling in the Classroom (2 credits)</strong><br>
This course is designed to help you develop and improve your
counseling and guidance skills in working with culturally different
students in the classroom setting. The focus will be on improving the
learning climate in school and applying counseling and guidance
concepts and techniques to work through the cultural barriers of
teachers and students. Send Intent to Register form by May 8 to
Matilde Narido, P. O. Box 4160, Hilo, HI 96720.<br>
Instructor:	Aiko Oda<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTWThF, 8 am-3 pm, July 8-12, DOE Annex Conference
room, $35 (CAF) non-refundable<p>

<strong>PICD: NATURAL SCIENCE</strong><P>

<strong>EDCI 581-U, Earth, Wind and Water (1 credit)</strong><br>
The use of natural energy resources on the island of Hawaii,
highlighting geothermal, wind and hydroelectricity, is the subject of
this introductory class. Learn how electricity is generated from these
renewable resources, the social and environmental impacts of their
use, and the contributions they can make to Hawaiis energy mix. You
will be provided with instructional tools which can be applied in the
classroom through field visits, hands-on activities, and simple lab
demonstrations. No intent to register form required.<br>
Instructor:	Andrea Beck<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTWThF, 8 am-2 pm June 17-21, Manono Campus, Bldg
379, MPR room, $35 (CAF) non-refundable<P>

<strong>EdCI 583-U, Developmental Approaches in Science, Health and Technology
(DASH) for K-3 or Grades 4-5 (3 credits)</strong><br>
DASH is a sequential K-6 program that integrates the content of
science, health, and technology and articulates well with other
subjects. The program uses a carefully planned sequence of activities
involving both students and teachers in defining concepts, generating
and testing ideas, correcting misconceptions, and ultimately coming to
a consensus on the adequacy of explanations.  Submit the 1996 CRDG
Summer Institutes Pre-Registration form on page 3  to CRDG by May 3,
1996. Upon receipt of this form, you will be sent a UHH registration
form to complete. You are officially registered after submitting the
form to CCECS with your payment of $35 to UHH-CCECS. Do not include
institute fee with UHH registration form.<br>
Instructor:	John Thatcher<br>
*	Sec 1, (Hilo), MTWThF, 8:30 am-3:30 pm, June 17-28 (5 additional
sessions for 3 credits in Fall 1996), Location TBA, $35 (CAF)
non-refundable plus $400 institute fee (for new participants, includes
Summer and Fall 1996) or $250 (for participants who want to repeat an
institute grade level, includes Summer and Fall 1996, certification as
DASH teacher required. Bring your own Teacher Set). Payable to RCUH
upon receipt of confirmation letter.<P>
<strong>
PICD: SOCIAL SCIENCE</strong><p><strong>

EdCI 587-X, Japanese Culture with Emphasis on Kimono (1 credit)</strong><br>
A hands-on learning opportunity to learn Japanese culture with
emphasis on the kimono. You will be participating in activities such
as dressing the yukata, tying the obi (sash), kumihimo, chigiri-e
paper collage with Japanese washi paper, and sashiko stitching.
Limited to 8 participants so early registration is recommended.
Instructor:	Jean Sakihara<br>
*	Sec 51 (Volcano), SSu, 8:30 am-3 pm and M, 8:30 am-12:30 pm, July
13-15, Volcano Art Gallery, $35 (CAF)<P><strong>

PICD: HUMANITIES<P>

EdCI 573-U, Rendering to Abstraction: Drawing from Life (2 credits)</strong><br>
This course has been designed to help teachers draw and paint by
studying and emulating the style and approach used by the famous
American artist, Georgia OKeeffe. Techers will be asked to step into
her shoes as they create their own works that reflect an
understanding of style as well as materials and techniques.<br>
Instructor:	Matthew Miller<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo) MTWThFS, 9 am-1:10 pm, June 24-29, Manono Campus,
$150 (residents)/$260 (non-residents) plus $30 materials fee payable
to instructor at first session<P><strong>

EdCI 574-U, Art Processes and Structures (3 credits)</strong><br>
This course provides a fresh, hands-on opportunity to explore
properties, structures and expressive uses of various materials.
Teachers of any grade level and with varied art experience will
develop a fine arts direction, gain confidence using a range of art
activities and design meaningful art activities.<br>
Instructor:	Diane Pierce<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTWThFM, 8 am-3 pm, July 15-26 and 8-12 noon, July
29, Manono Campus, Bldg 381-16, $225(residents)/$390 (non-residents)
plus $20 materials fee payable to instructor at first session<P><strong> 

PICD: LANGUAGE ARTS<P>

EdCI 575-U, Personal Journals in Schools (1 credit)</strong><br>
A participatory workshop for teachers and counselors who want to
enhance their use of personal journals as classroom and counseling
tools. Learn specific exercises and techniquesincluding numerous
creating writing promptsto free the writer within each student. Also
explored are specific ways to tap students deepest feelings and
stimulate their right brain thinking. These techniques can strengthen
students thinking skills and improve the depth and enjoyment of their
writing.<br>
Instructor:	Tom Peek<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTWThF, 1-4 pm, July 15-19, Manono Campus, Bldg
379, MPR room, $75 (residents)/$130 (non-residents) plus $7.50
materials fee payable to UH Hilo. Textbook required.<P><strong>

EdCI 576-U, Childrens Literature in the Content Areas: Language Arts
and Concept Development (2 credits)</strong><br>
Explore strategies and materials (including current childrens
literature and professional literature) to develop and enhance content
area curriculum.<br>
Instructor:	Janice Wizinowich<br>
*	Sec 21 (Waimea), TWThFMT, 8 am-4 pm, Aug 5-12, Kamuela
Montessori, $150 (residents)/$130 (non-residents) plus $15 materials
fee payable to instructor at first session.<P><strong>

EdCI 576-W, Developmentally Appropriate Practices for All Students (2
credits)</strong><br>
This course will provide preschool to grade 6 teachers with rationale
and strategies for engaging students with appropriate curriculum
through readings, discussions and collaborative and individual
inquiry. Revisit child development theories and adult and child
learning principles.<br>
Instructor:	Connie Wood<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTWThFS, 8 am-2 pm, June 24-29, Manono Campus, Bldg
381-17, $150 (residents)/$260 (non-residents) plus $3 materials fee
EdCI 576-X, Emergent LiteracyMore than ABC and 1-2-3 (2 credits)
This course is designed to provide insight and understanding into
childrens emerging language development especially for preschool to
3rd grade teachers. Examine current instructional and assessment
practices and stages of literacy growth and development.<br>
Instructor:	Connie Wood<p>

*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTWThFS, 8 am-2 pm, July 8-13, Manono Campus, Bldg
381-17, $150 (residents)/$260 (non-residents) plus $3 materials fee
EdCI 576-Y, Developmentally Appropriate Assessment Practices (2
credits)
Gain hands-on practice and experience in observing young childrens
learning and using the information to inform assessment, curriculum,
and instruction. It will also provide an opportunity for teachers to
examine their own beliefs about the nature of teaching, learning, and
assessment in the development of appropriate early childhood
curriculum. Appropriate for preschool to grade 6 teachers.<br>
Instructor:	Connie Wood<P>

*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTWThFS, 8 am-2 pm, July 15-20, Manono Campus, Bldg
381-17, $150 (residents)/$260 (non-residents) plus $3 materials fee
<P><strong>
EdCI 577-U,  Reading to Travel (3 credits)</strong><br>
Develop strategies to use in teaching reading in many cultures as well
as incorporate simple methods that travel well to other parts of the
world. Understand what the basics are in teaching reading and how you
can be culturally sensitive and not impose a western cultural grid on
other cultures.<br>
Instructor:	Katharine Callahan<P>

*	Sec 41 (Kona), TWFMTWThF, 8 am-12 noon, July 2-Aug 9 (except July
4), University of the Nations, $225 (residents)/$390 (non-residents)
plus textbook<p><strong>

PICD: MATHEMATICS<p>

EdCI 580-U, Developing Problem-Solving Processes through the Teaching
of Algebra (3 credits)</strong><br>
This course demonstrates how problem-solving processes can be
developed while teaching Algebra Curriculum materials from the Hawaii
Algebra Learning Project as model. You will have the opportunity to
adapt or create problems to enrich your current algebra curriculum.
Topics include calculators, manipulatives, writing in algebra, and
collaborative group work.<br>
Instructors:	Elaine Denny, Annette Matsumoto<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo) MTWThF, 8 am-12:30 pm, July 22-August 2, Manono
Campus, Bldg 379, MPR room, $225 (residents)/$390 (non-residents) plus
$105 materials fee <p><strong>

PICD: SOCIAL SCIENCE<P>

EdCI 587-U, 21st Century Discipline: Building Responsibility,
Self-Management & Self-Esteem (1 credit)</strong><P>
Practical, positive and pro-active strategies to assist in preventing
many of the most common discipline problems and power struggles
between teacher and student. Learn how to create a cooperative and
on-task classroom environment without using power or manipulation and
how to discourage student aggressiveness, passivity, and addictive
and/or destructive behavior. Textbook required.<br>
Instructor:	Jane Bluestein<br>
*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MTW, 8 am-1 pm, July 29-31, UHH, $75 (residents)/
$130 (non-residents) plus $2 materials fee.<p><strong>

EdCI 587-W, Increasing Student Learning by Implementing Self-Esteem
and Critical Thinking Interventions (1 credit)<br></strong>
An introduction to teaching strategies and classroom restructuring
interventions to help increase students learning. Learn the most
recent conclusions from research on cognitive science, neurophysiology
and brain science; how these findings relate to research on
self-esteem, critical thinking and altruism, and how the research in
all of these areas is integrated and translated into teaching
strategies. Textbook required.<br>
Instructor:	Susan Hales<p>

*	Sec 1 (Hilo), ThFS, 9:30 am-3:00 pm, Aug 1-3, UHH-EKH 122, $75
(residents)/$130 (non-residents) plus $5 materials fee.<p> <strong>

EDUCATIONAL TECHNOLOGY<p>

ETEC 561-U, The Use of Video in the Classroom (1 credit)</strong><br>
This workshop is designed to provide the educator with basic skills in
using and understanding video as an educational tool which may be
interfaced with other media. Provide own video camera and video tape
for use during class. Editing will be done in S-VHS format.<br>
Instructor:	Robert Okuda<P>

*	Sec 1 (Hilo), MWF, 1-4 pm, June 17-28, UHH Media Center, $75
(residents)/ $130 (non-residents) plus $5 materials fee.<P><strong>

