<FONT SIZE = 2>

<center><strong>

CRDG-FUNDED SUMMER INSTITUTES</strong></center><P>

To apply for all FAST, DASH, and HMSS courses, complete the 
<A HREF = "CRDG_FORM.HTML">1996 CRDG
Institutes pre-registration form</A>.  The pre-registration form and
instructions for completing and submitting the form are on page 2. 
Course Sponsor:  Al Evans  Phone:  956-4969<P><strong>

Pre-Registration Procedure for CRDG Summer Institutes</strong><P>

<strong>1.</strong>	Completion of a pre-registration form is required to enroll in
the institutes.<P>

<strong>2.</strong>	Not providing complete information and sending the form to the
incorrect address may mean a delay in processing your
pre-registration.<P>

<strong>3.</strong>	Send form to CRDG Summer Institutes, Al Evans, University of
Hawai'i, CRDG, 1776 University Ave., Honolulu, HI  96822 by
<strong>May 3, 1996</strong>.  Do <strong>NOT</strong> send payment
with the pre-registration form.<P>

<strong>4.</strong>	Upon receipt of your pre-registration form, CRDG will send you a
course registration form in the mail.  If by two weeks before the
start of class you have not received a registration form, call the
CRDG Dissemination Office at 956-4969.<P>

<strong>5.</strong>	When you are officially registered with UH Manoa or UH Hilo, a
course confirmation and supply list will be sent to you.  Your
institute fee is payable to RCUH after receiving your course
confirmation letter.<hr><P><P>

<strong>FOUNDATIONAL APPROACHES IN SCIENCE TEACHING (FAST)</strong><p>

<em>Foundational Approaches in Science Teaching </em>(FAST) is a
multidisciplinary, integrated, inquiry science program designed to
meet the special needs of students in grades 7-10.  FAST uses a
laboratory-and field-centered approach to learning science.  Students
spend approximately 60% to 80% of class time doing investigations. 
The remaining time is devoted to data analysis, small-group and class
discussion, literature research, and report writing.  There are three
one-year courses in the program.  A separate teacher institute is
provided for each FAST course.  In the institute participants carry
out all activities and experience this curriculum as
students.<P><strong>

EdCI 583K SEC. 1101 CRN 3071 PICD:NATURAL SC -- FAST 1, The Local
Environment (3 crs)</strong><br>
FAST 1, The Local Environment is designed for use in grade 6, 7, or 8.
 Topics include properties of matter, changes in state of matter,
energy, plant growth, animal behavior, and the physical environment. 
Students also investigate community water resource management and
local air quality.<br>
July 8-19, 1996<br>
M-F 8:30 am-3:30 pm<br>
O'ahu school site<br>
Instructor:  Staff<br>
Fee:	$35.00 CAF (non-refundable)<br>
Institute Fee:	$275 payable to RCUH upon receipt of confirmation
letter.<P><strong>

EdCI 583M SEC. 1101 CRN 3080 PICD:NATURAL SC -- FAST 2, Matter and
Energy in the biosphere (3 crs)</strong><br>
FAST 2, Matter and Energy in the Biosphere, is designed for students
in grades 7, 8, 9, or 10.   Student investigations establish that
photosynthesis, respiration, and decomposition are carried out by
living organisms; that matter is conserved and recycled; that solar
radiation entering the biosphere exits the biosphere as heat.  From
these investigations emerges the realization that all organisms are
part of a complex interdependent system.<br>
July 22-August 2, 1996<br>
M-F 8:30 am-3:30 pm<br>
O'ahu school site<br>
Instructor:  Staff<br>
Fee:	$35.00 CAF (non-refundable)<br>
Institute Fee:	$275 payable to RCUH upon receipt of confirmation
letter.<P><strong>

EdCI 583N SEC. 1101 CRN 3081 PICD:NATURAL SC -- FAST 3, CHANGE OVER
TIME (3 crs)</strong><br>
FAST 3, Change Over Time, is designed for students in grades 8, 9, or
10.  Foundational concepts in physics, chemistry, geology, astronomy,
and biology are developed through the study of changes in the earth,
the solar system, and the universe over time.  Students consider
problems of resource depletion, overpopulation, and energy
consumption.<br>
August 5-16, 1996<br>
M-F 8:30 am-3:30 pm<br>
O'ahu school site<br>
Instructor:  Staff<br>
Fee:	$35.00 CAF (non-refundable)<br>
Institute Fee:	$275 payable to RCUH upon receipt of confirmation
letter.<p><strong>

DEVELOPMENTAL APPROACHES IN SCIENCE, HEALTH, AND TECHNOLOGY
(DASH)</strong><p>

DASH is a sequential K-6 program that integrates the content of
science, health, and technology and articulates well with other
subjects.  In DASH, children discover the workings of science through
practical, hands-on experiences.  Activities are designed to promote
children's mental and physical development.  The goal of DASH is to
develop in students a basic knowledge of science, health, and
technology concepts and skills that will enable them to understand the
environmental and health concerns arising in our technological
society.<p>

The program uses a carefully planned sequence of activities involving
both students and teachers in defining concepts, generating and
testing ideas, correcting misconceptions, and ultimately coming to a
consensus on the adequacy of explanations.  Students engage in
classroom activities, field studies, data collecting, small group and
class discussion, home projects, and writing, drawing, or otherwise
recording findings.  Each activity results in a student invention or
other products.  In the institute participants carry out all
activities and experience the curriculum as students.<p><strong>

EdCI 583O SEC. 1101 CRN 1123 PICD:NATURAL SC -- DASH FOR GRADES K-1,
GRADES 2-3, GRADE 4; GRADE 5; OR GRADE 6 (3 crs) [10-day
institute]</strong><br>
June 17-28, 1996<br>
M-F 8:30 am-3:30 pm<br>
Pearlridge Elementary School<br>
Instructor:  Staff<br>
Fee:	$35.00 CAF (non-refundable)<br>
Institute Fee:	[$350 for participants who have not previously
enrolled in a DASH institute] [$200 for participants who want to
repeat an institute grade level taken previously.  Certification as
DASH teacher required.  Bring your own Teacher Set.]  Payable to RCUH
upon receipt of confirmation letter.<p><strong>

PICD:NATURAL SC -- DASH FOR GRADES K-3 OR GRADES 4-5 [Summer (3 crs)
and Fall (3 crs), 15-day institute - to receive full certification in
the DASH program completion of both EdCI 583P SEC. 1101 CRN 1125 AND
EdCI 583P SEC. 1201 CRN 4395 is required.]<br>
EdCI 583P SEC. 1101 CRN 1125<br></strong>
June 17-28, 1996<br>
M-F 8:30 am-4:00 pm<br>
Kaua'i school site<br>
Instructor:  Staff<br>
