Fee:	$35.00 CAF (non-refundable)<p><strong>

EdCI 583P SEC. 1211 CRN 4396</strong><br>
Sept. 21; Oct. 5, 26; Nov. 16; Dec. 7, 1996<br>
Sat. 8:30 am-4:00 pm<br>
Maui - Wailuku Elementary School<br>
Instructor:  Staff<br>
Fee:	$35.00 CAF (non-refundable)<p>

Institute Fee for both EdCI 583P SEC. 1111 CRN 1126 & SEC. 1211 CRN
4396:  [$425 for participants who have not previously enrolled in a
DASH institute.] [$275 for participants who want to repeat an
institute grade level taken previously.  Certification as DASH teacher
required.  Bring your own Teacher Set.]  Payable to RCUH upon receipt
of confirmation letter.<p><strong>

HAWAI'I MARINE SCIENCE STUDIES (HMSS)<p></strong>

Hawai'i Marine Science Studies is a multidisciplinary science course
set in a marine context for grades 9-12.  It integrates science,
technology, and environmental studies.  The content is learned through
an inquiry approach and in drawn from biology, physics, chemistry,
geology, and ecology of the oceans.  Students collaborate in
laboratory and field investigations of local and global marine
phenomena.  Two textbooks with accompanying workbooks, masters, and
teacher guides have been developed.  In the institute teachers carry
out activities from both textbooks and experience this curriculum as
students.<p><strong>

EdCI 583J SEC. 1101 CRN 1124 PICD:NATURAL SC - THE LIVING OCEAN: 
BIOLOGICAL SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY OF THE MARINE ENVIRONMENT AND THE
FLUID EARTH:  PHYSICAL SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY OF THE MARINE
ENVIRONMENT (3 crs)<br></strong>
<em>The Living Ocean </em>is a semester course exploring the biology
and ecology of the oceans and other aquatic environments and their
application in aqua culture and related technologies.  Students
investigate topics such as plankton and satellite remote sensing,
bioenergetics, and topics in global environmental changes.  The Fluid
Earth is a semester course exploring the physics, chemistry, and
geology of the oceans and their applications in ocean engineering and
related technologies.  Students investigate issues including acid
rain, the green-house effect, and exclusive economic zones, as well as
technologies such as seabed mining, satellite oceanography, and
ocean-mapping.<br>
June 17-28, 1996<br>
M-F 8:00 am-3:00 pm<br>
O'ahu school site<br>
Instructor:  Staff<br>
Fee:	$35.00 CAF (non-refundable)<br>
Institute Fee:	$350 payable to RCUH upon receipt of confirmation
letter.<p><strong>


CHINA INSTITUTE<p>

EdCI 588K SEC. 1101 CRN 1128 PICD:SOCIAL SC -- CHINA UNDERSTANDING ITS
PAST:  MATERIALS FOR HIGH SCHOOL TEACHERS (2 crs)<br></strong>
<em>China:  Understanding Its Past</em> is a hands-on, inquiry-based
social studies program for high school students.  Case studies,
primary document, literary selections, music of the period,
simulations, groupwork, and a variety of student activities develop
and reinforce student understanding.  The program places the
geography, and reinforce student understanding.  The program places
the geography, government, culture, and economy of the region in
historical context.<br>
June 17-21, 1996<br>
M-F 8:30 am-3:30 pm<br>
Tokai University, Honolulu<br>
Instructors:  Eileen Tamura, Linda Menton, Noren Lush<br>
Fee:	$35.00 CAF (non-refundable)<br>
Institute Fee:	$100 payable to RCUH upon receipt of confirmation
letter.<p><strong>

SCIENCE ENRICHMENT FIELD TRIP INSTITUTE <p>

EdCI 581I SEC. 1101 CRN 3093 PICD:NATURAL SC -- SCIENCE ENRICHMENT
FIELD TRIP INSTITUTE FOR ELEMENTARY TEACHERS (1 cr)<br></strong>
The <em>Science Enrichment Field Trip Institute </em>prepares teachers
to plan, execute and integrate science field trips with science
classroom and computer laboratory instruction.  Students will observe
and participate in classroom, field and computer activities with a
summer science class in The University of Hawai'i Laboratory School
Summer Programs.  Students will recieve instruction in site
observation, habitat preparation, field sampling, instrumentation,
transportation, clothing, safety and class management.  Presentations
by tne students of their observations and discussion on adapting these
experiences to their teaching situations will complete the institute. 
For more information call 956-4919.<br>
July 6-12, 1996<br>
Sat., July 6 8:30 am-3:30 pm<br>
M-R, July 8-11 7:30 am-12:00 pm<br>
F, July 12 7:30 am-3:00 pm<br>
University Laboratory School & filed sites, O'ahu<br>
Instructor:  Thomas W. Speitel<br>
Fee:	$88.00 Residents<br>
	$269.00 Non-Residents<br>
Institute Fee:  $40.00 payable to RCUH upon receipt of confirmation
letter.<p><strong>





