<HTML>
<TITLE>William Puette</TITLE>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Imgbgs/crest.JPG" TEXT=#0000FF LINK= #ff0000
VLINK= #ff00ff ALINK=#ff0000>
<CENTER>
<FONT color="#FF0000"><IMG src = "imbars/MYNAME3.GIF" BORDER=3><FONT SIZE=3 color="0000ff"><P>
<P>
<table border=8>
<tr>
  <td><IMG src = "imbars/Bill3.jpg" WIDTH="245" HEIGHT="328"></td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>

</center>
<P>
<p><center><img src = "Images/Swash1.GIF"></center><p>

<center><H3>Honolulu, Hawai'i<BR>
<FONT SIZE=3><A HREF = "MAILTO: puette@hawaii.edu"><IMG src = "icons/email02.gif"></A><p></H3>
<A HREF ="WJPres.html"><img src = "icons/resume.gif"></A>
</center>



<p>The name"Puette" is derived from the old Saxon word for magpie and the typically French diminutive "ette" was added by the Normans at  the time of the conquest of 1066.<P>

The shield design appearing as background to this page is a crest that dates back to the crusades in which an ancient ancestor presumably distinguished himself in battle/pillage.  The three yellow circles represent "bezants" or coins from the crusades. <p>

The name "Puette" is, therefore, a British surname and harkens back to old Staffordshire.  Details of the family's movement to America have not been tied down yet, but there is evidence of migration from old Virginia to Lenoir, North Carolina around 1790.<P>
<hr>
<P>Originally from Cleveland, Ohio, I am a twenty-seven year resident of the State of Hawai'i.  I was recruited from the mainland in 1969 to teach English at a public school on Maui.  I became a member of the Maui Teachers' Association and, soon thereafter, was a conventioneer at the founding of the Hawaii State Teachers' Association.  A few years later, I found himself serving as a school leader and picket captain during Hawai'i's first
state-wide teachers' strike.
<P>
I have an M.A. from Edinboro University of Pennsylvania and a Ph.D. from the University of Hawai'i at Manoa.
<P>
I taught as a Lecturer and Humanities Instructor variously at a private College in Kyoto, Japan, and the University of Hawai'i's Honolulu and Leeward Community Colleges. For three years I served as a full-time field organizer and contract representative for the Central O'ahu Chapter of the Hawai'i State Teachers Association.  At present, I am the Director of the Center for Labor Education & Research at the University of Hawai'i where, for the past fourteen years, I have been teaching classes for the local labor movement and working to establish a Labor Studies degree program.  At CLEAR I teach a Union Leadership Skills Seminar, a Labor Law course and popular programs on Grievance Handling, Stress Management, and Labor History.
<P>
I am also the publishing editor for a Hawaiian labor history series, author of the booklets, <A HREF = "book5.html">Labor Dispute Picketing: Organizing a Legal Picket in Hawai'i</A> and <FONT color="#FF0000">Pa'a Hui Unions: the Hawai'i State AFL-CIO, 1966-1991</FONT>; and of the books: <A HREF = "book-genji.html">A Readers Guide to the Tale of Genji</A> (Tuttle, 1983), <A HREF = "book1.html">The Hilo Massacre</A>(UH, 1988), and <A HREF ="book-TJE.html">Through Jaundiced Eyes: How the Media View Organized Labor</A> (ILR Press, 1992).
<P>
In addition, I was appointed by the governor to the Hawai'i Committee for the Humanities; I'm a member of the executive board of the local chapter of the Industrial Relations Research Association; a college representative of the UH Professsional Assembly; a founding member of the Hawai'i Association of Labor Editors; and a long time volunteer counselor with the Aloha Council of the Boy Scouts of America, having taught dozens of American Labor merit badge clinics for hundreds of boys throughout the state.  In 1992, working
with the Hawai'i State AFL- CIO and the Labor's Community Services Liaison Program of Hawai'i, I helped develop a similar program for the Hawai'i Council of the Girl Scouts, whivh was the first such program for Girl Scouts in the United States.
<P>
In 1993, I was named winner of Penn State's Lowell-Mellett Award for outstanding media criticism, and in 1994 was given the George Meany Award for Outstanding Service to Youth by the Hawai'i State AFL-CIO and the Aloha Council of the Boy Scouts of America.
<p>
That's the professional me.  For a look at some of my personal interests,  follow the arrow "Forth."
<hr>
<p><p><center><A HREF ="me2.html">... and <img src = "icons/Arrow-r.GIF"> FORTH</A></center><p>

<p>
<hr>
<FONT SIZE=2>[rev. 1-5-97]
<p>
