<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>About CCECS ...</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">
<IMG SRC = "Images/CCECSHeader.GIF">
<BR>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE = 3>
<STRONG>The College of Continuing Education and Community
Service</STRONG> has a commitment to provide educational services 
to the people of Hawaii. Its divisions include the <I>Center for Labor Education 
and Research (CLEAR), Community Service (CS), the Conference Center (CC), the Hawaii English Language Program, Extended Programs (EP), Professional and Special Programs (PSP),</I> and the <I>Small Business Management Program (SBMP)</I>.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE = 3>
<CENTER>
<img src ="images/CLEAR2.GIF">
</CENTER>
<P>
The <a href="CLEAR/AboutCLEAR.html">Center for Labor Education 
and Research</a> was established in 1976 by State Law, HRS 304-34 
(Act 202). In recognition of the substantial contributions of organized 
labor to the improvement of the well-being of the States citizenry, the
University is legally mandated to address the specialized 
education and training needs of workers and trade unionists.
In addition, the Center is committed to educating and 
informing the public at large of the valuable role of 
organized labor.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<img src ="images/CS2.GIF">
</CENTER>
<P>
The <a href="CS/Home.html">CCECS Community Service Division</a> 
arranges cultural activities in music, dance, theater, special attractions, 
and the visual arts, including off-campus sites throughout the island of
O`ahu and all neighbor islands. 
<P>
In 1995-96, the Division is coordinating tours by twenty ensembles 
from outside the state, including the Ballet Jazz du Montreal, Tandy Beal &
Company, the Ballet Folclorico do Brazil, and the Peking Acrobats. 
The Division also tours Hawai`i-based artists widely throughout the state.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<img src ="images/cc2.GIF">
</CENTER>
<P>
Guided by CCECS' mission of providing lifelong learning opportunities for adults through research, teaching and service, the <A HREF="CC/Home.HTML">Conference Center</A> emphasizes developing conferences and programs that integrate the components of the mission into public life. The Center serves as a catalyst for creative programming by first identifying issues then bringing people together. By venturing across disciplines and professional boundaries, the Conference Center transforms ideas into innovative conferences and meetings by providing expertise in three general categories: Planning, Support, and Administrative Services.
<P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<img src ="images/ep2.GIF">
</CENTER>
<P>
The <A HREF="Extended/Home.html">Extended, or Credit Program</a> 
establishes and administers credit course programs designed to serve 
individuals who are unable to attend the regular University day program. 
The program provides these individuals an opportunity to earn a college
degree, upgrade their professional occupational skills or
achieve personal enrichment. Courses are offered on the
Manoa campus, at various public and private schools as well
as other locations.
<P>
<P>
<!--
<CENTER>
<img src ="images/HELP2.GIF">
</CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="HELP/Home.HTML">The Hawai'i English Language 
Program (HELP)</A> is a full-time noncredit intensive ESL program
designed for highly motivated individuals who wish to
improve their English skills for academic, business, or
professional needs. For intermediate students, an intensive
TOEFL preparation course is also available. HELP is open to
all applicants 18 years or older who have completed high
school or its equivalent. The program issues I-20s for full-time 
international students. There are four 10-week terms each year, 
beginning in January, April, July, and October. Each full-time student 
will be in class four hours a day, five days a week for a total of 
20 hours. All classes are conducted in the HELP facility from 
8:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. The faculty and staff are highly qualified
professionals with many years of teaching experience overseas and 
in the U.S.
<P>
<P>
-->
<CENTER>
<img src ="images/PSP2.GIF">
</CENTER>
<P>
The <A HREF="PSP/Home.HTML">Professional and Special Programs</A> 
division establishes and administers noncredit course programs 
designed to provide various individuals and groups with an 
opportunity to maintain professional skills, advance or change in 
career, or to pursue personal development and enrichment. Although
noncredit classes do not provide academic credit, such
classes are offered to meet ongoing professional and
personal needs and are a significant part of university
outreach efforts across the nation. Unlike 12- to 16-week
credit classes which are the building blocks of a
traditional academic curriculum, noncredit courses are
usually relatively short and complete in themselves. Classes
are presented in a variety of formats such as workshops,
short courses, studios and lectures.
<P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<img src ="images/sbmp2.GIF">
</CENTER>
<P>
The <A HREF="SBMP/Home.HTML">Small Business Management Program</A> 
offers certificate programs in Entrepreneurship, Management, 
and Specials. The entrepreneurship program
provides courses for those who wish to start and operate
their own business. It addresses the small business problems
of organization, financial management, production, and
marketing using real-life business situations within the
classroom.
<P>
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="Default.HTML">Return to CCECS Home Page</A>

</Body>
