<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Labor Dispute Picketing</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Imgbgs/CLEARBG.JPG">

<Center>
<img src = "Images/thumb.gif"><P>
<img src = "Images/hPublications.GIF"><P>
</center>
<FONT SIZE=2>Ph: (808) 956-7145; FAX: (808) 956-2023;<br>
E-Mail: <A HREF = "MAILTO: puette@hawaii.edu">puette@hawaii.edu</A>;<br>
<p><img src = "Images/Swash4.GIF"><p>
<P><CENTER><FONT size=5 color ="#9F5F9F">Labor Dispute Picketing<br>Organizing a Legal Picket in Hawai'i, 3rd ed.</FONT><FONT size=3><P>
by William J. Puette<P>
<strong>50&#162</strong>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="Images/cover5.GIF" WIDTH="190" HEIGHT=
"245"> </CENTER><p>

This is the most recent edition of CLEAR's popular little handbook on Labor Dispute Picketing.  This 1994 update contains short, easy-to-follow descriptions of the basic rules governing picket line conduct and organization.  The Guide includes information on the different types of picketing: ULP, informational picketing, area standards picketing, common-situs, secondary boycott, etc.. <p>

There is also a useful section of practical guidelines for picket captains and a 17-page summary of the laws of Hawai'i relating to ingress and egress, obstruction, etc., based in large part on the material used to brief police officers assigned picket line duty.<p>

Unlike the other CLEAR publications, this handbook is designed to fit in a pocket or handbag (5 and a half by 4 inches) as a ready reference. [54 pages].<P>
.<P>


